the united states claimed nicaragua began planning a military incursion into honduras when congress cut off contra aid, and managua accused washington of creating an ``artificial crisis'' to justify direct military action against it
this invasion was no accident,'' u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun told the security council friday. ``it was not hot pursuit .. . it was and is a planned offensive conducted ... in clear violation of international law and conventions.''
the urgent session was sought by nicaragua to protest the united states' sending 3,200 troops to honduras on exercises managua called a threat to its leftist sandinista government and to international peace and security
the united states claims it sent in soldiers at honduras' request after nicaraguan troops crossed the border in an effort to wipe out the u.s.-supported contras
okun said the presence of u.s. forces was a measured response to the alleged incursion that ``does not constitute either a threat or the use of force against nicaragua.''
ambassador jorge ramon hernandez of honduras said nicaragua is trying to create confusion and chaos in central america
we denounce this invasion as the expansionistic, aggressive attitude of nicaragua, not only to my country but to others,'' he said
okun added: ``the sandinistas have been preparing for this operation since the beginning of march, moving equipment, vehicles, supplies, fuel and troops closer to the border and establishing a forward staging area within 45 miles of the honduran border
they apparently began planning this attack in reaction to a vote in the u.s. congress that ended aid to the nicaraguan resistance.'' on feb. 3, president reagan narrowly lost a house vote on continuing contra aid. a democratic alternative was defeated, 216 to 208, a month later
the sandinista government has said the offensive began march 8 and had succeeded in driving hundreds of contra guerrillas back into honduras, where they have base camps
nicaraguan envoy rita delia casco denied during friday's session that sandinista troops were in honduras and said the united states is to blame for any conflict between the two central american neighbors
she accused the white house of being out to justify direct military action against nicaragua: ``this is a crisis artificially created by the u.s. administration ... the military actions we have taken are limited to the defense of our territory and sovereignty.''
in managua, a sandinista military official indicated privately that nicaraguan troops had cross the border. and hernandez said sandinista troops were still in honduras on friday
ms. casco claimed the united states was preparing ``to step up its military presence on central american soil.''
she said a u.s. congressional delegation would be welcome to visit nicaragua on a fact-finding mission, including border areas
if truly the government of the united states wishes to support the peace process in central america,'' the nicaraguan envoy said, ``it is not by sending american young men to risk their lives ... it should put an end to its policy of state terrorism.''
okun said the united states supports the regional peace plan authored by president oscar arias of costa rica, but claimed nicaragua has failed to abide by it by discussing substantive issues with the opposition
he said it does not want negotiations with the contras _ but their surrender: ``the events which have unfolded in the past few days have confirmed our worst fears about nicaragua's true intent.''
ms. casco said it is the united states that wants to block a cease-fire and sabotage the peace plan, which calls for an end to outside aid to insurgents
she accused president reagan of cynically employing a ``pack of lies'' and generating hysteria to help gain congressional approval for further aid to the contras
the 15-member security council adjourned without a resolution or vote
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar is considering a nicaraguan request to send a joint fact-finding mission with the organization of american states to the nicaraguan-honduran border
the peace plan, signed aug. 7, calls for cease-fires, democratic reforms and negotiations to end civil wars in el salvador, guatemala and nicaragua
an ape billed as the world's largest lowland gorilla in captivity got its first look at the outside world since it was captured as an infant 20 years ago
he's never really had the wind in his face, the rain in his face, the sun on him in 20 years,'' said pat quinn, director of the zoo
colossus, estimated to weigh at least 550 pounds, moved cautiously and clutched a security blanket in his powerful hands friday as he ventured from his cage into an outdoor enclosure
the 6-foot, 2-inch ape never strayed more than a few feet from the cage door for the first hour, but soon was roaming throughout the 6,000-square-foot pen
the lumbering gorilla pounded his fist against the 1\-inch-thick glass enclosing the observation area, causing spectators to recoil. one woman was so stunned she dropped her camera
until he was moved here sunday, colossus had spent nearly all his life in a 240-square-foot indoor cage at benson's animal park in hudson, n.h. the zoo bought him for $37,800 at auction when benson's closed last october, but he remained there until the new facilities could be built
colossus was brought sunday to the zoo but kept inside until friday so he could become accustomed to his new suite of two adjoining cages before being reintroduced to the outdoors
when the door to his cage was opened, colossus clutched his blanket for security and peeked out several times before extending his right hand through the opening
he did this several times, putting one arm out and then both, before he finally climbed out. then he withdrew several more times into the cage
come on, son, come see me,'' quinn shouted
at one point, the ape bent over to smell the grass just outside his door before bounding back inside
he doesn't know what it is,'' quinn said. ``he's figuring out what this new texture is under his feet.''
in new hampshire, the gorilla never felt anything underfoot except concrete and steel, said quinn
the zoo plans to breed colossus. but first the giant ape will have to learn how to behave like a gorilla _ he has not seen another member of his species since his capture, quinn said
quinn said he wants to obtain another bachelor male or a non-productive female as a mentor for colossus before selecting a mate
more avalanches crashed down on mountain villages in the northern kashmir state, killing at least 145 people and injuring more than 100, united news of india reported today
the casualties in friday's snow slides brought to at least 217 the death toll from avalanches in the mountain state since snow storms hit march 10
uni said the friday's avalanches hit three villages in in kargil district, about 90 miles northeast of the state's capital of srinagar
the agency said senior government officials made aerial survey of the affected areas and relief operations were under way. it said roads to many of the affected villages were blocked by snow
francis bacon, whose paintings of hideously distorted human figures have made him the highest-paid living british artist, will show his works in the soviet union, the british council said
the council, which promotes britain abroad, said friday that 43 bacon canvases will be displayed in a two-month exhibition opening in moscow in september
the show, requested by the union of soviet artists, will be the first in moscow by a contemporary british artist
bacon himself was delighted to hear that soviet artists admire him, and he will go to moscow with his paintings,'' said council spokesman john nickson
a record $1.7 million for a work of the 78-year-old artist was offered last may. the offer was for his 1953 picture, ``study for portrait 1-8,'' one of eight paintings of pope innocent x. rico</head>
kansas and puerto rico claimed political center stage for the weekend as democratic presidential candidates sought to gain ground on one another and george bush expected to bolster his already commanding lead by adding a few offshore delegates
on the democratic side, 39 delegates were at stake in kansas caucuses today and another 51 were up for grabs in sunday's primary in puerto rico
among republicans, the vice president was expected to dominate the winner-take-all vote in puerto rico and pick up all 14 gop delegates. kansas republicans already have made their wishes known, favoring home-state contender bob dole
michael dukakis, albert gore jr. and jesse jackson all campaigned in kansas during the week, while richard gephardt instead focused his energies on michigan's march 26 caucuses and paul simon straggled along behind
dukakis, his prospects enhanced by a strong organizing effort, had a slight edge heading into today's kansas caucuses
we've been organized in kansas for eight months,'' said dukakis' state campaign chairman, state sen. paul feleciano. ``... i think we'll get 20 to 24 of the 39 delegates still to be picked.''
gore's state campaign chairman, state sen. joe norvell, was hoping the tennessee senator's late forays into kansas ``could minimize what i would consider an early lead for gov. dukakis.''
jackson had out-organized gore, but supporters conceded that not enough counties were organized to claim a majority of the delegates
gephardt, struggling to recover from the thrashings he took on super tuesday and again in illinois, was hoping michigan would revive his flagging campaign
eighteen members of congress flew to michigan on friday to campaign for the missouri congressman but a poll showed him trailing well behind dukakis and jackson
we're going to make political history in michigan, just as we did in iowa,'' said gephardt, who had his best showing to date in iowa's leadoff caucus
cash-poor simon was in pennsylvania on friday for a series of fund-raisers. he continue to predict none of the democrats would lock up the nomination before the national convention in july
if you're talking about buying the nomination, i can't do that,'' he said. ``if you're talking about winning the nomination, i can do that.''
gore spent friday vote-hunting in puerto rico, where he said that he would consider allowing the territory to be exempt from the federal minimum wage and that he favored letting the territory decide itself whether to become a u.s. state
dukakis released a videotaped address in spanish in which he pledged to work to increase payments to puerto ricans under the medicaid, aid to families with dependent children and supplemental social security programs
bush was the only republican to mount an organizing campaign in puerto rico
dole's weakened campaign, meanwhile, continued to shrink, with only about 10 to 12 aides left on the payroll, according to spokeswoman dale tate
pat robertson, campaigning in california, conceded bush had an overwhelming delegate lead but pledged to stay in the race because ``there has to be a rallying point for conservatives.''
other political activity on tap today: gephardt hoped to turn his victory in last month's south dakota primary into delegates at today's state convention, and dukakis and jackson, the front-runners in the texas primary on march 8, were expected to divvy up most of the 64 delegates at that state's caucuses. disruption</head>
a congressional delegation was bound for el salvador today to monitor legislative and municipal elections that leftist forces have threatened to disrupt
president reagan selected the group of republicans and mostly conservative democrats to watch sunday's election and report back to him, officials said friday
our presence there is mainly one to deter any fraud (by the participating political parties) and to objectively and fairly report what we see happening,'' said rep. john g. rowland, r-conn., a delegation member
andy fisher, an aide to sen. richard g. lugar, r-ind., said the lawmakers will visit polling places in san salvador and the countryside despite the pinpointing of the polls as military targets by the leftist forces
but rowland said the threats may keep the delegation away from the polls. the delegation's presence at the polls would ``show the voters we're not afraid,'' he said, but added ``i'm not sure if we're doing that.''
we cannot stop violence,'' rowland said
the delegation, headed by lugar and rep. john p. murtha, d-pa., was scheduled to leave andrews air force base today and return late sunday night or early monday morning
the u.s.-backed salvadoran government headed by president jose napoleon duarte is holding elections sunday for mayors and councils in the country's 262 municipalities and for all 60 seats in the legislative assembly
leftist groups have vowed to ban road transportation during the elections to disrupt voting, and said polling places will be ``military objectives.'' the rebels maintain that peace must be achieved before any election is held
the main electoral opposition to the ruling christian democratic party is arena, a rightist group
this particular election is a test for democracy, not only because of the hazards proposed by the rebels, but perhaps because many citizens of el salvador, after five elections, have lost some of their enthusiasm for democracy,'' lugar said in a statement
rowland said the election, which has not gained widespread attention because it does not include a presidential race, is important because duarte's party could lose its slim majority in the assembly
there could be a definite change in the makeup of the assembly,'' the congressman said in a telephone interview from connecticut
the congressional group will be briefed by state department officials in san salvador before monitoring the elections
the house members include reps. rowland; murtha; beverly b. byron, d-md.; john r. kasich, r-ohio; mickey edwards, r-okla.; and alan b. mollohan, d-w.va., according to rowland aide harry phillips
senators include lugar, frank h. murkowski, r-ala.; christopher s. bond, r-mo.; said fisher
the salvadoran defense ministry said about 53,000 troops will be deployed to provide election security
a new jersey developer and a wild west show owner are among the western history buffs who bought up the largest collection of ``buffalo bill'' cody memorabilia ever auctioned _ with some pieces fetching more than twice their appraised value
who better symbolizes the american west than buffalo bill?'' said buyer r.l. wilson, a historical consultant to the colt firearms co. of hartford, conn., who bid friday on one of eight guns in the collection
the prices paid ranged from $175 for a telegram sent by the legendary roughrider and showman to $22,500 for a silver-handled plains rifle
in all, more than $500,000 was spent on the collection of over 300 items, which were perserved by cody's sister, julia cody goodman, auction officials said
the collection was sold by san francisco gun collector greg martin, who bought the artifacts for $300,000 last year, removing them from storage in billings, mont., for the first time in 20 years
the collection was unique for its large number of personal items, including cody's buffalo-hide coat that sold for $18,000 and a letter that sold for $3,575 in which cody discusses the death of his son. the prices included a 10 percent fee for the auction house, butterfield &amp; butterfield
also up for auction were other letters to cody's sister discussing his marriage and other intimate events
we are interested in the correspondence because it is so revealing and personal,'' paul fees, curator of the buffalo bill museum in cody, wyo., said before the bidding began. ``we have a strong biographical interest.''
other bidders for the letters included thomas b. morrison, of the buffalo bill ranch historic park in north platte, neb. cody descendant walter goodman of dallas, julia cody's grandson, was expected to bid for the letters by phone, fees said. the names of the successful bidders were not known
a pair of chaps worn by cody sold for $1,400 and a rope lariat went for $500. other items included cody's silver-handled toothbrush, a family bible and dozens of photographs, show bills and theater tickets chronicling william f. cody's life as the indian fighter, buffalo hunter and scout who, along with shooting champion w. ``doc'' carver, founded the first wild west show. cody died in 1917
ned gillette's first thought after being knocked into the treacherous waters off cape horn was not about his fate, but whether the ``sea tomato'' would survive the wintry gale in its quest to sail to antarctica
moments later, gillette was pulled back aboard the high-tech rowboat _ never fully tested in open ocean _ to join three other adventurers who hoped it was possible to row 600 miles across the treacherous drake passage from south america
on march 7, after suffering three knockdowns in heavy seas and skirting icebergs, the four waddled about nelson island off antarctica like the penguins that greeted them at the end of the voyage
you should see what it's like to try to walk on land after being thrown around at sea for 12 days,'' said gillette, whose arrival in antarctica ended a 4{-year quest that included an unsuccessful expedition last year
until we made it, we weren't really sure it could be done,'' gillette, 42, a native of stowe, vt., said friday
while the crew bailed out flooded cabins and rowed their 28-foot boat through 100-foot swells, a massachusetts weather station each day fed them with sophisticated forecasts and the boat's location was tracked by satellite
the ``sea tomato,'' so-called because of its red color, was built for $17,000 and equipped with state-of-the-art navigational and survival equipment. after waiting for nearly a month for proper weather conditions, the expedition almost ended in disaster feb. 22 off the chilean coast. twelve hours after leaving under sail, a heavy squall erupted and tipped the craft, sending gillette overboard. gillette, an experienced moutaineer, was saved by a line fastened to the boat
in the next several days, the boat took two more spills, casting crew members jay morrison, 34, and fred trombly, 32, into the sea
three days out, the crew took down the sails and began to row in shifts, sometimes all night. they creeped southward at an average rate of 2.3 knots, about walking speed
crew member mark eichenberger, 35, said the raging drake passage seas and variable weather made the expedition more challenging than other rowing voyages across the atlantic and pacific
why did we do it?'' said morrison. ``because nobody had ever done it before. that's a pretty good reason.'' risk</head>
grocery store managers, construction foremen, mine inspectors and other low-level and middle managers have a greater risk of heart attack than blue-collar workers or other white-collar workers, a study shows
previous studies have found that blue-collar workers are more likely to die of heart attacks than white-collar workers. but robert brackbill, the author of the new study, said friday that the managers with increased risk of disability from a heart attack are in some respects more like blue-collar workers than white-collar workers
they had the lowest mean level of education compared to other professional groups,'' said brackbill, of the national institute for occupational safety and health in cincinnati
brackbill said the group's socio-economic status and wages were also closer to those of blue-collar workers and, like them, the middle and low-level managers might not have good access to medical care
brackbill, who presented his findings at a meeting of the american heart association, studied samples from 446,000 social security disability records covering the periods 1969-1973 and 1975-1976
during the first period, low-level and middle managers had 43 percent more chance of having a heart attack than other white-collar workers and blue-collar workers. the risk was 63 percent higher for them in the second period
the study also found that educators, lawyers and entertainers had among the lowest risks of professionals while medical professionals _ doctors, nurses and technicians _ had a slightly higher risk than blue-collar workers
brackbill had no information on the smoking and eating habits and alcohol consumption of the workers he studied, so it's possible that the increased risks he identified were due to those factors rather than jobs
had that been the case, however, he said it would have been unlikely for a single occupational group to have increased risk. the risk would more likely have been spread among all professionals or all blue-collar workers, rather than be specific to certain subgroups, he said
the study suggests that occupation is associated with disability, but does not prove it, he said
the american heart association includes stress as one of the risk factors for heart disease, and notes that stress may increase the likelihood of getting heart disease when combined with other risk factors, such as smoking, high blood pressure and elevated levels of cholesterol in the blood
dr. peter schnall of cornell university medical college in new york city reported in a separate study that high blood pressure was associated with ``job strain'' _ a combination of high psychological demands on the job and little latitude in making decisions
in another study, suzanne haynes of the national institutes of health in bethesda, md., said that women in high-demand, low-control jobs operating computer terminals all day reported a higher occurrence of angina, a chest pain associated with heart disease. requested</head>
president jose azcona hoyo said he was sending troops to rugged mountains near the nicaraguan border to oust sandinista forces, and a white house source said u.s. helicopter assistance was requested
azcona said friday that 2,000 troops had begun moving into the bocay jungle region on orders to drive out the sandinistas, adding that his government was preparing ``an operation to bomb inside honduran territory.''
he told a news conference he was `counting on the support of the united states'' to deter sandinista aggression. he called the arrival in honduras thursday and friday of more than 3,000 u.s. troops a ``warning'' to nicaragua
at the united nations on friday, nicaragua's leftist sandinista government denied u.s. and honduran claims that its troops invaded honduras, where the rebels maintain base camps
managua's u.n. envoy accused the reagan adminstration of creating ``an artificial crisis'' in a bid to get congress to restore military aid to the contras
on thursday, honduras mounted air raids in the border area where sandinista troops allegedly penetrated honduran territory in pursuit of contra rebels. azcona said his forces would bomb sandinista positions until an estimated 1,000 remaining nicaraguan troops withdraw
u.s. embassy spokesman michael o'brien said friday evening that the united states was considering airlifting honduran troops to non-combat areas. in washington, administration sources said the honduran request would likely be approved. the sources spoke on condition of anonymity
the united states helped honduras move troops to the border in december 1986, after nicaraguan forces attacked contra camps in honduras. no americans were involved in combat
the u.s. embassy said about 800 american paratroopers _ the last group of the 3,200 troops sent to honduras _ were dropped onto palmerola air base friday morning. the defense department said the u.s. troops would be in central america for about 10 days
azcona said he expected the ``simple presence and immediate response'' of u.s. troops would scare the sandinistas into withdrawing. he repeated what u.s. officials have been saying, that u.s. troops would not be involved in any fighting
on thursday, honduran warplanes struck at nicaraguan positions tegucigalpa says were inside its borders. but managua says rockets hit inside nicaragua, near the sandinista's border military encampment at san andres de bocay
sandinista troops retook san andres de bocay from the contras in an offensive managua says began march 8 and drove hundreds of guerrillas into honduras. privately, a sandinista military official indicated nicarguan troops had entered honduras
a high-ranking honduran officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said about 2,000 soldiers were moving friday into the area of hostilities from a base at juticalpa, about 90 miles west of san andres de bocay, and warplanes were on call
the officer said about half of the original force of 2,000 sandinistas who crossed the border had returned to nicaragua, while the rest penetrated deeper into honduran territory and were spread over an area of about 40 square miles
another source in tegucigalpa, who asked not to be identified, said the sandinistas stopped penetrated deeper into honduras when the united states publicized the incursion earlier this week
the source said the only activity reported in the region friday involved sandinistas he said fired highly flammable white phosphorus at contras inside honduras, estimated at 600 fighters
the main objective of the sandinista offensive was to destroy a contra headquarters and a large rebel supply depot in the jungle north of san andres de bocay, the source said, declining to name the site
president daniel ortega of nicaragua said thursday that his soldiers were ready to ``combat and liquidate'' the 82nd airborne and would continue the anti-contra offensive in an area from central nicaragua to the border
in their 6-year-old insurgency, the contras have had secret bases in honduras from which they have attacked nicaragua
at the u.n. security council meeting friday, nicaraguan envoy rita delia casco said the united states would be to blame if war broke out, saying the crisis was ``artificially created by the u.s. adminstration.''
u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun said managua had planned the anti-contra offensive after congress denied further aid last month. he denied u.s. forces sent to honduras constitute a threat or use of force against nicaragua
ambassador jorge ramon hernandez of honduras said nicaragua was trying to derail peace efforts in central america
sandinista-contra talks set for monday are now doubtful
foreign observers of czechoslovak-soviet military exercises will be allowed for the first time to use cameras and tape recorders, lt. gen. jiri brychta told a news conference
he said 22 countries have applied to send a total of 43 observers to the maneuvers to be held by 17,400 soviet and czechoslovak military personnel in western czechoslovakia march 22-28
brychta, first deputy chief of the general staff, said friday that the use of cameras and recorders by the observers ``should make their work easier and goes beyond the framework of conditions provided for by the stockholm document.''
under the stockholm agreement on security and cooperation in europe, the soviet-led warsaw pact and north atlantic treaty organization are to allow foreign observers to view large military maneuvers
a former wedtech corp. executive says a friend of attorney general edwin meese iii told him that meese intervened with the pentagon to help get a $24 million navy contract awarded to the bronx contractor
mario moreno made the revelation friday in his fourth day of testimony in the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi and six others accused of bribery and influence peddling involving wedtech
moreno said he met meese's friend, san francisco lawyer e. robert wallach, in december 1983. he said he asked wallach to get meese ``to change the navy's mind'' about awarding wedtech only the less lucrative part of a contract to build bridge pontoons. meese was presidential counselor at the time
meese said he would ask then-defense secretary caspar weinberger to call then-navy secretary john lehman, wallach told moreno
in january 1984, a month after wallach told moreno of meese's alleged intercession, wedtech received the approval making it eligible for the entire pontoon contract, which it signed in april 1984
moreno testified previously that wallach told him meese also had interceded on wedtech's behalf with the commerce department over another defense contract
moreno had described meese's alleged intervention for the pontoon contract in an affidavit disclosed last october at a senate hearing in washington. at that time, both meese and weinberger said they did not remember the incident
the contract was to build floating bridge units to link supply ships with u.s. rapid deployment forces
wedtech, a $100 million-a-year defense contractor before it filed for bankruptcy in 1986, grew from a small bronx machine shop through a series of no-bid defense contracts
the company was able to obtain those contracts through a small business administration program for minority-controlled businesses, but federal prosecutors claim that wedtech falsely portrayed itself as being eligible
wallach, meese's former personal lawyer, is under indictment for allegedly taking bribes from wedtech officials in exchange for trying to influence meese and others
last december, a special prosecutor in washington said there was insufficient evidence to charge meese with wrongdoing in the wedtech case
moreno, one of four ex-wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty to bribing public officials and other crimes, also testified that the company paid former bronx borough president stanley simon and biaggi's law firm $50,000 each for their help in a real estate deal with the city
moreno said wedtech did not have the proper facilities to assemble and test the pontoons and wanted to lease city-owned land in the bronx
the reagan administration, looking for an ``early response'' to its mideast peace plan, is sending special envoy philip habib to jordan, egypt, saudi arabia and morocco to discuss the proposal
the state department said habib will consult next week with officials in the arab countries and brief them on the discussions held this week in washington with israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir
he also is expected to ask jordan for its response to the proposal formulated by secretary of state george p. shultz for israeli-arab talks about palestinian self-rule in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
we're looking for an early response to our proposals from the parties in the region,'' department spokesman charles redman said friday
shultz's plan envisions that talks on self-rule would begin may 1 between jordan, israel, palestinians and any other arabs wishing to take part, under the auspices of the united states, the soviet union, china, england and france. the plan also calls for talks to start dec. 1 about the future of the west bank and gaza strip that israel captured from the arabs in the 1967 mideast war
we have an ambitious timetable,'' redman said. ``this is an active process. ... we're intensively engaged in it.''
shamir already has rejected the idea of an international peace conference, fearing it would bring pressure on israel to cede occupied lands, but he promised to bring up the plan next week for a vote by his divided cabinet
we continue to be encouraged by the active and serious consideration being given to this proposal by all the parties concerned,'' redman said
habib, a retired ambassador who negotiated between israel and the arabs in the early 1980s, undertook a one-day trip to jordan at the end of january to sound out king hussein about the shultz plan. this time he will spend less than a week on his mission, redman said
the united states also is consulting with syria on the shultz plan, but this is being done through the embassies in washington and damascus, according to a state department official who spoke only on condition of anonymity
habib's stop in morocco is designed to bring that country into the process as a moderating influence. morocco, a former french colony, enjoys good standing with both the arabs and israel
five former passenger service agents for airlines have been convicted of participating in an eight-year conspiracy to smuggle $1.5 billion worth of cocaine through kennedy international airport
after five days of deliberations, a jury in u.s. district court in brooklyn returned guilty verdicts friday against the five men and another defendant on all counts of the nine-count indictment
the defendants were among 56 people arrested last year in connection with the drug smuggling operation. of those arrested, most have either pleaded guilty or been convicted in state and federal courts. six others remain fugitives
all six defendants were convicted of the most serious charge of conspiracy, which carries a possible life sentence. sentencing is expected to take place within six weeks
federal prosecutors charged during the six-week trial that four of the airline employees used their positions to circumvent customs in the united states and brazil to bring several tons of cocaine into the country between 1979 and 1987
the two lead defendants _ jean marie chapoteau, 50, of queens, a former passenger service agent for pan american world airways, and pedro dasilva, 49, of miami, who held a similar position at varig airlines _ were charged with running separate smuggling operations at their respective airlines
two other pan am service agents _ vincent cicali, 29, of queens, and bruce duignan, 31, of massapequa _ were accused of working for a third smuggling operation at kennedy run by another former pan am employee, aart vanwort
vanwort pleaded guilty to a conspiracy charge earlier this year and was one of the prosecution's key witnesses during the trial. he is awaiting sentencing
the other defendants were also convicted of purchasing portions of the cocaine smuggled into the country. they are michael crown, 34, of queens, a former passenger service agent for pan am, and steven finn, 33, an auctioneer from boston
the case stemmed from an investigation by the federal drug enforcement agency, the u.s. customs service, the internal revenue service and the port authority police
two decades ago the kerner commission said news organizations were ``shockingly backward in seeking out, hiring, training and promoting'' blacks. they still are, according to a group of black journalists
despite some industry attempts to improve black employment prospects, ``what has resulted in far too many instances can simply be characterized as a lot of motion and little movement,'' the group said in a report released friday
the national association of black journalists formed a panel to compare the status of blacks in journalism today with the late 1960s, when race riots prompted president lyndon johnson to appoint illinois gov. otto kerner as head of the national advisory commission on civil disorders
the kerner commission's conclusion ``still rings true,'' said dewayne wickham of the gannett news service, president of the nabj
the panel, which wickham said carried out its study over a period of several months, acknowledged ``substantial good will'' among news media executives. ``we also found there had not been a lot of progress.''
among the panel's recommendations:
_ newspaper publishers should promise to double the number of black journalists over the next three years, from 3.5 percent of newsroom employees to 7 percent by 1991
_ the national association of broadcasters and the radio-television news directors association should join the nabj to form a task force to halt the decline in blacks working in television news. a declining number of black men employed in broadcast news caused the number of minority group members to drop from 15 percent in 1979 to 13 percent in 1986, the panel said
dwight ellis, nab vice president for minority services, said the reason for the decline was unclear. he said the nab and news editors were considering two remedies: an advertising campaign to tell minority group members about some of the less obvious jobs available in broadcasting, and an institute to train them for management
lee stinnett, executive director of the american society of newspaper editors, said its surveys show that the number of minority group members employed in newspaper newsrooms has more than doubled since 1978, rising from 1,700 to 3,600
the percentage of these minority employees, 55 percent of whom are black, has increased from 4 percent to 6.5 percent, he said
jerry w. friedheim, president of the american newspaper publishers association, said the organization was ``working to increase the number of minority journalists.''
he said anpa was readying the first industry-wide survey of minority employment, and has programs to encourage the hiring and promotion of blacks, including 12 minority job fairs in the past year
the nationwide pool of insurance funds to be tapped in the event of an accident at a nuclear reactor or related facility would grow from $700 million to more than $7 billion under legislation approved by the senate
the proposal, approved by senate voice vote friday, is part of legislation providing a 20-year extension of the price-anderson act. the bill now goes back to the house, which approved a slightly different version last july
under current provisions of the price-anderson act, the pool could pay up to $700 million to compensate victims if the accident involved a commercial nuclear power plant, and up to $500 million if it involved a government-owned facility. both the house and senate versions of the renewal legislation would boost the amount in both cases to more than $7 billion
the government is giving illegal aliens who want to file for amnesty an extra 60 days to come up with the documents to support their applications for legalization
under the change announced friday, the application deadline of may 4 still will stand, but amnesty seekers who file in the final month before then will have until july 5 to produce back-up documentation and medical data
if any of you have ever filed your income tax on the night of the 14th of april, there's usually one document or one fact you don't get,'' attorney general edwin meese iii told reporters at an immigration office in arlington, va. ``we want to be sure that doesn't stop anybody from this program.''
just over 1 million amnesty applications have been filed, and although a last-minute surge is anticipated, the volume of requests is likely to fall far below the 2 million estimated as recently as january by alan nelson, commissioner of the u.s. immigration and naturalization service
a group of senators from the pacific island chain of palau says problems with drugs there have been ``permitted to develop unchecked'' during 40 years of u.s. rule and could best be solved by a new sovereign government
the seven palau lawmakers on friday accused a house subcommittee of unreasonably delaying their country's independence with unfounded charges of corruption and narcotics trafficking
the palau senators raised the issues in a letter to ron de lugo, the virgin islands delegate, who is chairman of a house subcommittee on insular and international affairs
the senators admitted the islands had drug and other problems but said they had been ``permitted to develop unchecked'' during 40 years of u.s. rule, and could be attacked more effectively now by the new government with financing promised under the recently-approved compact of free association with the united states
taxi driver alfonso valdez stopped at a red light, and four young men jumped in the car. the one in the front seat and the one directly behind him pulled pistols
`we're a guerrilla urban commando cell, and you should know better than to take your cab out when we've called a transport ban,''' valdez quoted one of the men as telling him. they ordered him out of the cab, set it afire and fled
the cab was one of several vehicles burned friday by guerrillas trying to enforce the indefinite traffic ban they called to dissuade voters from participating in sunday's elections
even so, the government and small-time entrepreneurs with pickup trucks kept a lot of urban traffic moving
salvadorans cast ballots sunday to elect all the members of the 60-seat national assembly and municipal officials nationwide. leftist guerrillas fighting the u.s.-backed government since 1979 say the people's will cannot be expressed by voting in wartime
intercity bus transport was reduced by about 80 percent nationwide, according to dispatchers quoted in telephone and radio reports
the privately owned radio station ysu, with correspondents in almost all of el salvador's 14 provinces, said guerrillas burned eight vehicles in the eastern province of usulutan
the station said two buses, two tractor-trailers, two pickups, one jeep and one taxi were burned there. no injuries were reported
one person died in the capital when an extremely overcrowded pickup truck overturned. eighteen people were reported injured in the accident
scores of pickups with up to 40 people packed in truckbeds and standing on bumpers circulated in the capital, partially taking the place of privately owned buses, few of which were seen on the road
rides in the trucks cost up to 60 cents, or five times the normal bus fare
the government put several dozen blue and white state-owned buses on the streets, and they too were overcrowded, with people riding on roof luggage racks, hanging from the doors and standing on the bumpers. army trucks also were used for passenger transport
but many _ probably most _ people simply walked to work
ten yards from where valdez recounted the friday evening hijacking, in a middle class neighborhood of this capital, what was left of the yellow toyota smoldered. the guerrillas had run down the road about a half hour before, and firemen had just extinguished the blaze
what could i do?'' said valdez, 49. ``they were armed.''
he said his only remaining fear was informing the woman who owned the taxi that it was now a black hulk
dozens of children stood around, enthralled by the spectacle. their parents, who also had gathered to watch the flames consume the car, criticized the guerrillas. with contras</head> ^by bryna brennan</byline>
the sandinista government warned its citizens to brace for a possible invasion by u.s. troops newly arrived in honduras and encouraged its soldiers to keep contra rebels on the run
as nicaraguan troops on friday battled the u.s.-supplied guerrillas in a region bordering honduras, the leftist government said it still desires to hold peace talks with the u.s.-backed rebels next week
government radio warned listeners of ``american imperialism and the threat of military intervention.'' and a headline in barricada, the sandinista newspaper, said: ``the order of the day: intensify combat.''
the radio also condemned border air raids by honduras, which it said struck inside nicaragua. honduras said the raids thursday were confined to sandinista forces that had crossed into honduran territory
honduras and the united states contend sandinista troops entered honduras in the rugged jungle region in pursuit of contras. officially, the sandinistas deny this. but privately, a nicaraguan military official indicated friday that an incursion had occurred
honduran military officials said 1,000 sandinista soldiers remained in their territory on friday
in managua, the defense ministry said 17 soldiers and 15 rebels were killed between tuesday and friday in fighting in the central province of matagalpa, in zelaya on the caribbean coast and jinotega, along the honduran border
civilian sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity for security reasons, said 17 soldiers were killed and eight wounded in two clashes friday in the central province of chontales. six rebels were killed, they said
lt. col. javier carrion, who led the sandinista offensive, told reporters thursday at the border outpost of san andres de bocay that 4,500 sandinista soldiers backed by bombers and helicopter gunships were involved in the campaign that began march 8 and drove hundreds of contras back into honduras, where they have base camps
carrion said sandinista troops killed 92 contras and wounded 300, at the cost of 34 soldiers dead and 68 wounded
he said the purpose was to destroy contra bases in the border area, about 40 miles from an important mining region the rebels attacked in december
on thursday and friday, the united states flew in 3,200 soldiers of the 82nd airborne division and 7th light infantry to honduras in what the white house called a ``measured response'' to the alleged nicaraguan incursion
president daniel ortega said nicaraguan troops would take on the americans if necessary
his government, meanwhile, insisted it was going ahead with plans for cease-fire talks with the contras in nicaraguan territory on the costa rican border monday. the rebels said they would boycott the talks unless the sandinistas pull out of honduras
cease-fires in the region's civil wars, and a ban on the use of one country's territory for attacks on another, are provisions of the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by the five central american presidents
the plan also calls for an end to outside aid to insurgents
in washington, a bi-partisan group of senators proposed a $48 million package of new aid to the contras, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
on feb. 3, president reagan narrowly lost a house vote on continuing contra aid. a democratic alternative was defeated, 216 to 208, a month later
potential delegates to california's state democratic convention favor michael dukakis over his presidential rivals, but they still prefer non-candidate mario cuomo, according to poll results published today
the poll of 217 of 1,200 potential delegates to the convention this weekend in palm springs was conducted by the riverside press-enterprise
asked to rank their favorites among the declared candidates, the party regulars lined up 38 percent for dukakis, 22 percent for jesse jackson, 10 percent for paul simon, 8 percent for albert gore jr. and 3 percent for richard gephardt. eighteen percent were undecided
that changed dramatically when the list was expanded to include new york gov. mario cuomo. cuomo was the favorite of 34 percent, dukakis 20 percent, jackson 16 percent, simon 7 percent, gore 6 percent and gephardt 3 percent, with 15 percent undecided
on sunday, monday and tuesday, the paper interviewed potential delegates picked at random from a list provided by the party. max neiman, a university of california, riverside, political science professor with polling experience, reviewed the methods and calculated the sample had a 5.5 percentage point margin of error
while the number of new york democrats who think gov. mario cuomo should run for president keeps edging up, the number who think he will run is declining, a poll indicates
results of a poll released friday by the marist college institute for public opinion found that while 59 percent of the democrats surveyed said cuomo should run, only 24 percent said they thought he would. in a january poll by marist, 58 percent of the democrats said cuomo should run and 36 percent said they thought cuomo would run
he's pleased that the people are taking him at his word,'' cuomo spokeswoman anne crowley said of the governor's reaction to the poll results
the poll also indicated that michael dukakis and jesse jackson appear to be in a two-man race among likely new york democratic primary voters with the crucial april 19 presidential primary just a month away
the poll found that 37 percent of the 459 likely democratic voters surveyed said they would vote for dukakis while 28 percent said they would back jackson. the other democratic candidates trailed far behind
the poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points
a 75-year-old retired police chief appeared in court for allegedly selling heroin because he says his allergy-suffering wife wanted to buy a $9,600 carpet, a newspaper reported
vincenzo alessi and his wife fulvia borello, 61, of this seaside town in the northern region of liguria, appeared at a pre-trial hearing thursday to answer to charges of drug dealing, milan's daily corriere della sera reported friday
the alessis were arrested in may on charges of selling 5 grams of heroin to a woman in the area. police said they also found more than 30 grams of pure heroin inside their imperia home
alessi said in court that he had become involved in selling drugs because ``my wife wanted to change the carpeting.'' he said she insisted on the change because she suffers from allergies
a co-founder of the notorious red army faction leftist gang, having renounced terrorism, can now practice law again in west berlin
horst mahler, 52, who spent six years in prison on a terrorism conviction, regained his license friday after a november ruling by the west german supreme court, said west berlin justice department spokesman cornel christoffel
the court endorsed an appeal by mahler against an earlier refusal by west berlin's judicial authorities to allow him to work again as a lawyer
the high court pointed out that mahler distanced himself from his earlier actions and denounced terrorism
mahler was arrested in west berlin in 1970 and was convicted four years later on bank robbery charges and for helping notorious terrorist andreas baader escape from jail
he was sentenced to 14 years in prison but was released in 1980 after several public statements condemning terrorism and red army faction methods
suspected sikh extremists today shot to death five members of a sikh family, including a two-year old girl, in a raid on the family's farmhouse in punjab state, police said
police also recovered the bodies of five other people killed friday in attacks blamed on sikh radicals, including three sikhs shot to death in the village of manda in amritsar district and an unidentified man killed in nearby janti village
a sikh farmer, identified as amrik singh, was shot to death friday night in jalandhar district, police said
the killings raised to at least 480 the number of people who have died in attacks blamed on the militants since jan. 1. last year, more than 1,000 people were killed in punjab by the extremists, who have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for an independent sikh homeland in punjab
the latest attack came at 12:30 a.m. in the village of butt, about 17 miles north of the sikh holy city of amritsar, police said
they said four gunmen shot farmer balbir singh and his family as they slept. the other victims were his wife, a son, a daughter-in-law and his granddaughter, amandeep, who was 2
after the shootings, the extremists set fire to the farmhouse and fled, police said
the motive for the attack was not known, but the militants have killed a number of moderate sikhs who disagree with their separatist goals. the extremists also have accused some sikhs of being ``police informers'' and have killed others who refused to pay extortion money
sikhs, whose sect was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to hinduism and islam, claim they are discriminated against by india's majority hindus. although a minority of about 2 percent in india, sikhs are a majority in punjab. functions</head>
a world health organization panel has concluded that people infected with the aids virus but not the disease itself do not run a higher-than-normal risk of brain and nervous system disorders
the 48-member panel also said in a statement friday that ``there is no evidence'' that screening healthy people for the hiv virus, which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, would help predict ``the onset of functional impairment.''
the statement noted some people with the disease aids or with aids-related-complex have suffered damage to the brain and nervous systems believed caused by the hiv virus
but it said that ``governments, employers and the public can be assured that based on the weight of available scientific evidence, otherwise healthy hiv-infected individuals are no more likely to be functionally impaired than uninfected persons.'' it said these recommendations would be kept under continual review as additional scientific material is gathered
aids is a virus that attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers
it is most often transmitted through sexual contact. other means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers. aids can also be passed from mother to child at or before birth
i think it is a serious mistake. it's another example of where president reagan is exaggerating the situation for his own purposes.'' _ former president jimmy carter, who opposed sending u.s. troops to honduras
i didn't think it would happen. rules are rules, and there's never been any exceptions. it's a very warm feeling, because it comes from the players. that to me is the greatest thank you for what i did.'' _ mary bea porter, after the ladies professional golf association bent its rules to allow her into a tournament even though she missed qualifying by three strokes. she had interrupted her game to save a 3-year-old boy from drowning
(my wife) miss dixie is afraid that next i'll stop cussing.'' _ singer-songwriter tom t. hall, who says life has changed since he quit drinking, smoking and went on a diet
when dusk settles in this seemingly tranquil eastern sri lankan village, people carrying straw mats, pillows and blankets leave their huts and trek to a buddhist temple to spend the night
galmetiyawa, inhabited mostly by members of the majority sinhalese community, was attacked by separatist tamil rebels at dusk monday. fifteen villagers were killed
now, residents sleep in the temple, fearing the attackers will come again
the rebels, dressed in military uniforms, came out of nearby jungle. in 30 minutes, they shot and killed four children, five women and six men
villagers said the rebels threw some of the victims' bodies into a hut and set it on fire. a sri lankan army lieutenant and two soldiers, who came to the village after hearing gunfire, chased the rebels away
marasinghe ratnasiri, a member of a home guard that once protected the village, complained that a peace accord with the tamils had taken away the local men's weapons
when we had guns, the rebels did not attack our village,'' said marasinghe, 28, a farmer with two children. ``now, they know we are defenseless.''
the rebels have been blamed for the killings of more than 110 people, most of them sinhalese, in sri lanka's eastern province this month as part of their bloody four-year campaign for a separate homeland
colonel lakshman wijayaratne, a sri lankan army officer, said the spate of killings aims to halt a government resettlement program aimed at encouraging sinhalese to migrate to the north and east
he predicted there would be more rebel attacks in reaction to the settling of sinhalese in what tamils view as their traditional homeland, saying it was not possible to protect every village in the area
many rebels fled to this part of the indian ocean island in october, when indian troops attacked the tamil stronghold of jaffna in the north
india deployed soldiers in sri lanka to disarm the rebels after they denounced a new delhi-sponsored peace accord with sri lanka's government aimed at ending the fighting by creating some measure of autonomy in the north and east where tamils are most numerous
under the india-sri lanka peace accord signed in july, sri lankan soldiers in the north and east are to keep to their barracks while indian troops take on the rebels
there are more than 50,000 indian troops in sri lanka, but the number in the eastern province is uncertain
galmetiyawa is 30 miles west of the coastal city of trincomalee. most of the recent killings have taken place around trincomalee, and 2,000 sri lankan soldiers are posted there along with indian soldiers
about 1,000 tamil rebels are believed to be in the district
tamils, who make up about 18 percent of the country's 16 million people, claim they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese, who control the government and military
rock star boris grebenshchikov has signed a contract to cut an album of his songs with american musicians. soviet officials said it would be the first american-produced soviet rock album released in the united states
grebenshchikov told a news conference friday that his songs, some in russian and others in english, will be performed by his group aquarium and american musicians who are to be chosen later
sporting a pony tail, blue jeans and six rings, grebenshchikov seemed ill at ease alongside american and soviet officials in suits who announced the deal. an earlier record on which he performed was released in the united states without the soviet government's consent
grebenshchikov is to record the album in new york and los angeles this summer for cbs records, which plans distribution in the united states and europe, said his american lawyer, ina meibach. the record also will be released in the soviet union, soviet officials said
