vietnamese troops torched chinese forests along the border this week after an exchange of gunfire between the two countries near disputed islands in the south china sea, an official report from china said
the fire began wednesday near the guangxi autonomous region border town of pingxiang, the domestic china news service said in a report appearing in hong kong today. chinese troops battled the blaze throughout the night, finally putting it out early thursday, the report said
it was the 25th time in the past five years that vietnamese troops situated across the pingerguan pass had set fire to chinese forests across the border, the news agency said
the report accused the vietnamese of attempting to use northwesterly winds wednesday to fan the fire and ruin guangxi's taqingshan forestry center during tree planting season. it said chinese troops saved 500 acres of forest with the help of a 3,000-yard fire lane built in july
the report did not say how much of the area was destroyed by the fire
tension between the neighboring communist countries has been mounting since gunfire was exchanged between chinese and vietnamese vessels near disputed islands in the south china sea on monday
china acknowledged wednesday it suffered an unspecified number of casualties in the clash, and vietnam said three of its vessels were burned in the encounter in the spratly islands
romantic comedies swept the top movie-writing honors as the strikebound writers guild of america handed out its 40th annual awards at a ceremony largely shunned by studio executives
steve martin took best screenplay for ``roxanne,'' an adaptation of ``cyrano de bergerac'' by edmund rostand, while john patrick shanley won best original screenwriting for ``moonstruck.''
cbs came away as the night's big winner, taking top honors in seven categories, including best tv spot-news script
nbc and abc each took four awards. the public broadcasting system had three and home box office won one for best variety-music, award tribute or special event for ``will rogers: look back in laughter.''
neither shanley nor martin was on hand to accept the awards from presenter sylvester stallone, who wore his ``rambo''-length hair in a ponytail
martin's acceptance speech was read by an associate. in it, he called rostand ``a great first-draft guy.''
martin also provided an ``if-i-lose'' speech. ``you pigs, you idiots. you wouldn't know a good script if it walked up to you and vomited on your shoes,'' his associate read as the audience rocked with laughter
in addition to writing the script, martin starred in ``roxanne,'' a summer hit from columbia pictures, along with daryl hannah
in ``moonstruck,'' a darkly romantic film nominated for six academy awards, cher stars as an italian widow in new york who finds herself engaged to one man but in love with his brother
the dinner extravaganza came on the 11th day of a strike by the 9,000-member guild against the alliance of motion picture and television producers
references to the strike flavored the evening, despite guild executive director brian walton's admonition, ``this is a night to celebrate writers and writing.''
but wga president george kirgo told the black-tie audience: ``the writers guild of america is stronger, more powerful, more cohesive, more unified than at any other time in our history.''
studios were conspicuously absent from the banquet tables. only columbia and 20th century fox were represented
before the dinner, the wga announced winners of special awards from its board of directors
the husband-and-wife screenwriting team of irving ravetch and harriet frank won the prized screen laurel award honoring them for their body of work, which includes such movies as ``norma rae,'' ``hud'' and ``murphy's romance.''
longtime television writing team bob schiller and bob weiskopf, who wrote over the past 35 years for such series as ``i love lucy,'' ``all in the family,'' ``maude'' and ``the red skelton show,'' were named co-winners of the paddy chayevsky laurel award for television
the award goes to a writer who has advanced the literature of television and made outstanding contributions as a television writer
light snow was scattered over parts of the east and midwest today, while rain stretched from florida to mississippi
snow fell on michigan and parts of pennsylvania, ohio, west virginia and maryland. forecasters posted snow advisories today for parts of north carolina, maryland and new england
snow changed to rain and extended across virginia and the carolinas into eastern tennessee. rain also fell across florida, southern mississippi and southwest alabama
about 1 inch of snow and ice covered the higher elevations of the smokey mountains in eastern tennessee friday night
today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across southern and central florida; rain along the remainder of the southern atlantic coast; snow over the great lakes and the ohio valley; scattered snow or flurries from new england into the central appalachians; rain over western washington state and northwest oregon; sunny skies from california to the lower mississippi valley; strong, gusty winds near the eastern slopes of the northern rockies and along the coast of the carolinas
highs were expected to be in the 50s or 60s for much of the nation; teens and 20s from north dakota across the great lakes region; 30s and 40s from the lower and middle missouri valley to the northern atlantic coast; 40s in the tennessee valley and the southern appalachians; and 70s and 80s from california across the desert southwest and over south florida
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 14 degrees at international falls, minn., to 74 degrees at miami, homestead and key west, fla
