india may have to maintain a military presence in sri lanka ``for many months, if not years to come,'' according to jane's defense weekly
the authoritative magazine said in this week's issue that india has an armed force of 65,000 in sri lanka under an accord to disarm tamil separatists, and almost total control of the island country off india's southern coast
it added the indian army has suffered considerable casualties and a host of problems in trying to keep peace, and its mission is far from over
the magazine said ``india's influence on sri lanka is now total and even in matters of foreign policy, sri lanka is controlled from new delhi.''
but ``in spite of having considerable numbers of troops, the indian peacekeeping force has problems in neutralizing the liberation tigers of tamil elam.'' the tigers are the main tamil guerrilla group waging a four-year war for creation of a separate state in northern and eastern sri lanka
india, which has a politically powerful tamil population of 60 million in its southern regions, sent a military force to sri lanka last july under a peace agreement signed with the sri lankan government
under the accord, limited autonomy would be given to the tamils in exchange for an arms surrender by the guerrillas
the sri lankan army, mistrusted by tamils because most officers come from the majority sinhalese population, was to stop fighting the rebels. the tamils, however, denounced the accord and have been fighting the indian troops
tamils, most of whom are hindus, make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people and the buddhist sinhalese 75 percent
jane's said india has six divisional headquarters, at least 15 brigades, and paramilitary, parachute, police and other forces in sri lanka
it said 500 indian soldiers have been killed and an estimated 2,500 wounded. india has said 400 soldiers and at least 1,100 rebels have been killed died in the fighting
jane's said the indians' high casualty rate could be attributed to the army's desire to avoid civilian casualties, its lack of experience in fighting guerrillas and its ``politically motivated'' orders to move as quickly as possible
this resulted in troops being committed to operations within hours of landing in unfamiliar territory,'' the article said. honduras</head> delete redundant ``hundred'' in lead. picks up 6th graf pvs, `in los ...'</note>
from maine to california, opponents of the deployment of u.s. troops in honduras staged demonstrations that blocked traffic, damaged a military recruitment center and prompted nearly 400 arrests
more than 500 protesters, chanting and waving signs, obstructed the entrance to the federal building in san francisco and stopped traffic during a five-hour demonstration friday. police arrested 250 of them for failure to disperse at an unlawful assembly, said police sgt. dave ambrose
violence erupted sporadically at the second demonstration in two days when protesters tried to grab police batons and other equipment. officers lashed back, jamming the batons in the demonstrators' faces, stomachs and chests
another 1,000 demonstrators, gathered by a coalition of san francisco's gay and lesbian groups, stopped traffic friday night on market street
about two dozen police on motorcycles kept the marchers moving as motorists delayed by the demonstration honked, some in frustration, some in support
about 1,500 people marched from times square to the united nations in new york in a hastily organized protest friday night. two people were arrested for disorderly conduct, said sgt. edward burns, a police spokesman
police blocked rush-hour traffic along the route to accommodate the protest
in los angeles, about 75 demonstrators gathered at the federal office building. twenty-five were arrested for refusing to leave the lobby when the building closed for the day and were cited for trespassing, a misdemeanor
federal police in sacramento, calif., arrested 29 demonstrators outside the federal building, where 275 people gathered. at fresno state university, about 150 people rallied
former president jimmy carter joined the opposition to president reagan's deployment of the soldiers in the war-torn region
it think it is a serious mistake. it's another example of where president reagan is exaggerating the situation for his own purposes,'' carter said friday in new orleans after addressing a conference of university presidents
in chicago, 60 protesters out of a crowd of about 400 were arrested on misdemeanor disorderly conduct charges after they pasted orange stickers on windows at the federal building and sat in intersections, police said. many of the stickers bore skull-and-crossbone symbols and the message ``stop u.s. intervention in central america.''
protesters in minneapolis hurled bowling balls, eggs and paint at a military recruitment building, broke four windows and ripped up a uniformed mannequin. scuffles broke out between protesters and counterdemonstrators, but there were no arrests or injuries, police said
in washington, 150 to 200 people demonstrated outside the white house, said police officer tom randolph. twenty-four were arrested after the protest spilled into pennsylvania avenue and were fined $25 for disorderly conduct
in portland, ore., millie thayer, a member of the portland central america solidarity committee, told about 200 protesters that reagan is risking more than military failure
we may be facing the presence of another vietnam, but the reagan administration is facing a solidarity movement stronger, deeper and more diverse than the vietnam movement ever was,'' she said. ``we don't have to wait for the body bags to come back before we begin our protest.''
in boston, about 10 demonstrators were removed from a u.s. navy recruitment center friday afternoon. none was arrested
more than 100 people marched in the nicaraguan immigrant enclave of sweetwater, fla., with signs supporting u.s. policy and mutilated an effigy of nicaraguan president daniel ortega
about 200 people gathered at bates college in lewiston, maine, and at augusta, maine, about 15 people quietly gathered at a busy intersection holding signs saying ``stop the reagan war machine'' and ``u.s. troops out of honduras.''
in sioux falls, s.d., about 70 people opposed to the troop deployment demonstrated outside the main post office while a small knot of people who supported the move shouted taunts through bullhorns. three were arrested
in seattle, about 40 cars circled the federal building to show their opposition to the troop movement, jamming streets for about an hour
drug dealers shot two of three boys they had abducted to work for them after the boys apparently failed to pay them for crack, police said
joseph jones, 12, told police he managed to escape from the kidnappers early friday. the boy said he was abducted last saturday by two young men from new york who forced him and his friends to sell crack, a derivative of cocaine
the body of cornell williams, 15, was found friday afternoon near philadelphia international airport with two gunshot wounds in the head, according to the city medical examiner's office
williams' brother, anthony williams, 13, was found tuesday along railroad tracks near downtown philadelphia with a bullet wound in the head, police said. he died the next day
joseph told police the boys owed their captors $500 for crack, but the people to whom they delivered the crack in their housing project never paid for it
when the boys returned with little crack left and what neighbors said was just $68, the enraged dealers held the boys hostage, police said
the dealers decided to kill anthony williams, who was classified as socially and emotionally disturbed, when the boy filched drugs while in captivity, detectives said
joseph said he did not know what happened to cornell after he escaped, according to detective edward tenuto
police said they were searching for the two men they believed to be the killers and a third man they believe aided in the abduction. police said two of the suspects are thought to be jamaican
three black policemen were killed when two men opened fire with automatic rifles on a group of people in the yard of a township west of pretoria, police said today
the attack friday night in atteridgeville was so sudden none of the police fired back at their black attackers, who fled on foot, said police lt. col. johan labuschagne
he said it had not yet been established whether the policemen were off-duty during the attack
police said in a statement that two men who wore blue overalls killed two officers at the scene, and wounded three other people, one of them a police officer who died later at kalafong hospital
meanwhile, police said they had captured two alleged terrorists and two collaborators and seized some arms in roadblocks set up friday in central transvaal province in an attempt to find those responsible for a krugersdorp car bomb that killed three black people and injured 20 people on thursday
police refused to give details about the roadblock arrests, but said none of those arrested were wanted in connection with the car bomb
meanwhile, anglican archbishop desmond tutu issued a statement in cape town condemning the car-bombing
he said: ``i deplore without equivocation acts such as this week's car bombing, since all violence is evil, whether it is that of a vicious system such as apartheid or the violence employed by people who wish to overthrow apartheid ... i desperately hope the day will come when the authorities realize that the only way to end violence is to eradicate apartheid.''
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. baghdad and launching artillery attacks; iraqi air raids. pickup 5th graf pvs ``tikrit, on...''; adds byline</note>
iran fired a long-range missile into baghdad and said it pounded more than a dozen other iraqi targets with artillery after iraq launched new air raids on cities in western iran
the attacks followed a day in which the warring countries reported blasting each other's cities with more than 40 missiles and attacking other targets on land and in the persian gulf
iraq, acknowledging today's attack on baghdad, said the missile crashed in a ``purely residential'' neighborhood. baghdad radio said several civilians were killed in the blast shortly after midnight but gave no casualty figures
iran's official islamic republic news agency said the missile was fired at the iraqi army's ``command headquarters in response to their mischiefs.''
irna reported 12 missiles fired into the southeastern iraqi umm qasr port, and one into al-amarah, a city 200 miles southeast of baghdad
it said revolutionary guards artillery units hammered a string of cities and towns along the 730-mile war front, including basra, iraq's already devastated southern port city
the attacks came after renewed iraqi air raids today on the western cities of bakhtaran and hamadan, as well as southwestern dezful, irna said. it gave no exact casualty count, but said ``many civilians were martyred.''
bakhtaran also was hit at 11:30 p.m. friday, irna said
iran claimed its gunners fired a long-range missile into tikrit on friday in the first attack on iraqi president saddam hussein's hometown since the resurgence of the war of the cities feb. 29. iraq did not report any attack on tikrit
reports from both sides were monitored in nicosia
tikrit, on the tigris river about 100 miles north of baghdad, is home to ``most members of the ruling clique in baghdad,'' an irna dispatch said
other missiles on friday hit the northern iraqi cities of mosul and kirkuk, the latter an important oil center
six missiles pounded basra, iraq's second largest city, while 24 other projectiles were lobbed into the southern towns of haretha, shubair, an industrial center just south of basra
the official iraqi news agency reported seven missiles fired into tehran friday, raising to 30 the number of such attacks on the iranian capital since sunday. in all, baghdad says it has fired 101 missiles into tehran since the intercity dueling began feb. 29
the iranians also claimed they captured two towns friday in a five-day-old land offensive into northeast iraq in which they said 9,200 iraqis have been killed or wounded and 4,000 captured
they also said they recaptured the iranian border town of nowsud, held by the iraqis since the early days of the 7{-year-old war
the iraqi news agency, also monitored in nicosia, has denied there was combat in that region, where most of iraq's 3.5 million kurds live
irna reported five iraqi warplanes were shot down thursday and friday, but iraq confirmed only one jet downed
iraq claimed two iranian jets were shot down. irna denied the report
the iraqi agency said iraqi warplanes hit two ``large maritime targets,'' which usually means tankers, off iran's coast on thursday and friday
london-based lloyd's shipping intelligence unit confirmed only one _ on the 80,137-ton cypriot tanker kyrenicos
iranian gunboats attacked three neutral ships in the southern gulf friday
in one attack, a japanese seaman was killed aboard the panamanian liquified gas carrier maria ii in the first raid around midnight thursday, shipping officials said on condition of anonymity
gunboats later attacked the 284,494-ton norwegian tanker berge lord, starting a small fire, and the 87,768-ton singapore-flag tanker neptune saburu. no casualties were reported in either attack. officers</head>
soldiers gunned down a suspected communist assassin during a shootout in the capital today, military authorities said
the incident came a day after gunmen wounded a national police major and three troopers in two attacks and a rebel chief proclaimed an autonomous moslem region in the southern philippines
lt. pedro vergara, investigation chief of the philippine constabulary capital command, said the shootout occurred in manila's residential district of santa mesa
he said soldiers arrested the suspect, miguel jardin, 26, in the nearby suburb of san juan and confiscated a .45-caliber pistol from him
vergara said that while being transported to a military camp, jardin jumped out of the military jeep and drew another gun concealed on his back, prompting the officers to shoot him
vergara said jardin is a suspected member of an urban-based communist hit squad and has been under close watch by the military
on friday, police said gunmen in a car fired on a vehicle carrying maj. pepito campos and his driver in suburban quezon city. both were wounded but doctors said they were recovering
a captain of the paramilitary national police, the philippine constabulary, was arrested for questioning, according to the police. campos is chief of the special investigations division of manila's northern police district
in the other attack friday, gunmen believed to be communist rebels fired on a military car in suburban taguig, wounding two constabulary troopers
thousands of moslems in the southern philippines held marches and rallies friday celebrating the 20th anniversary of the moro national liberation front, largest of three rebel groups seeking an independent islamic state in the region
at a rally of about 100 moslems in taguig organizers broadcast a taped statement by the front's leader, nur misuari, who lives in saudi arabia
he accused president corazon aquino of reneging on self-rule for the 5 million moslems and said the archipelago's central and southern regions were under the ``unlawful and immoral hegemony'' of luzon, the main philippine island
misuari declared the establishment of 20 federated states in mindanao and other southern islands as the homeland of the moslem minority
he claimed the foreign ministers of the 46-member organization of islamic conference, a worldwide moslem federation, were preparing to recommend full membership for the front at a meeting next week in amman, jordan. it now has observer status
phillipine officials have called full membership tantamount to secession and said it could start a new war in the south
gov. evan mecham has recanted an accusation, made under oath while he testified at his impeachment trial, that his former chief bodyguard stole a report from his office
moments after the republican governor admitted friday that he lacked the proof he earlier claimed he had, a state official testified the report had in fact been taken by one of mecham's own men, former state official lee watkins
i did not have the proof then and i do not have the proof now'' that the missing report was taken by department of public safety lt. beau johnson, the former head of the governor's security detail, mecham acknowledged in his third day of testimony before the senate
the governor did not apologize, but said he did not want to leave senators with the wrong impression
in sworn testimony thursday, the governor said he had ``had complete confirmation that he (johnson) was the one'' who took a report on the dps from then-chief of staff jim colter's desk and turned it over to the dps. mecham testified that he had an ``informer'' within dps
johnson denied taking the report, and the dps deputy director, lt. col. gary phelps, told senators friday it actually was taken by watkins, the former state prison construction chief
watkins is accused of making a death threat against a former top mecham aide. one of the three impeachment articles against mecham charges the governor with trying to obstruct an investigation of the alleged threat
watkins, reached by telephone, denied that he took the report
mecham fired johnson from his security detail after the police officer reported the alleged threat to his superiors
republican sen. tony west, who had demanded that mecham reveal who accused johnson of taking the report, admonished the governor. ``when you have careers, reputations at stake ... we have an obligation to protect each and every ... reputation and career.''
mecham again insisted friday that he did not know the alleged death threat against former top aide donna carlson was a serious matter. at the time, ms. carlson was about to testify before the state grand jury about mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan
the governor is accused of ordering dps director ralph milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat
testimony is expected to begin next week on the second allegation against mecham: that he misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. the third impeachment article accuses him of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan
the governor also faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of hiding the campaign loan, and a may 17 recall election
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham, and lawmakers also could decide to bar him from holding any future office. mecham is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona. ``g.'' ^by the associated press</note>
bruce c. clarke, a retired four-star general who was the army commander-in-chief in europe when berlin was the focal point of the cold war between the united states and the soviet union, died thursday. he was 86
during world war ii, he headed combat command a in the 4th armored division and later commanded the entire division. during the korean war, he commanded the u.s. i corps and later the x corps of the far east command
later, he commanded the u.s. army in the pacific, the u.s. 7th army in europe and the continental army command at fort monroe, va. he was commander-in-chief of the army in europe from 1960 to 1962
cuba has presented the united states with a proposed timetable for the withdrawal of its 40,000 troops stationed in angola, angola said
u.s. negotiators left the angolan capital friday after 10 days of talks with government authorities on efforts to secure peace in southern africa. american officials refused to comment on the progress of the negotiations or on the timetable
in lisbon, portugal, a statement friday by cuba's armed forces ministry said 39 cuban soldiers have been killed or wounded over the past two months defending a key southern angola town. anti-marxist angolan rebels also announced they had shot down a soviet-built mi-17 helicopter in the region
the foreign ministry said angola and a cuban delegation presented the united states with a proposed timetable for the withdrawal of the 40,000 cuban troops stationed in angola
officials in luanda, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a u.s. assistant secretary of state, chester crocker, was expected to pursue negotiations in angola next week
the united states, which has been negotiating since 1981 for a peace accord in the region, wants cuba to pull out of angola in return for a south african withdrawal from neighboring south-west africa, also known as namibia
angola says it will not send the cubans home until south african troops withdraw from angolan territory and cease all military incursions. in addition, angola wants an end to u.s. and south african aid to angolan rebels and the implementation of a u.n. plan for namibian independence
south africa says the cubans must leave angola first
the cuban statement, distributed to reporters in lisbon, said cuba had sent infantry units, tanks and artillery to help defend the garrison town of cuito cuanavale from south african attack
the town is a staging post for angolan government offensives against strongholds of the anti-marxist national union for the total independence of angola, or unita
hundreds of angolan troops were killed or wounded, the statement said. enemy forces also suffered heavy casualties, including hundreds of south african and south-west african soldiers, it added
angola estimates 9,000 south african troops are fighting in angola. unita, which also receives u.s. support, has been fighting to share power in angola's government since 1975, when it gained independence from portugal
unita claimed friday that its guerrillas shot down a government helicopter ferrying wounded angolan army officers from cuito cuanavale
the rebel statement said the helicopter crashed and killed all aboard when it was hit by anti-aircraft fire wednesday between cuito cuanavale and menongue, 100 miles to the west. summoning brother, probing allegations after request by chun. pickup 7th graf, ``we strongly...''</note>
a younger brother of former president chun doo-hwan flew to japan, airport officials said today, as controversy raged about his alleged involvement in financial and political scandals
opposition leaders charged the government allowed chun kyung-hwan to leave south korea. a presidential official announced that the government was considering summoning chun back and investigating the allegations
that announcement followed a request by the ex-president today for a formal investigation into the scandals involving his younger brother, said officials who spoke on condition of anonymity
chun, 46, left for osaka friday afternoon after booking a seat under a false name, airport officials said
under the former president, the younger chun headed the new community movement, a non-political campaign started in the 1970's to modernize rural and urban areas
the younger chun was allegedly involved in large-scale land speculation and the abuse of power to exact money from businessmen and force government agencies to divert funds to help his organization
one report estimated the total amount of money involved at between $60 million and $100 million
in an apparent move to defuse the controversy before next month's legislative elections, government officials said they would consider summoning chun from abroad
the government may start a full-scale investigation into the scandals, along with summoning mr. chun kyung-hwan,'' a high-ranking official at president roh tae-woo's presidential office said
the younger chun's sudden departure quickly became a political issue as opposition parties charged that the roh government helped him out of the country to escape possible criminal prosecution
we strongly demand that the government immediately arrest the criminal, put him to trial and get him due punishment,'' the major opposition reunfication democratic party said in a statement
the other major opposition party for peace and democracy said the case would test the morality of the newly inaugurated roh government
the younger chun has never held a political office, but was considered one of the most powerful figures in south korean politics
the scandals were not reported under the old government, which put a tight lid on the news media. local newspapers, which enjoy more freedom with roh's inauguration last month, began to report details of the scandals
roh, chun doo-hwan's chosen successor, defeated rival opposition candidates kim young-sam and kim dae-jung in december's presidential election. roh did not win a majority of the vote, winning because the opposition vote was split
talk about room service
when george m. harris jr. made his first visit to the hotel pennsylvania in new york in march 1933, he was an unexpected but welcome guest, coming into the world in room 1032 with the assistance of a hotel doctor
on friday, it was harris' turn to be surprised
the staff of the hotel, now the new york penta across from penn station, marked his 55th birthday by giving harris and his family a party, complete with cake and champagne, and by putting them up in the hotel's presidential suite for the weekend
i was born in this hotel and after this weekend i may die in this hotel,'' harris joked during the festivities
edward w. moles, the hotel's director of advertising and public relations, said the hotel had hosted presidents, band leader glenn miller and other notables, but harris was the only guest born there. he said employees had decided to go all out with a celebration when they learned that harris and his wife were coming to the big apple for a visit
harris and his wife, shirley, were scheduled to go to new york next week with a band from a rocky mount high school. mrs. harris called for reservations and thought the story of her husband's birth might get them a discount
harris became a new yorker when his mother, winifred, gave birth earlier than expected while traveling to rocky mount, 53 miles northeast of raleigh, with his father. harris said his father, a tobacco buyer, worked in turkey most of the time but was returning to rocky mount
it was a surprise to her,'' he said. ``they thought sure they had plenty of time to get to rocky mount.''
it was only appropriate that kelly give birth on st. patrick's day, but it still came as a surprise to officials of the oklahoma city zoo. they had no idea that the 16-year-old dolphin was pregnant
kelly's been a real trouper with the aquaticus performing atlantic bottlenose dolphin troupe since she came to the zoo in october, and no one knew she was well along into her year-long pregnancy, said zoo spokeswoman emily hopkins
but on thursday, kelly went into labor and her 3-foot-long, 45-pound daughter was born 45 minutes later at 4:20 p.m. zoo officials and trainers said the calf, as yet unnamed, appeared healthy and normal
she swam immediately to the surface of the water to breathe and then began swimming near her mother. the calf, which will nurse for about 3 to 5 months, will grow to an adult size of about 350 pounds, ms. hopkins said
the dolphin birth was the first for landlocked oklahoma, ms. hopkins added
a dutch embassy official has denied reports that a ship released friday by venezuela carried a team looking for sunken nazi treasure
the vessel ``is simply a cruise ship and has nothing to do with any treasure-hunting whatsoever,'' embassy spokesman harry trouerbach said in a telephone interview
earlier reports in europe said the ship was carrying treasure hunters in search of a world war ii wreck
that is a fantastic story. it surely comes from a very imaginative mind,'' trouerbach said
the plancius was released friday afternoon and was bound for the neighboring netherlands antilles island of curacao, trouerbach said late friday
the venezuelan coast guard detained the ship a week agp off la blanquilla island, 170 miles northeast of caracas. venezuela claimed it had illegaly entered its territorial waters
trouerbach said it was allowed to leave la guaira port at caracas once authorities determined it never actually entered venezuelan waters
the plancius was taking its 40 passengers to willemstad, curacao's main city, where they were scheduled to board a klm plane for the netherlands, trouerbach said
most of the passengers are biologists, not treasure-hunters,'' he said. that music city news is not a trade publication.</note>
country singer tammy wynette will perform and be master of ceremonies for a talent show monday to benefit the troubled nashville symphony, promoters say
sixty singers are to perform in the first round sunday in the ``mr. and ms. country music america'' talent contest, sponsored by music city news, a monthly country music publication, and memphis, tenn.-based holiday inc
ms. wynette will preside over the finals and perform monday night at the grand ole opry, officials said thursday. the winners of the best male and female vocalist categories win $10,000 and a recording contract
during monday night's show, organizers plan to pass the hat for the symphony, which folded in mid-season this year because of financial difficulties, said music city news general manager john sturdivant
if people have a good time, we don't think they'd mind dropping some money into a goldfish bowl,'' sturdivant said. ``we might raise a couple of thousand dollars that way.'' up 9th graf, `iran claimed ...'</note>
iraq said its warplanes blasted iran's vital oil center at kharg island today, setting oil installations and tankers ablaze. iran fired long-range missiles into baghdad and other iraqi cities
iraq, acknowledging the attack on baghdad, said the missile crashed in a ``purely residential'' neighborhood of the capital. baghdad radio said several civilians were killed in the missile blast, but gave no figures
iran's islamic republic news agency said the missile was fired at the iraqi army's ``command headquarters in response to their mischief.''
the iranian news agency, monitored in nicosia, also reported 12 missiles fired into the southeastern iraqi umm qasr port, and one into al-amarah, a city 200 miles southeast of baghdad
an urgent dispatch, carried by the iraqi news agency, said large formations of fighter-bombers attacked kharg island, on the northern edge of the persian gulf, and a tanker holding area east of the facility, in a ``daring'' raid
the agency, monitored in nicosia, quoted a mlitary spokesman as saying: ``our pilots ... devastated their targets, setting facilities on the island and several tankers nearby on fire.''
the unnamed spokesman did not say whether all attacking planes returned safely from the raid, and irna reported that iranian jets shot down an iraqi aircraft in a dogfight over the persian gulf
iran did not confirm the attack on kharg
kharg accounts for about 90 percent of iran's oil exports. it has been hit frequently in iraqi air raids
the iranian news agency said revolutionary guards artillery units hammered a string of cities and towns along the 730-mile war front, including basra, iraq's already devastated southern port city
the attacks came after renewed iraqi air raids today on the western cities of bakhtaran and hamadan, as well as southwestern dezful, the iranian news agency said. it gave no exact casualty count, but said ``many civilians were martyred.''
iran claimed its gunners fired a long-range missile into tikrit on friday in the first attack on iraqi president saddam hussein's hometown since the resurgence of the war of the cities feb. 29. iraq did not report any attack on tikrit
tikrit, on the tigris river about 100 miles north of baghdad, is home to ``most members of the ruling clique in baghdad,'' an islamic republic news agency dispatch said
other missiles on friday hit the northern iraqi cities of mosul and kirkuk, the latter an important oil center
six missiles pounded basra, iraq's second-largest city, while 24 other projectiles were lobbed into the southern towns of haretha, shubair, an industrial center just south of basra
the iraqi news agency reported seven missiles fired into tehran friday, raising to 30 the number of such attacks on the iranian capital since sunday. in all, baghdad says it has fired 101 missiles into tehran since the intercity dueling began feb. 29
the iranians also claimed they captured two towns friday in a five-day-old land offensive into northeast iraq in which they said 9,200 iraqis have been killed or wounded and 4,000 captured
they also said they recaptured the iranian border town of nowsud, held by the iraqis since the early days of the 7{-year-old war
the iraqi news agency has denied there was combat in that region, where most of iraq's 3.5 million kurds live
the iranian news agency reported five iraqi warplanes were shot down thursday and friday, but iraq confirmed only one jet downed
iraq claimed two iranian jets were shot down. iran denied the report
the iraqi agency said iraqi warplanes hit two ``large maritime targets,'' which usually means tankers, off iran's coast on thursday and friday
london-based lloyd's shipping intelligence unit confirmed only one _ on the 80,137-ton cypriot tanker kyrenicos
iranian gunboats attacked three neutral ships in the southern gulf friday
in one attack, a japanese seaman was killed aboard the panamanian liquified gas carrier maria ii in the first raid around midnight thursday, shipping officials said on condition of anonymity
gunboats later attacked the 284,494-ton norwegian tanker berge lord, starting a small fire, and the 87,768-ton singapore-flag tanker neptune saburu. no casualties were reported in either attack
radical students hurled several firebombs at a u.s. military facility in downtown seoul, police said today
police officials said the students tossed seven firebombs into a building inside the u.s. corps of engineers office friday night
the red brick building did not catch fire, but two windows were broken, the officials said
anti-u.s. sentiment is relatively high among college students who are critical of washington's pressure on south korea to open its domestic market, especially to products such as beef and fruits. accords</head>
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, winding up his six-day u.s. visit, said the best course for bringing peace to the middle east was charted in the 1978 camp david accords
in a speech friday to the los angeles world affairs council, shamir praised the accords signed by israel and egypt under u.s. auspices, although he opposed them 10 years ago as a member of israel's parliament, the knesset
as at camp david, shamir said, peace talks between israel and her arab neighbors must be conducted directly and on an equal footing
this approach is enshrined in the camp david accords, to which we remain committed,'' he said. ``they still provide a workable blueprint for resolving issues between us and our arab neighbors, including the palestinian arabs.''
during his visit, prime minister rebuffed a u.s. proposal for peace negotiations in the region, saying the proposal for an international conference would allow the soviet union ``to push a settlement favorable to themselves and their syrian clients.''
the u.s. proposal was an attempt to accommodate jordan's king hussein, who has refused to enter peace taks with israel except at an international conference
shamir, whose likud bloc is opposed to the notion of trading territory for peace because it feels this would leave the jewish state vulnerable to the arab goal of destroying the jewish state altogether, also dismissed criticism about israel's crackdown on palestinian rioting in the west bank and gaza. the violence in the territories captured by israel in the 1967 six-day war has left 101 people dead
despite the recent differences of opinion, shamir said, ``the basic relationship between israel and the united states is as close as ever, as strong as ever and as good as ever.''
during shamir's speech, about 250 arab-americans and their supporters waved palestinian flags and chanted slogans as they demonstrated outside the century plaza hotel. about 20 members of the militant jewish defense league staged a counter-demonstration outside the posh hotel, but there were no confrontations, violence or arrests, said police sgt. larry mckinley
shamir has sought to blunt criticism of his country's action in the territories by some american jews
he reiterated his view that the picture presented of the palestinian riots in the occupied west bank and gaza strip has been distorted by the media, and said americans shouldn't confuse the violence with u.s.-style civil rights activism
it is war. it is an extension of urban terrorism,'' he said, defending his troops' use of rubber bullets, beatings and live ammunition
shamir returns to israel tonight
a dispute within the amish community over whether their horse-drawn vehicles should carry orange safety reflectors has divided the normally close-knit society
some who object to the orange, saying displays of such bright colors are against their religion, are only willing to use a hand-cut black metal triangle outlined with white reflective tape to warn drivers of other vehicles
the sign rift runs so deeply that the so-called ``orange-sign'' and ``black-sign'' amish now maintain separate churches. orange-sign amish also have opened their homes and farms to tour groups; the black-sign amish have refused
the rift has led two families to leave the 60-family community in southeastern minnesota's fillmore county and move to michigan
they want their freedom,'' said jacob hershberger, a community elder whose daughter and son-in-law moved to michigan. ``i feel really bad some of our group broke away. but they were making trouble. if they hadn't made trouble with the orange signs, there wouldn't be this other trouble.''
state law requires the amish to display orange reflectors on the backs of their horse-drawn buggies and wagons at night and in fog, and to carry it in the vehicle at all other times
but hershberger and others object to the orange on religious grounds. those amish, if they use any sign at all, use the white-bordered black triangle, a device permissible only in the daytime, and not in fog
i look at it this way,'' said menno mast, 24, an amish furniture maker from mabel who has orange reflectors on his vehicles. ``if the black sign was legal, i'd be willing to use it. but instead of making trouble with you folks, i'd rather use red (orange)
i don't feel it's hard on my religion. i look at this: we have red barns, and red stuff in the house. i don't have much difficulty with that.''
a bill that would have allowed the amish to use their black signs at night failed to clear a legislative committee this week
hershberger said he'll refuse to pay any fines for violating the sign law, risking a jail sentence
one amish man spent a day in the fillmore county jail last fall for not paying his $22 fine
special u.s. presidential envoy philip habib arrived in the egyptian capital today to seek arab backing for an american plan for peace in the middle east
habib met for an hour with foreign minister esmat abdel-meguid. he told reporters afterward that he had briefed the egyptian about the status of the peace process but refused to give details
abdel-meguid said that cairo's position ``has been to encourage the united states to move for the peace process because we all in this region are in need of peace.''
an egyptian government source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said habib was to meet with president hosni mubarak on sunday before continuing his swing
mubarak has called the american plan ``encouraging'' but suggested, without specifics, that some of its provisions be elaborated
habib's tour will take him to jordan, saudi arabia and morocco, according to a washington announcement friday by state department spokesman charles redman
redman said one aim of habib's mission was to get views of leaders in the four countries about the peace plan presented this month by u.s. secretary of state george shultz during a regional tour. syria and palestinian leaders rejected the plan and jordan criticized it
redman said habib also will brief arab leaders on talks this week in washington between administration officials and israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who rejected key elements of the plan
we are looking for an early response to our proposals from the parties in the region,'' redman said
the u.s. peace plan calls for a united nations-sponsored international conference. that meeting would give way by may 1 to direct arab-israeli talks on a three-year transition period of self-rule for 1.5 million palestinians in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip
negotiations on the final status of the two territories, occupied by the israelis since the 1967 war, would be held in december
meanwhile, egyptian defense minister abdel-halim abu-ghazala flew to washington today for a 10-day visit to discuss egypt's arms requirements under a 9-year-old aid program. u.s. military aid to egypt averages $1.3 billion a year in a program that began after egypt signed a peace treaty with israel in 1979
a bus crashed into a parked truck on the panamerican highway, killing seven people, police said
the suburban bus carrying 35 passengers hit the rear of the truck 125 miles north of the port city of antofagasta on friday
the bus driver was one of the dead, police said. police also reported 15 people injured
four iranian men were being held in the shooting of three saudi arabian teachers, a newspaper reported today
the new nigerian newspaper, citing unidentified police sources, said the four were arrested at the nigerian telecommunications office here after they were seen making international telephone calls shortly after the shooting
the unidentified iranians were arrested and held for questioning, but they have not yet been directly linked to the shooting, the sources said
four saudi arabian teachers were fired upon by a gunman as they left the lagos eko hotel just after midnight on march 13. the car's driver was shot twice in the chest, a passenger was wounded once in the chest and a third was shot once in the back, police sources said. a fourth teacher was unhurt
the three wounded saudis were all arabic teachers attached to the saudi arabian embassy in lagos, said the new nigerian
police and saudi arabian embassy officials have declined comment on the shooting and arrests
a massive brain tumor killed a 30-year-old western lowland gorilla believed to be the oldest breeding male gorilla in captivity, say officials at the brookfield zoo
samson died thursday at the zoo in suburban chicago and an autopsy later revealed the presence of the brain tumor, said brookfield spokeswoman linda elbert
he had sired four offspring at brookfield, including an infant born a week ago. a fifth is expected from a recent mating, ms. elbert said
samson, star of brookfield's ``tropic world'' exhibit, had been in failing health for some time before an apparent stroke felled him tuesday, said dr. anne baker, curator of primates. she said the 30005-pound gorilla regained consciousness only twice before his death
we were a bit taken aback by his apparent stroke,'' ms. baker said. ``after tuesday we knew he was in a life-threatening situation, but we had not expected that we would lose him as soon as we did.''
she said samson had suffered from rheumatoid arthritis since 1980, and had been blind for about a month before his death
samson came to brookfield in 1980 from the buffalo zoological gardens in buffalo, n.y. ms. baker said he was captured in africa and arrived at the buffalo zoo in 1962
samson has left a lot of offspring here to continue the genetic pool of these creatures,'' ms. elbert said. ``he was a really, really beautiful animal.''
gorillas usually live 30 years to 40 years in captivity, she said, and the record in captivity is 53 years
a gunman whose bullet paralyzed a marathon runner in a freeway shooting last july has been sentenced to the maximum 10-year prison term
a rash of similar confrontations, including several in which victims were killed or injured, plagued southern california last summer. incidents have been reported sporadically since then
albert carroll morgan, 33, of huntington beach, who apologized for shooting paul gary nussbaum, was sentenced friday to seven years for shooting at an occupied vehicle and an additional three years for infliction of great bodily injury
morgan also was ordered to pay a maximum $10,000 to the victim restitution fund by orange county superior court judge jean rheinheimer
morgan shot nussbaum on july 18, 1987, while nussbaum was driving on the southbound costa mesa freeway during rush-hour traffic
nussbaum, 29, confined to a wheelchair, said he was satisfied with morgan's sentence
i feel that he should spend the rest of his life in prison,'' said nussbaum. ``but the judge did what she had to do. i'm really glad he got the maximum.''
a jury convicted morgan in february of the felony charges of voluntary manslaughter, assault with a firearm and shooting at an inhabited vehicle
in another case, jurors began deliberations friday in compton in the case of ronald elam, 28, who is charged with first-degree murder, two counts of attempted murder and two counts of assault with a deadly weapon in connection with an aug. 17, 1987, roadway shooting. british soldiers, details. picks up 5th graf, `officials at ...'</note>
a funeral crowd mourning the death of an ira guerrilla dragged two british soldiers from a car, beat them with crowbars and stripped them naked, witnesses said. minutes later they were shot to death
initial reports said the crowd believed the men were plainclothes detectives who were spying on the funeral for irish republican army member kevin brady, who was killed earlier in the week during another ira funeral
police later confirmed that the two men were plainclothes british soldiers
witnesses said the victims fired shots in the air in an unsuccessful attempt to extricate themselves from the crowd, but it overwelmed them
some witnesses said the soldiers were beaten and driven away in a taxi and their bodies, stripped naked, were found later at an abandoned lot
others said the soldiers were not driven away but stripped naked by the crowd, bundled unconscious onto a wall surrounding a soccer field and then dragged behind a building and shot
it was not clear whether the men were shot by mourners or by other assailants
officials of sinn fein, the legal political wing of the ira, said papers were found on the men identifying them as british army personnel. they said the men were killed with their own pistols
there were reports that a priest was seen trying to give one of the victims mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and being ordered away by the gunmen who then pumped more shots into the men
after the men were killed, witnesses said the cortege continued toward milltown cemetery with some people weeping and trembling as they walked
it was the second time in three days that funerals of ira members have been disrupted by violence. on thursday, a protestant gunman fired shots and tossed grenades into a crowd of mourners, killing three and wounding 68
brady was shot as he and other mourners chased the attacker. the enraged crowd finally grabbed 33-year-old michael stone when his gun jammed. they severely beat him before police caught up and took him into custody
stone is under armed guard in a hospital, being treated for the injuries he received at the hands of his pursuers. police have arrested a second person believed linked to the shooting
police said friday that stone will be formally charged next week with murder in connection with the cemetery attack and other unrelated serious crimes
press association said stone was being questioned about 10 sectarian killings unrelated to wednesday's attack
on friday, west belfast catholics buried two other victims of sectarian violence. one was 20-year-old thomas mcerlean, another of the three people killed in wednesday's attack at milltown cemetery
the other buried friday was charles mcgrillen, who was shot monday outside a belfast supermarket. the ulster freedom fighters, an outlawed protestant extremist group, claimed responsibility for killing him in a statement friday
the outlawed ira is fighting to drive the british from northern ireland. the mainly catholic guerrilla group wants to unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic under socialist rule
protestant militants reject unity with the irish republic
