the israeli army detained two american television crews for an hour today after they refused to leave the west bank city of ramallah when protests broke out, a crew member and a military spokesman said
scattered protests were reported in the west bank and gaza strip but there were no reports of shootings. hospital officials in gaza city said nine palestinians were admitted with beating injuries
prime mimister yitzhak shamir said he may let israel's coalition government collapse because of the rift over how to make peace with the arabs. shamir said he was thinking about calling for early elections
in an unusual move, soldiers in the west bank city of ramallah detained four foreign tv crews, including crews from the cbs and cnn networks, who refused to obey orders to leave the area
eli fastman, a cameraman for the london-based visnews, said the four crews had entered ramallah in violation of an army order and had stayed there ``to challenge this crazy system of closing us out of the territories.''
when protests broke out in ramallah's central square, fastman said, the cameramen were approached by troops and told to leave, but they refused
fastman said he and the two-man crews from cbs, cnn and the london-based worldwide television news were taken to a military police station in ramallah where they ``discussed the situation with army officials.'' the army filed no charges and released the crews an hour later, he said
an army spokesman confirmed the detentions but could provide no details. local area commanders in the west bank and gaza strip are empowered to close areas under their command at will
shamir, meanwhile, revealed friday that he was considering supporting early electons
the internal situation in the government could be the main reason for early elections,'' shamir told israel television's washington correspondent. ``i am thinking about it ... i do not rule out such a thing.''
troops killed two palestinians in the israeli-occupied territories on friday. the shootings brought to 102 the number of palestinians killed by u.n. count in anti-occupation violence since it began dec. 8. hospital officials said at least 25 protesters were wounded in scattered clashes
in cyprus, u.n. officials announced that more than 400 palestinian refugees had been injured in the occupied gaza strip this week, bringing the casualty toll for march to more than 900
troops killed a protester at the shati refugee camp in gaza during a clash with hundreds of worshipers after noon prayers at the camp's al-gharbi mosque, the army said
officials at gaza city's shifa hospital identified the victim as 24-year-old hani abu hamam. witnesses said his family smuggled the body out of the hospital for a burial service attended by about 100 angry mourners
in the occupied west bank, a soldier shot and killed a 19-year-old protester who attacked him at the ein beit ilmah camp near nablus, the army said. a spokeswoman said the protester had assaulted the soldier with ``a dangerous object,'' but she would not elaborate
officials at nablus' ittihad hospital identified the victim as muhamed mahmud suleiman khaled. jehad alawni, a nurse, said khaled bled to death from a bullet wound in the left thigh
also friday, two israeli civilians were detained for allegedly stockpiling an arsenal of weapons intended for anti-arab attacks, police said. investigators determined the two had acted alone and were not part of a larger ring, the daily haaretz said
a canadian engineer kidnapped last year by colombian guerrillas has been freed, police said today
richard paulson was released friday near beleen, a town in boyacaa state, and he came to bogota by bus, according to colombian police
the national liberation army, a group inspired by cuban leader fidel castro, had asked $20 million in ransom for the engineer's release. but it later reduced the amount to $6 million, said colombian journalist alonso heredia, correspondent for the el espectador newspaper
however, the journalist said he didn't know whether paulson's employer, occidental petroleum of los angeles, paid for his release
heredia himself was kidnapped tuesday and released friday by the same guerrilla group. he interviewed paulson during his captivity
paulson learned spanish during his 376 days with the guerrillas and received teaching in revolutionary objectives, said heredia
the canadian engineer was abducted in arauca march 8, 1987, with another employee of occidental, amanda uribe, who was released a few hours later with the ramson demand
paulson worked as production manager for the giant canno limon oil field along the venezuelan border
the national liberation army attacked the canno limon pipeline and the occidental installations about 50 times in last two years. its demolition squads halted the exports of 180,000 barrels per day during the month of january
the guerrilla group, the most active in colombia, has vowed to expel foreign oil companies working in joint ventures with the state-owned company ecopetrol
federal regulators are reassuring nervous depositors in the california-based financial corp. of america that they won't lose money in any government action against the troubled holding company
the federal home loan bank board said friday it would protect all depositors and general creditors of american savings &amp; loan association, fca's main subsidiary. normally deposit accounts are only insured up to $100,000
the irvine-based fca, with $33.7 billion in assets, is the nation's second-largest thrift holding company and the biggest problem for the bank board, which regulates 3,150 savings institutions
the pledge of support came after the company, in a report filed with the securities and exchange commission, said for the first time that american, based in stockton, was insolvent under generally accepted accounting principles
karl hoyle, a bank board spokesman, said the statement was made in part to stem the drain of deposits at american. the bank board also reaffirmed its support for the management of both the s&amp;l and its parent
fca said american's net worth _ the difference between assets and liabilities _ had fallen to negative $106 million at the end of the year, compared with positive $244.4 million on sept. 30
under less stringent regulatory accounting guidelines, american's net worth was plus $69 million at the end of 1987, compared with $357.8 million at the end of the third quarter
fca had previously revealed that its net worth had fallen into the red, but this is the first disclosure that net worth at american has fallen below the zero mark. that happened when american concluded that repayment of debts due from its parent company were not assured
fca's annual report, filed with the sec, also revealed that depositors withdrew $493 million during the first two months of this year. deposits had totaled $17.1 billion at the end of 1987
the company attributed the drain to publicity about the bank's problems and said it eased during the first 10 days of march
the drain was milder than the severe run at american in august and september of 1984, when the bank lost about $6.8 billion of its $25 billion in deposits
the bank board's sister agency for commercial banks, the federal deposit insurance corp., issued a similar promise on thursday protecting all depositors and general creditors of first republicbank corp. of dallas, a bank holding company of about the same size as fca
however, the fdic went a step further than the bank board by pumping $1 billion into first republicbank
fca on feb. 23 asked for $1.5 billion in assistance as soon as possible from the federal deposit insurance corp., the bank board unit that guarantees deposits. hoyle said the request is under review
the largest-ever government bailout of a banking company was the $4.5 billion rescue in 1984 of continental illinois corp
the bank board has tried unsuccessfully for nearly a year to find another institution willing to take over all or part of fca on terms that wouldn't be too costly. on-again, off-again talks with the thrift unit of ford motor co. broke down early in january
on jan. 27, fca reported a loss of $224.6 million in the last three months of last year, bringing its 1987 loss to $468 million
two weeks later, the bank board ordered it to sell $2.5 billion in mortgage-backed securities to reduce its vulnerability to interest rate fluctuations
on march 9, the bank board passed a resolution reassuring nervous wall street firms, which had lent more than $12 billion to american in the form of reverse repurchase agreements
ranked by assets, fca is second among thrift holding companies to h.f. ahmanson &amp; co., the los angeles-based parent of home savings of america
calm has settled over plymouth-canton high school following two days of fights between ``jocks'' and ``burnouts'' in a turf battle that some students say has overtones of discrimination
louise gates, a spokeswoman at the suburban detroit school, said there was one minor scuffle friday lasting about 10 minutes, but order was restored quickly. large-scale fist fights rocked the school wednesday and thursday
everything was pretty calm, maybe we've seen the end of the disturbances,'' said a public safety officer, who declined to give her name
fights between the student-athletes and the so-called burnouts, who students say are distinguished by their leather jackets and concert t-shirts, erupted around noon wednesday
administrators said the fighting began over the use of a popular hallway gathering place known as ``the pit.''
there were no injuries, but at least 12 students were suspended and school officials sealed off the hallway, officials said
about 20 police officers were called to restore order thursday. police declined to say how many officers were at the school friday
some students said administrators over-reacted to the fights
the amount of police that they brought in was outrageous. it gave the kids a reason to keep going,'' said student reeder singler
the fighting is not really over turf, ... it's over discrimination of one group over another,'' singler said. the burnouts feel the jocks receive preferential treatment by some administrators and faculty, he said
on thursday, the burnouts sent school principal thomas tattan a note that said: ``we feel we should be treated with the same courtesy as other peer and social groups. we believe you're taking the jocks' side over the pit issue.''
the burnouts and the jocks met friday among themselves but the meeting broke up when administrators tried to join in the discussions, singler said
gates said administrators talked to both sides, but declined to reveal what was discussed. france, minor editing for style thruout.</note>
the government controlled by gen. manuel antonio noriega declared a state of emergency that suspended civil liberties but gave the state powers to reopen banks and stores closed by a cash crisis
also friday, deputy assistant secretary of state william walker arrived to negotiate the departure of noriega. in washington, a white house official said that if noriega flees, the united states will not seek his extradition to answer drug trafficking charges
the general's opponents responded to the emergency decree by calling for an indefinite general strike starting monday
the economy already is reeling from walkouts that intensified this week and u.s. sanctions _ all part of an increasingly violent campaign to drive noriega from power
under the ``state of urgency'' declared by acting president manuel solis palma, the government can suspend basic civil and property rights
a government statement announcing the move blamed the nation's economic chaos on the u.s.-backed freeze of its international bank accounts and the opposition campaign: ``there is a real undeclared war against the republic of panama.''
solis palma was named to succeed eric arturo delvalle, who was ousted feb. 26 by pro-noriega legislators and went into hiding after he tried to fire the general, who heads panama's 15,000-strong defense forces
the united states recognizes delvalle as panama's legitimate president and said noriega must go after he was indicted by a federal grand jury last month on charges of trafficking in colombian cocaine
just hours after the emergency decree was issued on friday, troops broke into a radio station owned by opposition national assemblyman francisco artola, arresting 12 people, artola said
he said those arrested, including members of the opposition umbrella group national civic crusade, were on the air discussing a strike against a subsidiary of united brands co. in the town of changuinola
this man must go,'' artola said of noriega. ``the country must democratize.''
in a late evening news conference, crusade leader aurelio barria said another general strike was being called ``to put a halt to the catastrophic national situation.''
asked about the negotiations aimed at facilitating noriega's departure, barria would say only that the crusade had been approached by an noriega intermediary. but he said his group refuses to deal with the general or any of his representatives
friday's decree allows the government to suspend virtually all civil rights, from freedom of speech and assembly to habeas corpus
also subject to controls is the right to private property. an explanation accompanying the decree took special aim at the scarcity of cash in the economy, signaling the possibility the government would force the nation's 118 local and foreign-owned banks to reopen
the banks were closed by the government march 3. since then, they have resisted government pressures to reopen, fearing a panic run on their deposits
the united states has frozen panamanian deposits in u.s. banks, leaving the government and many private companies without the money to pay their employees. panama's official currency is the u.s. dollar
strikes have spread throughout the country in the past two weeks, forcing the military to take direct control of many public services to keep panama functioning
dock workers in colon and panama city maintained their strike friday, demanding full pay before going back to work. many government employees have accepted half pay or a flat $75 a week, but dock workers union leader luis asprilla said his membership was standing firm
in washington, sources in the reagan administration said walker went to panama to discuss possible terms for noriega's departure
one official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said walker would tell noriega the united states will not seek his extradition on drug trafficking charges if he seeks asylum in a third country
noriega says he is innocent of all charges
spanish prime minister felipe gonzalez said today that noriega could be granted asylum in spain or france to aid in bringing an end to the panamanian political crisis
gonzalez spoke to reporters at coto de donana on spain's southern atlantic coast before the start of a six-hour private meeting with french president francois mitterrand. the french leader did not speak to reporters
strikes by ferry workers crippled weekend travel between britain and france on saturday, jamming ports on both sides of the english channel with long lines of cars, buses and trucks
the dover port authority said separate strikes had reduced sailings to the european continent by 75 percent. it advised casual travelers to stay away
ferries staffed by belgian crews and traveling from dover to belgium were departing normally, but only one passenger ferry still was sailing to france, the port authority said
early saturday, there were about 250 cars and 100 buses waiting inside the docks at dover, but the pressure was relieved when some of the cars were ferried to nearby folkestone to cross the english channel to boulogne, france
about 400 freight trucks also were jammed inside the dover dock, and 240 others lined up along a cordoned section of the expressway leading into the port city
it's a pretty desperate situation,'' said a port official, speaking on condition of anonymity
the dover harbor board said travelers to the continent might have to wait up 36 hours to make the crossing
about 2,200 employees of p and o european ferries went on strike six weeks ago to protest the company's plan to cut 400 jobs and change work conditions
on thursday, french crews of the british-french consortium sealink-sncf walked off the job on both sides of the channel in a separate protest over work practices
french workers are striking against a reduction in wages and an increase in working hours
port officials in france, speaking on condition of anonymity, said some truck drivers who had been waiting for more than 72 hours to cross temporarily abandoned their vehicles at calais
crews of three french ferries were on strike in calais. the only ferry making the crossing to dover, england, was the saint anselm, run by british sealink
departures continued from cherbourg to poole, england and from ouistreham
in dieppe, the car-ferry le chartre had blocked the vehicle access ramp to all ferries since thursday, according to port authorities. ferry captain gerard delaunay has refused to allow another ferry, the versailles, to take on cars for the crossing to newhaven, england
heavy wind and rain lashed the bangladesh capital of dhaka, flattening houses, uprooting trees and plunging the city of 4 million into darkness, police said saturday
at least 100 people were reported injured in the storm, which hit late friday, hospital officials said. doctors said that 10 people were in critical condition
police said the storm, with winds as high as 36 mph, ripped through the city. hardest hit were suburban areas, where mud and straw huts collapsed, they said
efforts were under way to restore electricity and telephone services
vice president george bush says it is too early to discuss dropping the drug indictments against panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega. jesse jackson says he favors a guarantee of no extradition if that will speed up his departure
other presidential candidates, in reponse to a survey by the associated press, voiced support for u.s. efforts to force noriega to step down and end the crisis in panama
several democrats faulted the reagan administration for not acting sooner
pat robertson, a republican hopeful and former television evangelist, said, ``under no circumstances should a deal be made whereby drug charges are dropped.''
the ap asked the candidates last tuesday if the united states should impose a trade embargo on panama to force noriega out, if it should drop drug charges against noriega if that would hurry his departure, and if there were conditions under which they would annul the treaty giving panama eventual control of the canal
all the candidates except sen. bob dole, r-kan., responded by friday
only robertson suggested the crisis was grounds for changing the treaty
in light of the uncertainties and volatility of the situation in panama, i believe the u.s. should reconsider transferring control of the canal,'' robertson said
however, bush said: ``we signed the treaty in good faith. the canal is operating smoothly and we expect it to continue to operate smoothly. we fully expect panama to live up to its treaty commitments.''
bush called the u.s. drug charges against noriega ``a matter for the judiciary and it is premature to discuss dropping indictments.''
on a trade embargo, the vice president said: ``noriega should go and will go and the united states government is listening to the panamanian people and the legitimate government of panama. we hope this internal problem will soon be resolved.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis said he supports sanctions, ``but i don't believe that a trade embargo is necessary or appropriate at this time.''
before we consider any action that would affect the criminal proceedings against noriega, it is essential that the american people be given a full accounting of the past relationship between gen. noriega and agencies and officials of the u.s. government,'' dukakis said
jackson said, ``drugs are our no. 1 national security issue. apparently, gen. noriega is deeply involved in the international drug trade. therefore it is justified to use diplomatic and economic pressure to push him out.''
but jackson added the united states should be acting in concert ``with our friends in the region'' and the organization of american states. ``when we act unilaterally, we fan the flame of nationalism and undermine our effectiveness,'' he said
the administration's recent moves are to be supported, but we lack moral authority, which undermines our diplomatic and economic actions, because the administration failed to respond quickly and forcefully when it first learned of noriega's involvement in drug traffic,'' jackson said. ``our weak policy has put the u.s. in another crisis in central america.''
it is in our interest and that of the panamanians to settle the crisis with noriega as quickly as possible. if that means granting noriega a guarantee of no-extradition, then it should be granted,'' jackson said
sen. paul simon, d-ill., said, ``i support the economic steps taken last week against noriega. the pressure must be kept on noriega so that he quickly steps aside and allows president delvalle to take over. if that happens, the u.s.-panama relationship will greatly improve, barring other revelations about panamanian drug dealings.''
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., said, ``supporting dictators does not serve our interests. the lesson of the shah and somoza, and before them batista, and diem, is that by sticking with dictators, the united states sets the stage for the outcome we fear the most.''
the days of the united states deciding who governs panama are over. we are not going back to the days before the panama canal treaty,'' gephardt said. ``the days of military dictatorship in panama are also over. gen. noriega does not understand that history has passed him by.''
gephardt ruled out dropping the drug indictments, saying, ``the united states is a nation of laws. the rule of law cannot be subordinated to political expediency.''
sen. albert gore jr., d-tenn., said through spokesman arlie schardt that he supports a trade embargo and the possibility of dropping the drug charges if that would speed up noriega's departure
gore's spokesman added that it was hard to envision circumstances that would justify annuling the treaty
a team of u.n. observers will visit nicaragua as soon as possible to investigate the tense border situation with honduras, a u.n. spokesman said saturday
mahbub ahmad said secretary-general javier perez de cuellar decided to send the team at nicaragua's request. he said it would include one poliitical officer from u.n. headquarters and a still-undecided number of military observers
diplomatic sources said the team was likely to inclkude two military observers and probably would leave tuesday. the observers have not been named
the announcement followed a security council meeting friday night during which nicaragua, honduras and the united states traded allegations over whether sandinista troops are in honduran territory and who is responsible for the current conflict
several latin american speakers endorsed nicaragua's call for a neutral u.n. observer mission to visit the site of the border clashes
ahmad said there are no immediate plans to visit the honduran side of the border. sources said no request had come from honduras
nicaragua has requested a joint mission by the u.n. and the organization of american states to investigate the border situation and make recommendasntions on preventing further conflict
honduras and the united states contend that nicarguan troops have attacked contra bases in honduras. nicaragua has denied the claim
honduras has responded by attacking nicaraguan forces around the border area. situation unchanged this morning.</note>
authorities evacuated 2,000 people after firefighters were unable to extinguish a burning gas container that threatened surrounding cylinders in a plant rocked by a fatal blast the day before
the cylinder was found earlier friday amid the ruins of the gollob analytical services chemical plant, where the explosion and fire thursday killed three men
it's just a waiting game right now,'' james staples, a spokesman for the state department of environmental protection, said friday night. ``the slightest vibration could cause that cylinder to turn into a fireball.''
the cylinder was still a threat this morning, he said, and people remained away from their homes
authorities ordered the evacuation in a half-mile area surrounding the plant out of concern that the flames would ignite surrounding cylinders containing unknown gases
nursing home patients were evacuated from the nearby berkeley heights convalescence center on stretchers at about 8 p.m. and residents from some 400 nearby homes also were ordered to leave as a precaution, said deputy mayor albert boyance
officials said some of the residents were staying with relatives while others went to a nearby high school
the new jersey transit authority discontinued passenger rail service near the plant until at least sunday. passengers were to be shuttled by bus
staples said the flaming cylinder contained phosphine and hydrogen. authorities were planning to wait until all the gas burned before attempting to move the cylinder
investigators said the plant burst into flames thursday after another cylinder exploded outside the plant and became a projectile, shooting into the building. authorities were investigating whether mislabeling or a contaminated gas may have been the cause
a delivery man who was severely injured remained hospitalized in fair condition friday. he had a leg amputated and suffered shrapnel wounds in the blast, said doris ortiz, a spokeswoman for university hospital in newark
the evacuation followed a smaller evacuation earlier friday of an industrial area around the plant, said police capt. michael borsos
state environmental officials said authorities cleared the area at lunchtime as a precaution since workers were preparing to remove gas cylinders from the building and were not sure what they contained. detail.</note>
the red cross said today that blood that slipped through procedures against aids contamination was not actually contaminated with the virus or posed no known health hazard
twenty-four questionable units of blood were erroneously shipped last month from red cross centers in washington and nashville, tenn., to hospitals for use but were never given to any patients, according to the food and drug administration
while it should not have been shipped, it actually proved to be hiv (aids virus) free, and a number of units underwent processing that would inactivate the virus,'' said gene jeffers, american red cross spokesman
he said there was ``no known health hazard associated with the 24 units of blood. we were very fortunate and lucked out in that there was no human risk at all involved here.''
however, he conceded when questioned that five of the units tested positive for hepatitis b antigens and would have posed a health risk had they been used in transfusions. however, they were not used, he said
ten of the units initially tested positive for hiv antibodies but they underwent fractionation, which eliminated the danger of any contamination, jeffers said. fractionation breaks the blood down into components for specific uses
the remaining nine units were from donors who were unacceptable because they previously tested ``false positive,'' but all the actual units were tested safe, he said
the washington post reported today that federal officials recovered the 24 units, each consisting of one pint, and were ``virtually certain'' all the questionable blood had been destroyed or quarantined
none of the blood was transfused, and we were out of the gate in a hurry, but of course it's a worrisome event,'' dr. frank e. young, commissioner of the food and drug administration, told the post
two senior officials of the washington regional office of the american red cross _ john mcgraw and frederick darr _ have been suspended with pay for 30 days pending an investigation of their actions
the purpose of the suspension is to permit us to assign someone to make recommendations'' said richard schubert, president of the american red cross. ``then we will decide what to do. we are not in a position yet to take disciplinary action.''
schubert said no officials in the nashville center had been disciplined, but that the investigation there was continuing
six of the questionable units of blood were from the washington center and the other 18 were from nashville
the mistakes in washington were detected after the chapter found discrepancies during a routine audit and then contacted the fda, which conducted a more complete investigation. the tennessee errors were detected when the fda began an audit after a woman sued local blood bank officials because she became infected with the aids virus through a previous blood transfusion
as a result of the errors, the fda said it has increased its periodic audits of the blood supply and instituted new training procedures for blood bank employees
an ongoing investigation by fda at the two blood centers has revealed that standard operating procedures were not followed in handling these blood products,'' the public health service said in a statement
the fda and the red cross are continuing to investigate the issue and monitor the recall to ensure that all suspect units of blood products are identified and that appropriate follow-up action taken,'' the service said
dr. s. gerald sandler, associate vice president of the american red cross, said that in 1987, more than 37 million tests were conducted on the 6 million units of blood donated, which placed increased demands on laboratory workers
we are seriously concerned about this, and we are implementing additional efforts to help reduce potential human errors,'' sandler said. comments</note>
lt. col. oliver north says he's retiring from the marine corps because he may have to subpoena ``the highest ranking officials in our government'' to defend himself against charges in the iran-contra affair
north, making a brief appearance friday at the office of attorney brendan sullivan, said sullivan had informed him ``that the defense against these charges may require him to issue subpoenas for the testimony and records of the highest ranking officials in our government.''
that strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my continued service as a marine officer,'' north said. ``accordingly, with great sadness, i have tendered my request to retire from the marine corps.''
white house chief of staff howard h. baker jr., in an interview taped friday for the syndicated television program, ``john mclaughlin's one on one,'' declined to say how president reagan would respond if subpoenaed
we haven't had to face that yet,'' baker, who is a lawyer, said. he recalled that former president ford was subpoenaed in the case of squeaky fromme, who was convicted in an attempt on his life. ford videotaped a deposition
asked whether this was what reagan would do, baker said, ``the president undoubtedly will cooperate with both the prosecution and the defense. now, how that translates into actual conduct remains to be seen. we have to face that issue when it arrives.''
north, who wore a civilian business suit in place of his usual ribbon-bedecked marine uniform, refused to answer questions after reading the statement
but pentagon sources said north, 44, had submitted his request on thursday, asking that he be allowed to retire effective may 1 when he will have completed 20 years of active military service
the request already has been approved by gen. alfred m. gray, the commandant of the marine corps, and is expected to receive ``routine'' approval monday from the office of the navy secretary, the sources added
twenty years is the minimum amount of service required to retire from the military with a pension. with 20 years of service, north is entitled to a pension totaling 50 percent of his base monthly pay, or slightly over $22,000 a year
the pentagon sources said north also had requested approval to begin terminal leave, meaning he wants to use accumulated leave benefits to stop working at his military post now instead of waiting until may 1
that also should be approved routinely,'' said one source
north was reassigned to marine corps headquarters on the planning staff in november 1986 after president reagan fired him as an aide to the national security council
north will become the second major figure in the iran-contra scandal to retire from active military duty. rear adm. john poindexter, president reagan's former national security adviser and north's boss, exercised his right to retire from the navy late last year
north, poindexter and two others were indicted by a federal grand jury wednesday on charges they conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
the 23-count indictment, which also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim, said the defendants organized, directed and concealed ``a program to continue funding of and logistical and other support for military and paramilitary operations in nicaragua by the contras'' at a time u.s. law barred such action
after the indictment was returned, north vowed to fight the charges, declaring: ``i did not commit any crime.''
north, a much-decorated combat veteran of vietnam and graduate of the u.s. naval academy, testified last year before congress that he always believed he had the approval of his superiors to take the actions he did
poindexter, during his testimony before congress, said he never informed the president of his decision to divert arms sale profits to the contras
according to the defense department, the pension rights of north and poindexter are unlikely to be affected by the outcome of the legal cases against them since both men served honorably for at least 20 years
generally speaking, a conviction does not affect eligibility for a military pension,'' said col. david shea, a pentagon spokesman
well-wishers waved good-bye saturday to about 75 people who boarded a ``citizens' train'' bound for washington, d.c., where they intend to lobby for new national budget priorities
they will ask lawmakers to spend less for weapons and more for improved housing, health care, education and care for the environment
several dozen people held a rally friday, carrying signs with messages such as: ``citizens' budget _ more for children, less for weapons.''
about 75 people from washington, 175 more from oregon, 20 from california and a few from other western states planned to board trains this weekend and meet in chicago on monday. the travelers then will board a train later that day bound for washington, d.c
while on board, riders will attend workshops on lobbying strategies, the federal budget process, education, health care and the constitution. they'll be met by supporters at stops along the way
they'll arrive tuesday in washington, where they plan to rally on the capitol steps and be greeted by astronomer carl sagan. then they'll scurry in different directions to try to meet with congressmen, interest groups, peace lobbies and coalition leaders
virginia day, a peace activist and mother of five, is taking her two youngest children, aged 9 months and 5 years, on the train with her
i want to make sure they have a safe world,'' ms. day said. she plans to focus on the act for better child care, which would provide more day care services
our government forgot that real security isn't based on military might,'' ms. day said. ``it's based on a healthy population that's well-educated, well-nourished, fully employed, psychologically healthy and living in a clean environment.''
the citizens' train plan was hatched by four women in oregon two years ago, who hope the campaign will impress american leaders
independent counsel lawrence e. walsh took a riverboat gamble by steering a federal grand jury to a catch-all indictment which includes charges that connote greed by the four major iran-contra principals, legal experts say
former prosecutors, interviewed by the associated press, said the strategy may open a line of testimony that could draw out sympathy for the defendants _ especially lt. col. oliver l. north
for instance, north was accused of accepting an illegal gratuity _ a $13,800 home security system _ from his key operative in the iran-contra affair, richard v. secord
by including that particular charge, the experts said, the door is open for north to repeat congressional testimony that he was threatened by international terrorists including abu nidal
defendants in the broad conspiracy indictment handed down last week are north, a former national security council aide; his onetime boss, former national security adviser john m. poindexter; secord, a retired air force major general; and his business partner, albert hakim
most of the 23 counts focus on the broad conspiracy to aid the nicaraguan contras when such assistance was banned, and attempts to cover up the activities
but several counts allege motives of personal gain by north and the secord-hakim enterprise _ which carried out the logistics of aiding the nicaraguan contras and secret sale of u.s. arms to iran
there are charges that north received the illegal gratuity of a death benefit education fund for his children; that he used contra traveler's checks for personal purchases, and that the secord-hakim enterprise made enormous profits
north has already testified under congressional immunity that he made a bad mistake when he accepted the home security system as a gift, then tried to cover up the gratuity. but he said he was motivated by fears for his family in the wake of threats against him by terrorists, including nidal. his explanation before the iran-contra congressional committees won sympathy from many americans who watched the proceedings live on television
that charge opened up the ability of north to admit all kinds of evidence on terrorist groups around the world,'' said joseph digenova, until recently the u.s. attorney for the district of columbia and now a private attorney
he said it would open ``a pandora's box of national security information. it may not show venality, but instead a legitimate concern for north and his family.''
at the congressional hearings, north also disavowed knowledge of the $200,000 death benefit fund set up for his family with money from the u.s. arms sales to iran
he apologized for trying to cover up acceptance of the security system, saying, it ``was probably the grossest misjudgment i have made in my life.'' in cashing the traveler's checks for personal items, north said he was reimbursing himself for money he paid out of his own pocket for covert activities when a special fund ran dry
the experts said walsh likely has anticipated that the defendants will wrap themselves in a cloak of patriotism, and contend they were following legitimate orders from top government officials. they speculated walsh used the allegations of greedy motives in an attempt to overcome that defense
it's much easier to persuade a jury to convict somebody who has been advancing his personal interest, which could mean political interest, at the expense of other people or the national treasury,'' said philip hyman, a harvard professor and former chief of the justice department's criminal division
you can show you're not dealing simply with misguided patriots, that these are also men now receiving some personal benefits along the way, wheeling and dealing in a way that gives them a great deal of pleasure.''
but philip lacovara, a former watergate prosecutor, agreed that ``some of these charges give a very clear platform for north in particular to emphasize the sympathetic role he will portray to the jury as one of leaders in america's fight against world terrorism
he will explain the security fence as a wholly justifiable attempt to protect his family while he was on the front line protecting america against forces of evil,'' lacovara said
lacovara said ``one of issues i'm sure the defense will raise will be demands for production of highly classified information. this is the age-old question of `graymail' _ a demand for classified information to prevent the prosecution from proceeding with the case because risks to national security might be unwise.''
a federal law establishes courtroom procedures that look for alternative ways of conveying the information, but a judge could order it released in open court if he deems it essential to protect a defendant's rights. this leaves the prosecution with the dilemma of whether to proceed, and can tie the case in knots
another former watergate prosecutor, richard ben-veniste, said the 101-page indictment _ combining charges of personal gain with difficult issues like separation of powers _ could be too complicated for jurors
my own philosophy was to be as streamlined and direct as possible,'' he said. ``this indictment looks to me a little more of the kitchen sink philosophy.''
it is a directive for discipline from nepal's monarch, one of the many edicts written on red-and-yellow signs and sprinkled throughout katmandu. ``speak the truth, perform your dharma, do not fall from self-studies,'' it says
the dharma _ or cosmic order _ remains largely undisturbed in nepal. tourists still spend money, foreign aid rolls in, and criticism of king birendra remains taboo
rarely is the harmony upset. in the past few months, the only public dissent has been an unsuccessful call for a general strike and criticism from a handful of outspoken officials who later were suspended from their jobs
but something is amiss amid the majesty of nepal's mountains. half the 17 million residents live in poverty, only 2 percent have sanitary sewage disposal and more than 70 percent are without safe drinking water
a nepalese born today has an average life expectancy of 47 years
some blame lack of progress on meager resources. some blame the country's unusual government, under which political parties are banned
but not even massive foreign aid _ $500 million this year _ makes much dent in nepal's troubles
not all the statistics are depressing. life expectancy at birth is up from 38 years in 1960. some 70,000 nepalese students are in college. tourism grew 23 percent last year, to 223,000 visitors
but the population is expected to jump to 24 million by the year 2000, and food production can't match it. world bank figures show nepal's farms met all demands for food in 1960 but now meet only 86 percent of the nation's needs
despite efforts to add jobs, one-fifth of the people have 60 percent of the private income. the bottom fifth has less than 5 percent. per capita annual income is $160
harkha gurung, a former cabinet minister, said only about 60 percent of foreign aid that is offered can actually be used because much of the population lives in the so-called middle hills, which are largely inaccessible
shortage of food and surplus of population has always been a problem in the middle hills,'' gurung said. ``now they have reached a saturation point. they can't support any more people.''
gurung, educated as a geographer, said nepal's landlocked position between india and china also blocks development. the country's best untapped resource is hydroelectricity from its rivers, but the only possible customer is its huge southern neighbor, india
india also has come to dominate nepal's two growth industries, tourism and garment making. one foreign observer said indians ``either own or control much of the cash economy'' of the country
but no one doubts the authority of the king
in nepal, the king is advised by the rastriya panchayat, or non-partisan parliament. political parties were outlawed in 1961. the parliament has 112 elected members and 28 appointed by the king, with the prime minister chosen by the members
nav raj subedi, the panchayat chairman, noted no king has found it necessary to veto a law passed by parliament. he insisted dissent was welcome, but added that criticizing the partyless system was not allowed
of the dozen officials suspended last year, one was a member of parliament who demanded a return of political parties and 11 others were local officials who boycotted national day ceremonies last december
a strike against the suspensions was called in january by the outlawed nepalese congress party, but party officials say the action flopped when 250 organizers were arrested. they were later freed
the punishment can be more severe. a report last november by the human rights organization amnesty international said up to 100 political prisoners are in jail at any given time, with some kept tied or caged as a means of torture
even more staunchly forbidden is criticism of the king. one leader in an outlawed party railed against nepal's political system, but turned suddenly thoughtful when asked about the monarch
our law says we can't speak anything against the king, so we don't say anything against the king,'' he said
sikh militants saturday sneaked into an indian farmhouse and killed five members of a sikh family as they slept, including a 2-year-old girl, police said
the killings brought to 16 the number of people believed killed by sikh extremists during the past two days in india's northern punjab state, police and news reports said
at least 13 of the victims were sikhs. this year, 486 killings have been blamed on sikh militants fighting for a separate homeland in punjab
balbir singh, a farmer, and four members of his family were shot and killed early saturday at butt village 17 miles north of the sikh holy city of amritsar, police said
the other victims were his wife, son, daughter-in-law and 2-year-old granddaughter. izhar alam, amritsar district police chief, said the victims were killed as they slept
the motive for the killings was not known, but the militants have in the past killed fellow sikhs who do not support their separatist campaign
the united news of india said at least six other sikhs were killed in the district on friday night. three farmers were shot and killed in separate attacks and the bodies of three sikhs were found at manda village
two unidentified bodies were found in nearby janti village, the news agency said
the body of a factory guard was found at bawa village, also in amritsar district
in neighboring jalandhar district, a farmer, amrik singh, was shot and killed friday night, uni said. a sikh woman, identified as gurdial kaur, was killed friday when militants opened fire at a gathering in ludhiana district in central punjab, the news agency said
at least 1,000 people were killed last year in the separatist camapign, which has gone on four years. sikhs form just 2 percent of india's 800 million people but comprise a majority in punjab state
the militants claim that sikhs are discriminated against by the majority hindu community, who form 80 percent of india's population
president li xiannian on saturday accused the dalai lama, exiled spiritual leader of tibetan buddhists, of trying to undermine the national unity of china
we have respect for the dalai lama, but he does not respect china, his motherland,'' li told a delegation from the nepalese parliament. ``he is actually trying to split the country up.''
li's remarks, carried by the official xinhua news agency, were among the first by a senior chinese official criticizing the dalai lama following bloody anti-chinese riots in the tibetan capital of lhasa on march 5
the xinhua report did not say whether li directly linked the dalai lama, who lives in exile in northern india, to the riots. china blamed followers of the dalai lama for instigating similar pro-independence disturbances in lhasa last september and october
li told the nepalese visitors that the principle of unity rather than ``crude tactics'' must be used to settle problems concerning religion or nationality
the crude and leftist policies formulated during the cultural revolution have long since been corrected. the central authorities have adopted a policy of unity and mutual help. another important principle is that the more than 50 nationalities in china should be united,'' he said
during the 1966-76 cultural revolution, leftists destroyed tibetan temples and suppressed the languages and customs of tibetans and other minority groups. although beijing has tried to make amends by restoring temples and promoting local autonomy, resentment against the chinese remains strong
the dalai lama fled to india with about 100,000 followers after an unsuccessful uprising against chinese troops in 1959. he is still widely revered in tibet
china says one policeman was killed during the march 5 riots, which were led by monks shouting slogans in support of the dalai lama and independence. unconfirmed reports from western travelers in lhasa have put the death toll much higher, with one traveler quoting tibetans as saying 21 tibetans and three police died in the clash
there have also been widespread reports of mass arrests, but china's official media have given no figures
the dalai lama, following the march 5 disturbances, issued a statement praising the courage of tibetans who stood up to chinese rule and said that ``even in the face of mounting tibetan resentment the chinese leadership still fails to understand the true aspirations of the tibetan people.''
he also appealed to tibetans to restrain from violence
li thanked the nepalese delegation for making it possible for 10,000 tibetans to live in nepal, and nepalese parliament chairman navraj subedi said the nepalese government will never allow those tibetans to do anything harmful to china, xinhua reported
at their first encounter, soviet defense minister dmitri yazov reminded the senior pentagon officials he met last week of a giant kodiak bear _ big, rough and gruff, with distinctive russian features
he's a real ground-thumper, a real soviet infantry officer,'' one senior u.s. official said after defense secretary frank carlucci and his aides dined with yazov. ``he seemed a little ill at ease, not exactly cut out for this type of diplomacy.''
but that view of yazov changed wednesday, during the first business meeting ever conducted between the defense secretaries of the superpowers. it was held in a small conference room at the u.s. embassy in the swiss capital of bern
yazov, 64, showed the americans why kremlin leader mikhail gorbachev summoned the four-star general back from his command assignment in the far east last may and appointed him defense minister him over the heads of more senior candidates
yazov appears committed to the task of convincing a skeptical soviet officer corps of the need for economic reforms. soviet advocates argue reforms may cut defense spending at first, but could lead to technological progress that will ultimately benefit the red army
they are desperate for `detente 2,''' said a u.s. official, explaining the soviet rationale for the yazov-carlucci meeting. ``so they they trotted out their big, burly defense minister and said, `look. he's a teddy bear.' they wanted to convince us that they are benign.''
yazov, wearing a business suit instead of his uniform, broke the ice by noting how small the room was and recalling a russian saying that, ``although we have close quarters, we shouldn't quarrel.''
everyone got a laugh out of that,'' said pentagon spokesman dan howard. and although the talks weaved through a minefield of explosive east-west issues, they remained, in carlucci's words, ``cordial and businesslike.''
yazov delivered major statements from notes, but for the most part spoke off the cuff, competently arguing the kremlin position on doctrine, force levels and tricky regional issues such as afghanistan and nicaragua. he had the ability to defuse tense moments with humor, when it suited him. or start an argument, when he wanted
on wednesday afternoon, said a u.s. offical, yazov ``pulled out a map showing u.s. bases and fleets, and said, `you see how the united states has us surrounded.'''
carlucci responded by ``referring to cuba and nicaragua, and said, `you have got a beachhead yourselves,'' said a senior pentagon official, who like others interviewed, spoke on condition of anonymity
the three-day session was valuable for u.s. analysts. american policymakers had already gotten a picture of yazov based on his meetings with the u.s. ambassador to moscow, jack matlock. the americans who met yazov were particularly interested in the aides he brought with him
we have never seen most of these guys before,'' except for col. gen. nikolai chervov, the top soviet military spokesmen on arms control, said a veteran american on the team
the americans included defense and state department kremlin-watchers as well as the top white house adviser on soviet affairs, former senior cia analyst fritz ermath
carlucci and yazov did 90 percent of the talking, but they appeared to make little headway in resolving such fundamental disputes as who has the larger military
to settle the argument, carlucci said at one point, ``the simple thing would be to publish your military budget.''
yazov said, `well, it isn't all in one piece. it's as difficult for us as for you''' to determine the exact level of soviet defense spending, recounted a senior u.s. official
the americans pursued the point in less formal moments, and were convinced that the soviets ``really didn't know the size of the budget or everything that was going on in their military establishment,'' said another u.s. official
and yazov didn't know everything his forces are doing
at one point, he complained about our ships collecting electronic intelligence off their coast,'' said a senior u.s. official
carlucci responded that ``your spy ships are three miles off our coast,'' just beyond the territorial limit, ``and they are welcome there.''
yazov turned to an admiral (in the soviet delegation), and said, `is that right?' and the admiral said, `yeah, they're there,''' said the u.s. official
yazov kept his cool during tense moments, and showed no offense when carlucci demanded an apology for the fatal shooting, by a soviet soldier, of u.s. army major arthur d. nicholson in east germany three years ago. yazov did not apologize, but promised to re-examine the event
editor's note: bryan brumley, who was an associated press correspondent in moscow during the eras of leonid brezhnev and yuri andropov, covered the carlucci-yazov talks in bern. minister says</head>
gen. manuel antonio noriega could be granted political asylum in france or spain if he is forced to relinquish his power in panama, prime minister felipe gonzalez said saturday
gonzalez spoke to reporters just before beginning a meeting with french president francois mitterrand at this national park on spain's southern atlantic coast
gonzalez didn't elaborate on his statement, and mitterrand did not speak to reporters
in paris, the french foreign ministry said it had no comment on whether france was prepared to offer asylum to noriega
gonzalez reiterated an offer made last week. spain said it would be willing to admit noriega, chief of the panamanian military and the country's de facto leader, provided he requested asylum and the united states agreed not to seek his extradition on drug trafficking charges
noriega has denied the charges
the noriega-dominated national assembly ousted panama's civilian president, eric arturo delvalle, on feb. 25 after delvalle ordered noriega to step down from his post. murder</head>
terry donald hudson was no different from a lot of the young men who cruised the streets and drive-in restaurants of north chattanooga in 1957
the 24-year-old liked souped-up cars and sometimes ran moonshine, but then bootlegging wasn't uncommon in southeast tennessee
and when hudson was gunned down in his car on july 20, 1957, investigators thought he died as the result of a ``corn liquor'' feud
at the same time bobby hoppe was 22, the best football player in town. the all-state halfback was preparing for his senior year at auburn university and later he played briefly for the san francisco 49ers
so people were shocked when hoppe, now athletic director at chattanooga state technical community college, was charged this month with first-degree murder in the 30-year-old slaying
authorities say it was police detective richard heck, who was just 5 at the time of the killing, who figured out what led to hudson's death
dick has a good case,'' said maj. john taylor, head of the homicide squad. ``he's done an exceptional job on this.''
heck reopened the case 14 months ago after he and detective steve angel were appointed to a special squad to investigate unsolved murders
at a meeting of families and friends of murder victims, a counseling group, heck met hudson's mother, georgia
she realized we had other, more recent cases to work on,'' said heck. ``but she said there hadn't been a day go by in 30 years that she hadn't thought of her son's murder.''
heck refuses to discuss details, except to say that he has obtained new evidence. much of his basic information was gleaned through news clippings at the public library, followed by interviews with at least 45 people
hudson was not a stranger to police. on the previous monday, he had been arrested for allegedly driving a ``liquor car'' that overturned during a chase and was charged with transporting untaxed liquor
he had some run-ins with them, but not too bad,'' mrs. hudson said in a recent interview. ``he'd go racing a lot. he was good at it. of course, i didn't approve. i was afraid he'd get hurt.''
moonshine was really the big thing,'' said taylor. ``this is kind of the bible belt. we got churches on every corner, but people drink liquor, too
to some young men then ... this was an exciting life, driving a whiskey car. it was an adventure. somebody who transported liquor and drove a hot car was kind of a hero to some people.''
hudson was about a block from his parents' house when someone pulled beside him and fired a .410-gauge shotgun through the passenger window of his car, hitting him in the head
investigators suspected a moonshine connection
but then they learned that hudson had received a threatening call two weeks earlier warning him to stay away from a woman. they talked to joan hoppe voiles, a former girlfriend with whom he had recently broken up. mrs. voiles, a widow with a child, was bobby hoppe's older sister
it was a hot and cold relationship,'' said taylor. ``they had their squabbles but they ended up getting back together most of the time.''
mrs. hudson agreed that her son's romance with mrs. voiles was stormy
they said he beat her up, but i don't think so. she could beat him up,'' said mrs. hudson. ``i don't know. she was bigger than he was. ... he was just a little guy.''
heck acknowledged that both mrs. voiles and hoppe refused to talk with him. hoppe and three other witnesses invoked their fifth amendment right against self-incrimination at a coroner's inquest after hudson's death
mrs. hudson said she felt authorities in 1957 ``didn't seem to be interested'' in pursuing the case. but heck said, ``the best i can tell, i don't think they had enough information at the time to make an arrest.''
hoppe has declined to talk to reporters on the advice of his attorney
free on $7,500 bond, he is scheduled to stand trial june 21, although his attorney, leroy phillips, has indicated he may challenge the case because of the long delay in bringing charges
if hoppe is convicted, he can only be sentenced to 20 years to life in prison, because the state's 1957 death penalty law was later declared unconstitutional. this morning, picking up 5th graf pvs, ``the jurors ....''</note>
jurors deliberating the fate of murder defendant robert chambers jr. for a second day asked to hear and see again some of the evidence and testimony presented at the 11-week trial, but did not reach a verdict
chambers, 21, is charged with second-degree murder in the strangulation of jennifer levin, 18, during an early morning tryst in central park on aug. 26, 1986
on friday, forewoman debra cavanaugh sent justice howard bell a note from jurors at 2 p.m., expressing the desire to deliberate until 8 p.m. however, the judge cut deliberations off at 6:30 p.m., and a few of the jurors seemed surprised by bell's move
the jurors, who resumed deliberations nearly an hour late today, at 11:20 a.m., have spent 15{ hours discussing the case. chambers, his family and lawyers were in the courtroom this morning awaiting any word
the jurors also asked the judge for the transcript of a taped telephone conversation between defense lawyer jack litman and dr. werner spitz, the chief medical examiner of detroit who was the prosecution's chief witness
however, the transcript had not been put into evidence and was therefore not available to jurors. in the discussion, litman sought to recruit spitz as a defense witness and spitz declined. litman taped the call
spitz testified for the prosecution that he believed chambers killed miss levin by using her blouse to strangle her. chambers has contended he killed her accidentally during sex. he said he was reacting to the pain caused when she squeezed his genitals
during the afternoon friday, jurors also asked for the following: an enlarged picture of the crime scene; an x-ray of chambers' right hand, showing a fractured fifth metacarpal; and a reading of the testimony of dr. allan garber, a resident physician at bronx lebanon hospital
garber, who jogged by while chambers and levin were under a tree in central park, testified that he saw a white male sitting astride another person under a tree 30 to 40 feet off the park's east drive. he testified that he encountered the same scene 15 to 20 minutes later, and assumed the people he saw were having sex
jurors also asked friday to see evidence they had seen on thursday _ miss levin's clothing and lipstick case, smaller pictures of the crime scene, photos of miss levin at the bar she left with chambers and chambers' written statement to the police
the jurors, who can also convict chambers of manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide, were given all the material they requested, with the exception of the transcript not entered into evidence
america's next national head count isn't until 1990, but the census bureau's dress rehearsal already is underway
the census tests are being conducted in st. louis, and in east central missouri and eastern washington state
forms are being mailed to most residents of these areas, as was done in 1970 and 1980, although census takers will visit households in some sparsely settled areas. the effort is expected to continue into the summer
the special counts are designed to be as much as possible like the effort planned for 1990, in order to get an understanding of what problems will develop before the work is begun nationwide, census director john g. keane said
earlier tests were conducted in parts of new jersey, florida, mississippi and california. questions on the forms, while similar to those asked in the past, were developed in a series of more than 100 public meetings over the last few years
for the woman who wants that `dressed to kill' look, fashion accessories that conceal even the bulkiest firearm are being modeled at the bing bang boom gun show this weekend
this could only happen in miami,'' said ron campos, who spent several hours friday testing some of the weapons at the radisson centre show. ``where else would you find a fashion show on how to wear a concealed weapon?''
the purpose of friday's runway show and fashion displays throughout the weekend is to attract women into the gun market, said promoter ted walker, who is also spokesman for the shotgun news, a nebraska trade magazine for gun enthusiasts
what we're trying to do is show the contemporary woman that she can carry a concealed weapon and still look good,'' he said
one model wore a hair bow with a holster in it. others displayed gun-concealing purses and bras
cindy mccall modeled several lines of handbags that hide a pistol in a secret compartment
if you are accosted, she said, all you need to do is slip your hand through the velcro panel in the back of the purse, grab the trigger and blast. the handbag is destroyed, but what is a $100 accessory when your life is at stake?
until i found these handbags, i would not carry a weapon with me,'' ms. mccall said. ``when i found these, i said to myself, `somebody finally did something that makes sense for women.'''
the fashion show was narrated by charlene meriedy, who described a horizontal shoulder holster as ``the perfect accessory for the business women of the '80s.'' the holster is generally worn under a jacket
some 75 firearms fans applauded as the models walked by
some of the gun dealers went along with the theme of the fashion show by offering what they called ``sweetheart specials,'' such as a .22-caliber jennings pistol that can fit readily into a purse. murder</head>
terry donald hudson was no different from a lot of the young men who cruised the streets and drive-in restaurants of north chattanooga in 1957
the 24-year-old liked souped-up cars and sometimes ran moonshine, but then bootlegging wasn't uncommon in southeast tennessee
and when hudson was gunned down in his car on july 20, 1957, investigators thought he died as the result of a ``corn liquor'' feud
at the same time bobby hoppe was 22, the best football player in town. the all-state halfback was preparing for his senior year at auburn university and later he played briefly for the san francisco 49ers
so people were shocked when hoppe, now athletic director at chattanooga state technical community college, was charged this month with first-degree murder in the 30-year-old slaying
authorities say it was police detective richard heck, who was just 5 at the time of the killing, who figured out what led to hudson's death
dick has a good case,'' said maj. john taylor, head of the homicide squad. ``he's done an exceptional job on this.''
heck reopened the case 14 months ago after he and detective steve angel were appointed to a special squad to investigate unsolved murders
at a meeting of families and friends of murder victims, a counseling group, heck met hudson's mother, georgia
she realized we had other, more recent cases to work on,'' said heck. ``but she said there hadn't been a day go by in 30 years that she hadn't thought of her son's murder.''
heck refuses to discuss details, except to say that he has obtained new evidence. much of his basic information was gleaned through news clippings at the public library, followed by interviews with at least 45 people
hudson was not a stranger to police. on the previous monday, he had been arrested for allegedly driving a ``liquor car'' that overturned during a chase and was charged with transporting untaxed liquor
he had some run-ins with them, but not too bad,'' mrs. hudson said in a recent interview. ``he'd go racing a lot. he was good at it. of course, i didn't approve. i was afraid he'd get hurt.''
