here is a summary of the developments saturday involving nicaragua, honduras and the united states:
honduras ordered several more battalions of soldiers to reinforce its 2,000 troops along the border with nicaragua. the troops are trying to oust nicaraguan soldiers who entered honduran territory. president jose azcona hoyo said he wouldn't hesitate to seek more u.s. help
but a few hours after azcona spoke, the honduran armed forces announced the nicaraguans were withdrawing. honduran officials said the sandinista troops had crossed the border last week in pursuit of u.s.-backed nicaraguan rebels
president reagan called for renewed aid for the rebels, known as contras. his administration sent 3,200 american soldiers to honduras last week. the defense department said the u.s. troops probably will be in central america for about 10 days
president daniel ortega said he is asking the international court of justice in the hague for an injunction preventing military activities that could ``raise tension'' between honduras and nicaragua. the tribunal, also known as the world court, has no power unless both sides of a dispute agree to its jurisdiction
nicaragua's rebels said they are willing to hold cease-fire talks as scheduled this week with the sandinista government, despite threatening earlier to boycott them unless nicaraguan troops withdrew from honduras. a contra spokesman, carlos hurtado, said the rebels were ready for monday's talks in the southern town of sapoa near the costa rican border
the official tass news agency accused the united states of using military threats to impose its will on nicaragua and spoil peace efforts in central america
a team of u.n. observers will visit nicaragua as soon as possible to investigate the border conflict with honduras. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar decided to send the team at nicaragua's request. the group will include one political officer from u.n. headquarters and an undecided number of military observers, u.n. spokesman mahbub ahmad said
mexico said the crisis in panama and at the honduras-nicaragua border calls for ``great prudence and the need to use political means to achieve a negotiated peace.'' foreign minister bernardo sepulveda said mexico opposes outside military intervention in the region. track</head> with tass comment; picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `another state'</note>
the reagan administration will complain to soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze this week about his country's military aid to nicaragua, but won't let the issue disturb preparations for a superpower summit, officials said
shevardnadze, due to arrive sunday afternoon, will hold three days of talks starting monday with secretary of state george p. shultz. lunch at the white house with president reagan is tentatively scheduled for wednesday
the aim is to clear the way _ especially on arms control _ for a reagan trip to moscow in may or june to sign another u.s.-soviet disarmament agreement
the soviet foreign minister will come at a time of preoccupation in the capital with events in honduras, where 3,200 u.s. troops were sent after nicaragua moved against guerrillas using sanctuaries on honduran territory
the soviet union supplies the nicaraguan forces
in 1986, moscow and its allies gave nicaragua $500 million in economic assistance and $600 million in military aid, including helicopter gun ships, transport aircraft and more than 1,200 vehicles for probable military use, according to the pentagon's most recent report on soviet military power
that aid, compared with what the united states sends to the resistance and to u.s. client states in the region, ``makes us look like paupers,'' state department spokesman charles e. redman said friday
he called the soviet effort ``massive'' and said the issue would be raised during the talks with shevardnadze
shevardnadze may carry complaints of his own
the official soviet news agency accused the u.s. government saturday of sending troops to honduras to destroy a central american peace plan signed in guatemala last summer. tass said the administration's support for the guerrillas in nicaragua aids terrorism
redman sought to dispel the view that the issue would dominate the talks, saying ``the soviets know how we feel.''
another state department official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said arms control, the situation in afghanistan and human rights in the soviet union were equally important topcs for the talks
shultz is expected to press shevardnadze to clarify soviet plans for the withdrawal of its estimated 115,000 troops from afghanistan
a soviet spokesman said last week that even if united nations-sponsored negotiations in geneva fail to produce a political settlement in afghanistan the soviet union would withdraw its troops anyway
this appeared to be a change in soviet emphasis, away from the need for a geneva accord and toward a unilateral pullout
the soviets didn't need the geneva accords to invade afghanistan so they certainly don't need the geneva accords to leave afghanistan,'' redman said. nevertheless, he added, ``we do believe it would be preferable if there were an agreed-to, orderly basis for that withdrawal. we think that's something that would be in the interest of all parties, including the soviets.''
the chief u.s. desire is an end not just to soviet presence but to moscow's financial and military support to the afghan government _ which the state department has labelled a mere ``faction'' among political groups in the country
if the soviets continue helping the afghan government after a troop pullout, the united states will continue its support to resistance forces fighting the kabul regime for almost a decade, the state department said
shultz and shevardnadze's last meeting, in moscow in february, was dominated by discussion of arms control, notably efforts to reach an agreement on up to 50 percent cuts in long-range nuclear missiles and bombers carrying atomic weapons
negotiators have been trying to devise a pact in time for signing at a summit
one of the most difficult-to-achieve ingredients of the arms pact is a verification system that insures the destruction of the weapons and satisfies both sides that armaments outlawed by the pact are not subsequently deployed
since february, each side has completed its drafts of how the verification system should work and the negotiators are now trying to narrow the differences in the documents
on tuesday, shevardnadze is scheduled to join shultz in a ribbon-cutting ceremony opening the u.s. end of washington-to-moscow communication links known as ``risk reduction centers.''
the computer and telefax filled center, on the 7th floor of the state department, and a comparable communications post in moscow, will be used to help the two sides keep in touch at a minute's notice if problems arise with treaties to limit weapons, incidents at sea and the danger of accidental war
center managers tested the high-speed communications link last week by exchanging maps of the moscow and washington subway systems by high-speed data transmitters
tobacco companies can be held accountable for not having warned consumers about the hazards of smoking before a law was passed requiring warning labels on cigarette packages, a federal judge ruled
u.s. district judge walter jay skinner dismissed claims by joanne kotler that her husband died of lung cancer because three tobacco companies failed to warn about the hazards of cigarette smoking after the cigarette labeling and advertising act went into effect on jan. 1, 1966
but skinner ruled that she will be allowed to continue her case on the basis of inadequate warnings before the federal law was enacted
there is no language in the act that even hints at retroactive application (of protection provided by the package warning), and it surely is not necessary to give the act retroactive application in order to give it full force of effect,'' skinner wrote
skinner's opinion, issued last wednesday, resulted from a hearing held in october 1987, two months after a similar case was dismissed by a federal appeals court ruling that the warning labels on cigarette packages protect tobacco companies from liability suits
american tobacco co. had argued that the kotler suit, filed in march 1986 against it and two other tobacco companies, philip morris inc. and liggett group inc., should also be dismissed. but skinner disagreed, saying the court did not distinguish in the previous case between smoking done before the warning labels were begun and smoking done after
mrs. kotler, of cambridge, alleged in her suit that her husband, george, started smoking at age 11 because of aggressive and negligent advertising campaigns by the tobacco companies. he continued smoking for 44 years until his death in january 1986
the suit also alleged that the companies failed to warn of the dangers of their cigarettes and that they failed to adequately test, design and market them. the defendants have denied the claims
skinner permitted the continuation of mrs. kotler's allegations that the cigarettes were defectively designed and breached the implied warranty of their sale
the defendants argued that the law states, ``good tobacco is not unreasonably dangerous merely because the effects of smoking may be harmful,'' skinner wrote
but skinner said a ``product may be negligently designed even though it functions as intended if design changes would have reduced the danger of the product without significant reduction in its efficiency and without undue cost.''
other courts have held that cigarettes may be found to be `bad' if the tobacco contains pesticide residues, which might have resulted from inadequate testing, or if they contain excess nicotine or additives, which may affect their safety,'' skinner wrote
eric nissen, mrs. kotler's attorney, did not immediately return a message left on his office telephone answering maching saturday. spokesmen for connecticut-based american tobacco; new york-based philip morris; and durham, n.c-based ligget did not return phone calls to their offices saturday
a judge has dismissed attempted manslaughter charges against a prostitute who continued soliciting sex after she contracted the aids virus, a case believed to be the first of its kind in the nation
circuit judge michael cycmanick ruled friday that prosecutors failed to prove that elizabeth kay sherouse, 24, actually intended to kill any of her customers
thank you, jesus,'' ms. sherouse said after the judge's decision
although the judge said she might have been negligent in continuing to solicit sex, he said there was no evidence indicating she had an intent to kill
prosecutors claimed that ms. sherouse, who has been convicted nine times on prostitution-related charges, tried to kill two men last summer by agreeing to have sex with them after she had been told she carried the deadly acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus. neither man has tested positive for the virus
assistant state attorney rick bogle said the state will decide next week whether to appeal the ruling. ms. sherouse is scheduled for trial may 2 on six unrelated misdemeanor charges and a racketeering charge
her attorney, bill sheaffer, argued that ms. sherouse, a cocaine addict with a seventh-grade education, was too ignorant about aids to understand the danger she posed to the men
bogle disagreed
she didn't care what happened,'' bogle said. ``she didn't care she could kill somebody.'' pickup</note>
south dakota democrats, honoring results of the feb. 23 presidential primary, allocated national convention delegates saturday on that basis during a statewide caucus in pierre
although national party rules do not permit the election to have any directly binding effect on the national convention delegates, state democrats said it was only proper to do so
missouri rep. richard gephardt will receive nine pledged delegates and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis will receive six delegates, state democrats decided
gephardt initially was allocated six delegates saturday and dukakis was given four. five more pledged delegates will be parceled-out between the two candidates in proportion to primary results on april 23 when the democratic state central committee meets in mitchell
in addition, four top members of the south dakota democratic party automatically receive seats as delegates to the national convention in july
gephardt received 44 percent of the vote to win the state's democratic primary. dukakis came in second with 31 percent
the decision to pattern the delegate selection process after the results of the state presidential primary was made with no debate and no dissent
i move that we reflect the integrity of the south dakota voters and reaffirm the express presidential preferences of the primary election vote,'' said ted muenster of sioux falls, state chairman of the gephardt campaign
the motion was immediately seconded and the question called for, which in parliamentary proceedings prevents any further debate
there had been rumors that some democrats might attempt to discard the election results and instead base the allocation of delegates on the preferences of those attending the caucus
after the caucus, rick hauffe, the newly named executive director of the state democratic party, confirmed the rumors but said he was pleased that no opposition surfaced
this is a good demonstration of democratic unity in south dakota,'' hauffe said. ``it's going to go uphill from here.''
kip scott of sioux falls, state campaign manager for dukakis, said he was disappointed that dukakis finished second in the state primary
michael dukakis wasn't exactly a household name in south dakota before the election,'' scott said. ``i felt some of the lessons we learned enabled us to go into the south and do well there.''
dukakis gained the most democratic convention delegates on super tuesday and leads in total pledged delegates. martin anderson named in 13th graf.</head>
u.s. soldiers deployed on what washington officials call a show of military support for honduras and a training mission said saturday they are ready for anything
we're prepared to do anything they ask us to do,'' maj. mike nason of the 82nd airborne division headquartered at fort bragg, n.c., said at the palmerola air force base. ``i don't want to speculate, but the 82nd airborne is a combat unit. anything can happen.''
nason arrived in the first plane thursday of an airlift of 3,200 american soliers sent by the reagan administration to honduras. they were dispatched after nicaraguan soldiers entered honduran territory in pursuit of u.s.-backed rebels known as contras
u.s. officials say the troops will not engage in combat. they say the troops are in honduras for a training mission combined with a show of force and support for the central american nation
but nicaragua's leftist sandinista government has accused the united states of preparing to invade nicaragua. president daniel ortega said last week his forces are ready to ``liquidate'' the u.s. troops
nason, from garden city, n.y., said the american soldiers would be surprised if they are called upon to do anything other than demonstrate american support for honduras
our orders remain that we're here to train. we're not here to enter into combat,'' he said
the arrival of the 82nd airborne and units of the 7th light infantry from fort ord, calif., put u.s. strength in honduras at about 6,900, according to maj. gary hovatter, the public affairs officer for american troops in honduras. the troops who had been here before the reinforcements were sent are assigned to various u.s. facilities and engaged in training exercises
president jose azcona hoyo of honduras asked for the additional u.s. troops in hopes of forcing a nicaraguan retreat and he said saturday he won't hesitate to ask for more u.s. assistance
azcona has asked for a u.s. helicopter airlift to help him deploy honduran troops in the mountainous bocay border region where the sandinistas crossed the frontier
despite the tense situation, the american soldiers at the palmerola headquarters were relaxed saturday. many said they looked forward to the training activities and nothing more
i like it. it's fun,'' said pfc. shane lawson of columbus, ohio. ``you can't train like this in the states, so we came down here. and we get to train with honduran troops.''
sgt. kenneth martin anderson said he was upset at protests back home over the deployment
they're protesting just to protest something,'' he said. `they don't understand that you can't have communists running free all over the place doing what they want to do. what happens if the united states gets attacked by communists?''
anderson and lawson were in a contingent of about 670 airborne soldiers in camouflage battle dress who climbed into blackhawk and chinook helicopters for the brief flight to their bivouack at the nearby base of tamara
hovatter said the u.s. troops were sent to four honduran bases: tamara, just north of the capital; san lorenzo in the south; juticalpa, about 65 miles northeast of the area where the nicarguan incursion took place, and palmerola, 40 miles west of tegucigalpa
nason denied nicaraguan claims that the u.s. operation was designed to bring in equipment for the contras in their 6-year-old war against the leftist sandinistas
wherever we go, the equipment goes. none of it will stay here,'' he said
nason said the 82nd flew in two tanks, four cobra combat helicopters, three light helicopters, more than 100 machine guns, a dozen 105mm howitzers and several thousand rifles
on the main highway through tegucigalpa, people stopped to look at a convoy of about 25 trucks filled with u.s. soldiers
reporters driving alongside the caravan asked the troopers where they were heading
nowhere!'' one soldier shouted
claude montana's winter ready-to-wear collection of long trousers and christian lacroix's display saturday of short skirts showed that the two lengths can live in harmony
montana's show featured long pants along with some skirts, tops cinched at the waist and often with huge funnel collars
the designer has abandoned his big shoulders in favor of the raised or large sloped collars and shoulder wraps
he has honed down the sharp silhouette to simplicity in great fabrics and colors _ lots of caramels and a few pastels or black in silk gabardines, ribbed jerseys, leather and shorn mink
for evening, he concentrated on ways to make the black suit different. his black suits had satin scroll details over collars, lapels and jacket hems, and some elegant swirled stitch patterns, updating the tuxedo or smoking suit
christian lacroix's collection featured short coats with rounded shapes in hot-colored mohair with fichu wrapped collars
from lean suit shapes to the familiar bell-shaped short skirts or some bloomer-dresses for evening, lacroix surprised viewers with new velvets printed like persian rugs or prints with small leaf motifs
givenchy also showed acres of luxury clothes, mainly shorter lengths for daytime, just skimming the knee or slightly above
his man-tailored suits and waist-fitted suits with slightly full skirts displayed elegance. in shades of raspberry or bright blues or green, the tweeds are outstanding, as are some of the leather cardigan jackets
the knit outfits were in bright colors or tan and beige, sometimes with a wide-wrapped top
guy paulin was another designer who went in for simplicity. his models displayed short suits with clinging stretch black skirts topped by bordeaux and olive long piped jackets
cable-knit or jersey trouser suits were best with boleros in shades of khaki and caramel, or in pastel boucle knits
long iridescent taffeta raincoats with elasticized waists over full skirts or fitted coat-dresses in vermilion or emerald added a lively touch to the sober gathering of winter clothes. only</head>
the saudi arabian government said saturday the intermediate-range missiles it had acquired from the chinese would be used for defensive purposes to protect its territory and islam's holiest shrines
the saudi information office, in a statement to the official saudi press agency, quoted an unidentified official as saying that any nation has a legitimate right to defend itself by any means it deems necessary but that saudi arabia would not arm the missiles with nuclear warheads
the official said newspaper reports about the ``nuclear capacity of these missiles does not lend itself to truth and is utterly negated by the kingdom, as the steadfast and well-known policy of the kingdom is based on the permanent efforts to make the middle east region avoid the dangers of the nuclear arms race and to remain free from all its forms.''
the state department confirmed friday that saudi arabia had acquired chinese missiles with a range of 2,200 miles, capable of hitting all areas of the middle east, including israel
the missiles were described as chinese css-2 rockets, similar to those used in china's limited space program in the early 1970s and capable of being outfitted with nuclear warheads
it is not a new or strange tendency that saudi arabia seeks to secure its requirements of weapons for its armed forces from different sources, in accordance with its defense needs and in conformity with the prevalent circumstances in the region,'' the statement said
this principle is based on its defense policy aimed at bolstoring its capabilities, for the sake of the legitimate defense of its territory and holy shrines, particularly in view of the unstable situation and existing conflicts in the middle east region,'' the statement said
the official said saudi arabia is responsible for protecting the holy shrines of mecca, the birthplace of prophet mohammed, and medina, site of mohammed's tomb, which are located in a western region known as hijaz
on the other hand, the official said the kingdom's defense policy ``has never demonstrated any aggressive tendency. its policy was, and still is, based on keenness to avail security and prevail peace throughout the region.''
therefore, the official said, any program ``aimed at fostering its defense capabilities and protecting its legitimate interests is not a menace to peace. on the contrary, the more its defense capabilities are reinforced, the more it helps in propagating peace in the region
on the basis of this principle, saudi arabia acquired this chinese-made medium-range surface-to-surface missile system,'' the official said
the united states and the soviet union on saturday completed the first round of negotiations by the two countries on a new long-term grain agreement
deputy trade representative alan f. holmer, u.s. team leader in the negotiations, called the seven-hour discussion ``frank and amicable with both sides presenting their respective point of view.''
no deadline has been set for completion of the agreement,'' holmer said in a statement. ``however, both countries would like to come to mutual terms over the next several months.''
the current five-year agreement, which expires sept. 30, calls on moscow to buy at least 9 million tons of grain annually and specifies that the purchase include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
the last full day of winter made itself felt with a blast of cold arctic air across the north-central united states on saturday, plunging afternoon temperatures into the teens in northern minnesota and upper michigan
spring begins at 4:39 a.m. est sunday
daytime temperatures remained below freezing from the northeast half of north dakota through much of the great lakes to new england. strong northerly winds ushering the cold air into the north-central united states were expected to produce squalls and heavy snow in parts of ohio and pennsylvania on saturday night
heavy snow warnings were issued for northeastern ohio and northwestern pennsylvania, where 6 to 10 inches of snow was expected
it was also unseasonably cool in parts of texas, where morning temperatures dipped into the 20s and 30s. several cities set low-temperature records for the date, including el paso with 22 degrees; del rio, 29; corpus christi, 30; and brownsville, 38
the upper midwest and northeast had scattered snow showers, while the carolinas and the mid-atlantic coast region had sporadic light rain. sunny skies prevailed across the south-central and southwestern united states
a high wind warning was issued for southeastern wyoming on saturday. gusts of up to 52 mph were clocked at cheyenne
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 16 degrees at marquette, mich., to 87 in san diego, calif. the early-morning low for the nation was 3 degrees below zero at gunnison, colo
sunday's forecast called for scattered snow from the great lakes and upper ohio valley to new england, with rain in the pacific northwest, especially in western washington state and northwestern oregon. fair to partly sunny skies should prevail across the rest of the nation
afternoon highs should remain below 40 degrees from eastern north dakota through the great lakes region and ohio valley to new jersey and new england, with highs in the 20s and upper teens from minnesota across the great lakes to northern new england. highs should reach into the 70s from the southern plains through southern arizona to california, climbing into the 80s in western texas and the desert southwest. highs in the 40s, 50s and 60s were forecast for most of the rest of the nation
separating honduras and nicaragua where sandinista troops entered honduran territory to attack bases of u.s.-backed nicaraguan rebels is the the coco river, a wide, shallow stream
but the coco is a confusing border, winding through a maze of thick jungle and mountains, merging with enough tributaries to make one uncertain of the side of the frontier he's on
the thrust of the nicaraguan offensive has been in the area around san andres de bocay, a border town 170 miles northeast of managua where the bocay river flows from nicaragua's jinotega province into the coco
north of the coco at that point is a series of small honduran mountain ranges and a broad plateau. flat and parched during the current dry season, it resembles parts of the american southwest
there are narrow valleys that provide relatively secure locations for the bases of the rebels, known as contras
south of the coco, in nicaragua, the swift-running bocay tumbles down a long series of rapids through the mountains of jinotega province and cuts through a deep valley named after it in its fall to the low-lying coco
where the two join at the border, they look much alike, both now in the six-month dry season that began in november and in the rainy season when they carry enormous amounts of water
the bocay valley, extending from the honduran border far into jinotega, has long been a strategic supply route for the contras
over the years, the jungled hills that rise hundreds of feet on both sides have been laced with an narrow trails, first made by local farmers and more recently by the contras
from the honduran border, the contras send supplies down the valley into nicaragua in dugout canoes and other boats or on the backs of mules and men who walk the jungle trails
on the honduran side of the coco where it is met by the bocay a small airstrip extends perilously along a bluff overlooking the water. supplies are landed or parachuted there by light planes that bring them from other contra bases inside honduras
the area is just 43 miles northwest of bonanza, a nicaraguan mining district. but bonanza is too isolated and difficult to defend for the sandinistas to station troops there permanently
instead, the sandinistas have driven the contras out of the bocay valley several times as they did this month and have attacked their bases inside honduras
a woman who claims she inspired michael jackson's 1983 hit ``billie jean'' was sentenced to 303 days in jail for violating a probation order to stay away from the pop singer's home
lavon a. muhammad, 40, who was twice previously convicted of trespassing on jackson's estate and who is described as suffering from delusions, was found guilty friday of violating the terms of probation for the 1986 convictions, which required her to remain a mile away
municipal court judge michael j. farrell, however, dismissed several misdemeanor charges against ms. muhammad, including trespassing and violating a court order
she was arrested at 3 a.m. feb. 12 in jackson's back yard after scaling a 5-foot wall
both prosecutors and her defense attorney say she suffers from delusions and believes she is engaged to marry jackson. she also claims the superstar is the father of her 6-year-old twins
jackson, 29, denies any involvement with ms. muhammad
in 1986, he obtained a four-year restraining order to keep the woman away, said deputy city attorney david s. kestenbaum
kestenbaum said that ms. muhammad, despite her claims, was not the inspiration for the song ``billie jean,'' which includes such lyrics as, ``billie jean is not my lover'' and ``the kid is not my son.'' ^eds: subs 2nd graf to add date of annual meeting.</head>
a white supremacist group has forced at&amp;t into asking shareholders to vote on ending the telephone company's minority hiring program on the grounds that blacks are intellectually inferior
the racist national alliance offered the resolution on the ballot for at&amp;t's annual shareholders' meeting in denver, set for april 20. the securities and exchange commission ruled that it must appear, with minor changes in wording, despite the company's objections
at&amp;t's management has recommended that shareholders vote against the proposal
at&amp;t has had a long-term commitment to the advancement of women and minorities,'' said at&amp;t spokesman herb linnen in washington. ``it's ludicrous in this day and age to have it suggested that women and minorities not be given their rightful place based on their achievements in the workplace.''
he said at&amp;t, the nation's largest long-distance telephone company, has an ``outstanding record to point to (on affirmative action), one which we're proud of and we intend to continue our firm commitment in this area.''
the national alliance is a washington, d.c.-based organization that promotes the study of adolf hitler's writings
its leader, william pierce, also heads the white supremacist cosmotheist church, with headquarters in pocahontas county, w.va. he is the author of ``the turner diaries,'' a fictional account of an all-out race war ending in the domination of a worldwide hitler-inspired regime
the national alliance bought 100 shares of at&amp;t in 1986, and pierce told the charleston daily mail that the group's members have been working on the at&amp;t campaign for a year and a half
in a statement sent to shareholders, the national alliance claimed that ``only 1.1 percent'' of blacks possess an iq of 114 or above _ a ``desirable'' figure for most at&amp;t employees
we believe that to ignore data such as this in employment practices sacrifices the essential long-term benefits of personnel quality, for the short-term approval of pressure groups,'' the statement said
the resolution says minority hiring has had ``negative effects'' on morale among white at&amp;t employees who could ``feel discouraged and ignored when they notice that the company is actively seeking to advance non-whites.''
at&amp;t has disputed the group's allegations that its minority hiring program has hurt morale
ironically, at&amp;t management also has recommended a vote against another proposal from a new jersey shareholder who believes there aren't enough women and minorities in executive positions
that proposal asks at&amp;t to reformulate affirmative-action programs ``to ensure that racial minorities and women are not under-utilized in upper-middle and executive levels of corporate leadership.''
left-wing guerrillas attacked a state-owned coal mine, stole dynamite, blew up equipment and took two hostages with them as they fled, police reported saturday
they said an estimated 100 guerrillas of the pro-cuban tupac amaru revolutionary movement were involved in the pre-dawn raid friday on the cachi mine 30 miles west of this provincial capital
police and army units are searching for the rebel band and the two miners taken captive in the mountainous area about 130 miles east of lima
authorities reported no one was injured in the attack. no estimate of damage at the mine was given
the tupac amaru front emerged in 1984 as an urban guerrilla group but in the past year it has extended its attacks to include a few rural zones
it is considered less violent than peru's largest guerrilla organization, the maoist shining path movement that has been active for eight years. government officials say more than 10,000 people have been killed in violence related to the shining path
steve martin's screenwriting for the movie ``roxanne'' and john patrick shanley's work on the ``moonstruck'' script won top honors at the annual writers guild of america awards
cbs was the big television winner during the 40th annual awards presentation late friday at the beverly hilton hotel, taking top honors in seven categories, including best tv spot news script
nbc and abc each took four awards while the public broadcasting service had three and home box office won one. three of nbc's awards came via a three-way tie in one category, best comedy episode
the awards were presented on the 11th day of the 9,000-member guild's strike against the alliance of motion picture and television producers, and references to the strike flavored the evening, despite guild executive director brian walton's admonition, ``this is a night to celebrate writers and writing.''
martin was honored for best screenplay based on material from another medium
the comedian, who also starred in ``roxanne'' with daryl hannah, wrote the script for the summer comedy hit which was adapted from edmund rostand's ``cyrano de bergerac,'' a story about a man with an unattractive nose who uses well-chosen words to woo his lady
shanley was honored for best original screenwriting on ``moonstruck,'' which is nominated for six academy awards and stars cher as a brooklyn italian widow who finds herself engaged to one man but in love with his brother
broadcasting winners were:
original long form: john sayles, ``unnatural causes,'' nbc
adapted long form: reginald rose, ``escape from sobibor,'' cbs
anthology episode, single program: harry cauley, ``there were times dear,'' pbs
episodic drama (two-way tie): debra frank and carl sautter, ``it's a wonderful job,'' episode of ``moonlighting,'' abc; georgia jeffries, ``turn, turn, turn, part i,'' episode of ``cagney &amp; lacey,'' cbs
episodic comedy (three-way tie): barry fanaro and mort nathan, ``'twas the nightmare before christmas,'' episode of ``the golden girls,'' nbc; gary david goldberg and alan uger, ``a, my name is alex, part ii,'' episode of ``family ties,'' nbc; jay tarses, ``here's why cosmetics should come in unbreakable bottles,'' episode of ``the days and nights of molly dodd,'' nbc
variety-music, award tribute, special event: bennett tramer, ``will rogers: look back in laughter,'' hbo special
children's script: joseph maurer, ``an enemy among us,'' cbs
documentary-current events: perry wolff, ``the battle for afghanistan,'' cbs
documentary-other than current events: theodore thomas, ``the grizzlies,'' pbs
television spot news: thomas phillips, paul fisher, hugh heckman, paul enger, ``reykjavik summit,'' cbs
daytime serials: claire labine, eleanor mancusi, william burritt, madeline b. david, steve lehrman, david appell, ``ryan's hope,'' abc
television graphic art-network: kelly lee, kris celich, jay haiden, ray duke, ``shuttle disaster,'' abc
television graphic animation: frank sveva, ned steinberg, ``special events,'' cbs
on-air promotion: larry scheflin, ``wnet-pbs promo,'' wnet, pbs
radio documentary: norman morris, ``under the big sky,'' cbs
radio spot news: les blatt, ``peter jennings' journal,'' abc
a michigan schoolteacher and a retiree together raised $14,000 to help cover the medical expenses of a toddler who's the longest survivor of a five-organ transplant
moses rutland, 71, a retired butcher, and john ribner, 49, an eighth-grade teacher, both of flint, mich., said contributors ranged from the city's mayor to a child who gave $34 in pennies
the money was donated saturday for tabatha foster, 3, of madisonville, ky., who is recuperating from a five-organ transplant she underwent nov. 1 at children's hospital of pittsburgh
she received a new liver, pancreas, small intestine and parts of a stomach and colon during the experimental operation, which is not covered by her parents' insurance. she suffered from short gut syndrome, a congenital defect, and she would have died without the transplant, according to doctors
rutland said he began collecting money for tabatha last november
it seemed like somebody in the world should try to help this family,'' he said
ribner later organized a two-week, $1,400 drive at whittier middle school in flint
i always stress to my students to help their community, to not always take for yourself,'' he said
joe williams, a pittsburgh attorney representing tabatha and her parents, roy and sandra foster, said the $14,000 gift is the largest one so far. it brings total contributions to $320,000, leaving about $225,000 in unpaid bills
contract bridge players in france, italy and the united states sat down saturday to play one another in a computer-linked game
a computer dealt 32 bridge hands to 80 players in milan, italy; 80 in paris; 100 in houston, texas; and 244 playing in buffalo at the north american bridge championships, sanctioned by the american contract bridge league. each table of four players in each city got the same cards for each hand
the system, first demonstrated in buffalo on friday, dealt the cards in trays in one city while dealing identical bridge hands in the other cities
dubbed ``bridging the world,'' the international game was described by sherri rosen of the bridge league as the first world competition with computer-generated bridge hands and instant scoring
it will give players here in buffalo a chance to see how they can compete against people in other parts of the world,'' she said
the scoring, she explained, was to be done in paris and the results transmitted to buffalo
the buffalo players also were competing among themselves in the men's and women's pairs finals of the spring championships. at the same time they were competing in the international game against players in the other three cities
they came to buffalo expecting to be in the men's and women's pairs, but didn't expect to play an intercontinental match,'' said ms. rosen
the 10-day spring championships, one of three major tournaments that the american contract bridge league runs each year, have attracted about 5,000 bridge players to buffalo. info-changes grafs 1-11. pick up 7th graf pvs: a source close to...</note>
gen. manuel antonio noriega rejected washington's demands that he resign and leave the country, his press office reported saturday
the military strongman also purged more officers from the defense forces he commands in a move to strengthen his position
his press office said noriega met friday with ``some state department representatives'' and rejected their proposals for him to leave the country ``as being unacceptable, illogical, and anti-panamanian.''
the statement did not name the state department representatives, but it was known that william walker, a ranking member of the department's latin american affairs bureau, met with noriega friday
in washington, a reagan administration official said noriega had indicated a willingness to step down as panama's military chieftain but was unwilling to go into exile, as the united states insisted
opposition leaders called for a general strike monday to protest a nationwide state of emergency that restricted civil liberties
walker, a deputy assistant secretary of state, reportedly was empowered to tell noriega the united states would not seek to extradite the general on drug trafficking charges if he accepted asylum in a third country, possibly spain or france. noriega was indicted on the drug charges by a federal grand jury in florida last month
the defense forces press statement gave no details of the american proposal, but said that while noriega rejected it he ``totally reiterated his position of keeping the doors open to dialogue.''
it said noriega and members of his high command met with the washington envoys and he and his officers ``are prepared to hold all necessary conversations to resolve the panamanian problem, but without any type of conditions and always with the talks taking into account national interests.''
the reagan official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the united states was insisting that the general leave the country for fear he would continue exercising influence even after resigning from his official post
diplomatic and other sources said noriega appeared to be consolidating his base of power through the purges in the defense forces after rejecting the u.s. demands
a source close to the military said 15 colonels and majors have been forcibly retired or moved out of key positions since the head of the national police tried to remove noriega in an unsuccessful coup on wednesday
noriega's high command has acknowledged only five retirements and one major demotion, the transfer on saturday of col. lorenzo purcell from chief of the air force to an unspecified headquarters desk job
the defense forces admit to holding five officers, including the former police chief, col. leonidas macias, arrested wednesday morning when the attempt to take over noriega's headquarters went awry
but the source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 12 officers have been arrested, ``three or four are in hiding and quite a few more are suspected and being investigated _ up to 100.''
the latest military purges came a day after the civilian government, which answers to the general, declared a state of emergency aimed at putting panama's tottering economy back on track. the move prompted an opposition coalition known as the national civic crusade to call for an indefinite, nationwide general strike for monday, hoping to give a coup de grace to the economy and a final push to noriega
the united states has been pushing for noriega's ouster since he was indicted in florida
the planned work stoppage comes at a time when many major industries and smaller businesses already are closed by wildcat strikes or a lack of business caused by a critical cash shortage
the cash crisis became acute on feb. 26 when noriega dismissed the nation's civilian president, eric arturo delvalle, prompting a panic run on bank deposits. most banks closed four days later after the government acknowledged it did not have enough money to meet the demand for withdrawals
then, on march 3, the government ordered all banks closed until arrangements could be made for their orderly reopening. they remained closed through last week
the government was unable to fully meet its payroll last week for some 130,000 public employees. most got only $75 of their semi-monthly wages
economic discontent erupted in violent public demonstrations wednesday after word of the coup attempt spread. workers went on strike at the state-run electric and water utilities, ports in panama city and colon, a main port 50 miles north, and a number of government ministries
the government ordered the military to take control of the utilities and ministries wednesday, but at week's end the strikes continued
meanwhile, last week's coup attempt was depicted as poorly planned and executed by several diplomatic, political and other sources
several, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the same story of a colonel who overestimated his chances, came to the coup unprepared and fell victim to foul luck
according to their version, macias lined up support of several officers with most of the rank-and-file of his own police force and went to noriega's headquarters early wednesday. he was accompanied by 12 other officers and a squad of policemen
but, according to the sources, when the group arrived at the walled military compound in the heart of the capital of panama city, macias decided they were too lightly armed. he and his fellow officers marched to the base armory and demanded that it be opened, the sources said
once the officers were inside, the door was slammed shut behind them and locked. macias' police detachment, left behind in a courtyard, quickly surrendered after headquarters guards began shooting over their heads, the sources said
a former policeman has been convicted of second-degree murder in the july 1978 slaying of two young advocates of puerto rican independence, but another former policeman has been acquitted
rafael moreno was found guilty of participating in the killing of carlos soto arrivi, 18, and arnaldo dario rosado, 24, after both had surrendered to police on a remote mountain top. former police lt. col. angel perez casillas was found innocent of first-degree murder
the slayings had caused political convulsions in the u.s. commonwealth, and its senate still is investigating the involvement of top-ranking government officials
the verdicts came friday in superior court after a trial that lasted more than two months
last august, five other policemen pleaded guilty to reduced charges of second-degree murder and perjury stemming from the case, and a sixth pleaded guilty to conspiracy and perjury. the six received sentences ranging up to 30 years
in march 1985, all eight were convicted of perjury for having lied to several federal grand juries investigating the killings. each was sentenced to terms up to 30 years
soto arrivi and dario rosado were killed by police after they went the mountain with an undercover agent. the agent said the two intended to sabotage a communications tower
police initially claimed the two were killed in a shootout when they resisted arrest, and then-gov. carlos romero barcelo of the pro-statehood new progressive party called the policemen heroes
but in hearings in 1983 by the senate, controlled by the popular democratic party, the youths were shown to have been executed at close range after having surrendered
the popular democratic party favors continuation of commonwealth status, while the puerto rico independence party favors independence, as do several extremist groups
senate president miguel hernandez agosto said earlier this month that evidence uncovered during the trial indicates high officials had planned in advance to entrap the youths
the government, which appointed a special independent prosecutor to investigate the killings, spent about $6.5 million on the case
the families of the victims won a $1.5 million out-of-court settlement from puerto rico last year after eight years of legal battles
puerto rico, about 1,000 miles southeast of florida, has been a u.s. territory since 1898. caucus and delegate numbers due to no-shows in two counties; picks up 11th graf pvs, bgng, `dukakis, who.'</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won the kansas democratic caucuses saturday, fending off the urban strength of jesse jackson who finished a surprising second
with 115 caucuses reporting, dukakis had garnered 278 local delegates for 36 percent, jackson had 235 delegates for 31 percent and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. 125 for 16 percent. another 114 delegates, or 15 percent, were elected in uncommitted status
missouri rep. richard gephardt got only 12 delegates and illinois sen. paul simon failed to pick up a single delegate. gephardt chose not to campaign in kansas, spending his time instead in michigan ahead of its caucus on saturday
no democrats turned out in greeley and wichita counties in far western kansas, reducing the number of caucus sites from 117 to 115 and the number of local delegates elected from 768 to 764
it's terrific,'' dukakis said at the jefferson-jackson dinner in detroit. ``we've had a major victory in kansas and feel good about it. now we're on to michigan and here we are.''
the massachusetts governor, asked about the significance of winning in kansas, said, ``i think it's the first farm and agriculture state that i've won and won decisively. i think that's a very good sign for the future.''
gephardt, speaking at the same detroit dinner, said he wasn't really concerned about kansas
we really didn't mount much of an effort there,'' gephardt said. ``our focus really has been on michigan over the last week and a half or two weeks.... i'm concerned about doing well michigan and i think we will.''
jackson beat dukakis in topeka and kansas city, and held him to a virtual draw in wichita. dukakis won in populous johnson county, which is suburban kansas city
dukakis won 42 delegates in johnson county to 20 for jackson and 19 for gore, and sedgwick county, which includes wichita, with 44 delegates to 40 for jackson and 31 for gore
jackson shocked most observers by winning shawnee county, which includes topeka, with 32 delegates to dukakis' 14 and gore's four, and claimed wyandotte county, which includes kansas city, as expected, with 44 delegates to 13 for dukakis and none for gore
twenty-six delegates were elected as uncommitted in the four metropolitan counties. gephardt got four of his delegates in johnson county, which borders missouri, but none in any of the other three big counties
dukakis, who had been organized in kansas far longer than any of the other contenders, had been expected to do well. his state chairman, paul feleciano of wichita, had predicted dukakis eventually would claim between 20 and 25 of the kansas national delegates
the first larger county to report was reno, just west of wichita
jackson, who didn't win any local delegates in reno county four years ago, got 75 votes from the 285 democrats attending. another 88 voted for dukakis, 79 for gore and 43 for gephardt
democrats attended 115 local caucuses, electing 764 delegates to congressional district conventions on april 23 at which 26 of kansas' 43 delegates to the national convention will be picked. four state party officials are automatic delegates and the final 13 will be named on may 14 by the state committee. derailed cars</head> with 4 grafs to update with evacuation over, leaks capped.</note>
twenty railroad cars, including nine hauling chemicals, derailed saturday, forcing authorities to evacuate an entire town of 1,700 people for seven hours, officials said
the derailment also led to a fire that destroyed an empty building, said deputy sheriff pat miller. no injuries were reported, however
some of the cars struck power poles as they derailed, knocking out electricity to the town for two hours, said a spokesman for northern states power co
a partial evacuation began when officials learned that two of the tank cars carrying methanol, a type of alcohol, were leaking, miller said
the decision to evacuate the entire town was made at 11 a.m., after it was determined another tank car carrying sulfur dioxide was damaged, said city council member val lawler. he said the car was not leaking, but the tanker's outer envelope was ruptured
miller said the other tank cars, carrying anhydrous ammonia, were not leaking
the car carrying sulfur dioxide was righted and stablized by early afternoon and leaks on the two methanol alcohol tankers were capped, said phil marbut, director of safety and hazardous materials for the minneapolis-based soo line. residents were allowed back in their homes shortly after 6 p.m
many residents had begun leaving the town immediately after the derailment, which occurred at 7:38 a.m., an official said. the state patrol also began closing off several highways to the town, about 40 miles northwest of minneapolis
hazardous waste crews from the minnesota pollution control agency were investigating, miller said
the cause of the derailment was not known, said soo line spokesman john bergene. the eastbound train consisted of 65 cars and the derailment occurred in the middle of the train, he said. to update with statement from noriega's press office; picks up 7th graf pvs bgng, `spain has'</note>
panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega indicated a willingness to step down as military commander but he rejected efforts by two u.s. envoys to persuade him to go into exile as well, an administration official said saturday
he wants to stay on. he wants to stay in panama,'' the official said, commenting on the outcome of meetings noriega had on friday with two state department officials who were dispatched to panama
noriega, at his request, met with deputy assistant secretary william walker and the state department's deputy legal adviser, michael kozak. the two were said to be planning a return to washington this weekend
the administration official, who asked not to be identified, said noriega indicated a willingness to step down as commander of the defense forces but made it clear he wished to remain in his country
other u.s. officials had said earlier that walker and kozak were prepared to tell noriega that the united states would not seek his extradition on federal drug-trafficking charges if he sought asylum in another country
the administration was willing to make that concession because of concern over the high stakes that the united states has in that country and the desire to end the political and economic chaos there
noriega's press office said saturday that he rejected the u.s. proposals for him to leave the country ``as being unacceptable, illogical, and anti-panamanian.''
the defense forces press statement gave no details of the american proposal, but said that while noriega rejected it, he ``totally reiterated his position of keeping the doors open to dialogue.''
it said noriega and members of his high command met with the washington envoys and he and his officers ``are prepared to hold all necessary conversations to resolve the panamanian problem, but without any type of conditions and always with the talks taking into account national interests.''
spain has said it would admit noriega, provided he asked for asylum and the united states did not seek his extradition
the u.s. official said that noriega's departure from panama is the minimum prerequisite for settling the crisis, which has featured widespread anti-noriega protests and the virtual paralysis of panama's economy
according to the official, the administration fears that any arrangement which does not include noriega's exile would enable him to continue his role as the dominant figure in panama's political life
noriega probably would be able to continue ``pulling the strings'' even if he resigned as chief of the defense forces, the official said
a series of legal actions and other measures taken by the reagan administration has effectively dried up the flow of dollars into panama, leaving the country's banking system in crisis and the government unable to meet its payroll
the official said the administration expects the situation in panama to worsen this coming week because of a general strike which has been called by opposition forces and the wednesday payday for the 20,000 defense force personnel
there was considerable doubt that the government has enough money to cover the military payroll, the official said
the crisis was touched off three weeks ago when president eric arturo delvalle attempted to fire noriega but instead was fired himself. delvalle, who has been in hiding ever since, is regarded by the united states as panama's constitutional president
the administration has refused to recognize the successor government in panama, nominally headed by president manuel solis palma. occurred in same building where parents lived but not same apartment; and to update with suspect transferred back to county jail. picks up 6th graf pvs, `authorities had...'. subs 10th graf, `one investigator...', to add that bodies found in upstairs apartment.</note>
a man shot to death four people, including his brother and a pregnant woman, for playing a stereo too loud, police said
earl losier jr., 32, of bangor was arrested at his parents' apartment, in the building where the shootings occurred, and was later charged in district court with murdering his 26-year-old brother, stephen, authorities said
more charges were expected to be brought in connection with the other slayings, said fernand larochelle, chief of the maine attorney general's criminal division
police identified the other victims as peter prendergast, 26, of brewer; michael prendergast, 31, of bangor; and sharon prendergast, 23, of bangor. preliminary autopsy findings indicated that ms. prendergast was pregnant, authorities said
losier, who entered no plea to the charge, was ordered held without bail and taken to the augusta mental health institute for a psychological examination. he was transferred saturday evening to the penobscot county jail in bangor
authorities had not determined how the prendergasts were related and what their relationship to the suspect was, said police lt. don o'halloran
bangor police detective roy e. mckinney said in an affidavit filed in court that losier told another policeman that he shot the four ``because he was taking cough syrup and because they were playing the stereo too loud.''
o'halloran also said that it appears losier was upset about noise ``but we really don't know ... why it escalated so rapidly.''
in his affidavit, mckinney told the court that two policemen were sent to the building and were told of a shooting by the defendant's mother, carol losier
one investigator went to an upstairs apartment and found four people with gunshot wounds, mckinney testified. a .45-caliber semi-automatic handgun was seized at the scene, police said
according to jeffrey hjelm, an assistant attorney general assigned to the case, two of the victims were taken to local hospitals for treatment but did not survive
hjelm would not elaborate on the circumstances of the shootings. he said the case would probably be taken before a county grand jury. town</head>
a handful of white supremacists led a peaceful march and rally saturday to protest a three-month black boycott of white-owned businesses, while some 300 blacks stood silently on the sidelines
white supremacist richard barrett and about eight supporters gathered on the steps of the adams county courthouse after a short downtown march
barrett, of jackson, and his followers marched despite efforts by natchez officials to prevent it
last month, the board of aldermen passed a parade ordinance that stipulated a 30-day waiting period. barrett said he notified the city of his intent to march before the ordinance was passed and filed for a temporary restraining order in u.s. district court
city officials agreed out of court to grant barrett the permit
we come to you in the name of freedom,'' barrett told the group, which included about 100 white onlookers. ``those of you who rob a merchant of his trade are guilty of breaking the law, `thou shalt not steal.'''
black residents started the boycott against white-owned business after charging that the school system was discriminatory against black students and educators
natchez-adams county public school superintendent claude porter recently resigned after weeks of pressure from boycotters. one of the signs carried by the white supremacists read ``back porter.''
some of the boycott organizers, including state rep. barney schoby, natchez alderman george hardin and adams county supervisor phillip west, flanked barrett and his followers on the courthouse steps, but remained silent
blacks carried signs that read ``we will be here when you're gone,'' and ``we've paid our dues.''
natchez police chief ken farily said 40 police officers in riot gear stood by during the parade and rally.    protection</head> honduran attack; pick up 5th graf pvs, `honduran armed ...'</note>
the defense ministry said honduran warplanes bombed sandinista positions saturday inside nicaraguan territory near the border
the nicaraguan statement said two american-made f-5 jets staged a 10-minute attack saturday afternoon in the bocay area about 65 miles northeast of managua, dropping four bombs against sandinista army positions but causing no damages
the ministry said that two f-5 warplanes flew over sandinista positions saturday morning in the frontier sectors of mukuwas, san andres de bocay, waniwas and wayawas, producing no damage
the defense ministry said the area of the saturday's attack was the same where honduran jets dropped several bombs on thursday
there was no comment from the honduran government on the nicaraguan report. honduras has several thousand soldiers in the bocay border area under orders to drive out any nicaraguan troops they find in honduran territory
the bocay zone is where honduras said sandinista troops invaded honduran territory last week to attack bases of u.s.-backed nicaraguan rebels, known as contras
honduran armed forces officials had said earlier saturday that the nicaraguans were withdrawing
president daniel ortega, speaking saturday before his government reported the honduran air raids, said he would ask the international court of justice for an injunction preventing military activities that could ``raise tension'' between honduras and nicaragua
the move appeared designed to step up political pressure on the united states, which last week sent 3,200 american troops to neighboring honduras as a warning to nicaragua
the tribunal at the hague, netherlands, also known as the world court, has no power unless both sides of a dispute agree to its jurisdiction
ortega made his announcement in a talk show appearance on government television during which he accused neighboring honduras of ``being an accomplice in the criminal activities'' of contra rebels against his regime
while he did not name the united states in his announcement, ortega appeared to be referring to the dispatch of american troops to honduras
ortega asked the court to issue an injunction calling for unspecified ``interim measures of protection'' against any military activities ``that could raise tension even more between honduras and nicaragua.''
in washington, reagan administration officials said the dispatch of troops to honduras was in response to an appeal for help by that country's president, jose azcona hoyo
azcona claims sandinista troops are still inside honduran territory. but the sandinistas say they are on their own side of the border chasing u.s.-supported contra rebels
ortega said his appeal was part of a lawsuit that nicaragua filed several months ago with the world court, demanding that it condemn honduras for allowing rebels to use its territory to mount cross-border attacks
honduras and the contras claim the rebel camps are on the nicaraguan side of the ill-defined, sparsely populated border. the sandinistas contend the camps are inside honduras
nicaragua's civil war has taken more than 40,000 lives since november 1981, when the contras began fighting the sandinista government. car bomb explosion, one injured, details</note>
surrounded by soldiers, harassed by a guerrilla ban on road travel and wary of violence, salvadorans vote sunday for a new national legislature and municipal officers nationwide
for the fifth time since a 1979 coup by reform-minded officers, citizens of this massachusetts-sized nation are casting their ballots in an open election. el salvador has a population of about 5 million
as before, they are doing it under less than ideal circumstances
on saturday night, a car bomb exploded in front of a movie theater in the affluent san salvador neighborhood of escalon. flying glass injured a woman ticket vendor
jorge medina, an employee of the cinema theater, said vendor cecilia torres was cut in the arm and back
the blast destroyed the car and damaged vehicles on either side
no group claimed responsibility. but leftist guerrillas said they planted a march 11 bomb that injured two people in san salvador, and have been accused of killing the mayor of a northern town and kidnapping a mayoral candidate last week
the election is for all 60 seats in the national assembly, the unicameral legislature. voters are also electing mayors and municipal councils in all the 262 cities and towns nationwide
the guerrillas, waging an 8-year-old war against the u.s.-backed government, reject the elections as ``a farce.'' they contend that, during wartime, popular will cannot be expressed at the polls
the rebels have been urging people to boycott the voting and declared a ban on all road transportation in an effort to disrupt the elections
the armed forces said 95 percent of the country's 56,000 troops have been deployed to deliver ballots and ballot boxes and to provide security at the 341 polling places set up throughout the country
the defense ministry said it could guarantee secure voting conditions in 244 of the 262 municipalities. voters in the other 18 provincial communities, located in areas under the virtual control of the guerrillas, are being allowed to cast ballots in the nearest town they can
but few are likely to do so because of the transportation ban
polls open at 7 a.m. and close at 5 p.m., and about 1.6 million people have registered to vote. early returns are not expected to be announced before midnight
more than 100 observers from 45 countries and several international organizations are on hand, including a 19-person delegation from the united states, headed by sen. richard lugar, r-ind., and representative john murtha, d-penn, to watch that the balloting and counting stays clean
the guerrillas have burned about 10 vehicles since they declared their ban on travel at dawn friday. most of the sabotage was in the eastern province of usulutan, but at least three taxis were reported burned in san salvador
traffic was drastically reduced in the capital and most of the country friday and saturday. but, between state-owned buses the government put into service and pickups converted by their entrepreneurial owners those who needed to get around san salvador could generally find a ride
in the elections, the governing christian democratic party of president jose napoleon duarte is expected to lose its majority in the assembly. the rightist republican nationalist alliance, commonly known by its spanish acronym of arena, is expected to make significant gains, but is unlikely to get a majority of its own
leftist parties declined to present candidates, contending the war makes a legitimate election impossible
the christian democrats have 33 deputies in the current assembly. arena has 13. the center-rightist national conciliation party has 12. there is one independent and one legislator from a small rightist party called paisa
presidential elections are scheduled for next march. the current campaign was characterized by mudslinging, with little emphasis on proposals for resolving the country's tremendous problems caused by the war
guerrilla squads late friday and early saturday blew up electricity transmission towers in several areas. the sabotage left the entire northern province of chalatenango without power, as well as the northern part of san salvador and parts of other provinces
the guerrillas on thursday warned people to avoid concentrating at polling places. the rebels said the heavy military presence at the stations make them ``military targets.''
jose antonio gonzalez, an 18-year-old student who will vote for the first time sunday, said he disapproves of both the transportation ban and the anti-election sabotage
it is a harsh reprisal against the people,'' he said, adding that he thinks the elections are legitimate ``because through elections, it is the people who decide what they want.'' update with report that u.s. denied honduran request that u.s helicopters ferry its troops to the battle zone, that alternative request for joint exercise will be approved, with report of honduran bombing raid along nicaraguan border area, comment from honduran official that sandinista troops pulling out, report that those troops were laying mines in honduran territory, denial from nicaraguan government; picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `reagan opened'</note>
president reagan blamed congress saturday for the nicaraguan border crossing into honduras, and said rebels fighting nicaragua's marxist-led government ``must have assistance now.''
in his weekly radio address, delivered from the oval office, reagan made his first substantial statement on central america since he ordered troops airlifted to honduras on wednesday
he said congressional rejection last month of renewed aid for the contra rebels in nicaragua was ``giving the communist dictators ... a chance to smash their opponents.''
because of congress' aid cutoff last month, the sandinistas have mounted their major cross-border incursion into honduras,'' he said
the freedom fighters are in desperate need of support,'' the president added. ``if they are to remain a viable and effective force, they must have assistance now.''
the president spoke as administration officials, on the condition they not be identified, were saying that honduran president jose azcona had asked that u.s. helicopters be used to ferry honduran troops to the fighting zone
the officials said no decision had been reached, but one said the request was likely to be approved, perhaps this weekend
the new york times, citing a senior administration official that it did not identify, reported in sunday's editions that the administration already had rejected a proposal to use u.s. helicopters to transport honduran troops to the battle zone
the urgency of the honduran request _ which never was made formally _ diminished as the sandinista offensive appeared to wind down, and u.s. officials were able to persuade honduras to accept a more limited alternative, the times reported. that alternative was a joint training exercise in which u.s. helicopters would carry honduran troops to about 30 miles from the nicaraguan border but 100 miles from the battle zone
the hondurans were expected to request the exercise formally, and the united states will agree, the official told the times
white house spokeswoman liz murphy said late saturday that no decisions had been made on whether u.s. helicopters would ferry honduran troops to or near the border and said all queries should be directed to the pentagon
maj. bill o'connell, a pentagon spokesman, said he knew nothing about it and nancy beck, a state department spokeswoman, said she had no comment
one official, also speaking on condition he not be named, told the associated press that the nicaraguan forces were withdrawing from honduras. according to administration estimates, 1,600 to 2,000 sandinista soldiers had crossed the border
this official said the contra rebels remained an effective fighting force, but faced serious short-term supply problems
col. manuel suarez benavides, the honduran armed forces spokesman, said in a telephone interview saturday that the nicaraguan troops were withdrawing from honduran territory and that only about 600 sandinista soldiers remained inside honduras
this is a good sign on the part of the managua regime, so that peace can prevail in central america,'' he said
however, the nicaraguan defense ministry said saturday night that honduran warplanes had bombed sandinista positions inside nicaragua in the bocay region, the same area where honduran jets had dropped several bombs on thursday
there was no immediate comment on the nicaraguan report by the honduran government, but the washington post reported in sunday's editions that honduran national radio said the bombings were of nicaraguan positions in southern honduras. the radio said the raids were ordered after u.s. and honduran intelligence found nicaraguans laying mines in 50 square miles of honduran territory as they withdrew
a nicaraguan defense ministry spokesman denied that troops were sowing mines in honduras, the post reported
reagan opened his radio speech with a reference to a jovial get-together on thursday with congressional leaders, saying, ``there was a nice celebration of st. patrick's day up on capitol hill this week; but believe me, that wasn't the only reason congress knew i had my irish up.''
just as the heroic efforts of the democratic resistance have forced the communists to cut back on their aggression abroad and to make peace concessions, the congress in a close vote, decided to cut off aid to the freedom fighters,'' he said
the president scoffed at the notion that the halt in aid amounted to ``giving peace a chance,'' as some of its supporters argued
instead,'' he said, ``the aid cutoff is giving the communist dictators a chance, a chance they long hoped for. a chance to smash their opponents.''
the president said the sandinistas had responded by hardening their negotiating posture, firing cardinal orlando y bravo as mediator and sending ``mobs of thugs against peaceful opposition groups.''
and now, instead of negotiating for a cease-fire, they have launched a major military assault on the weakened contras _ invading democratic honduras in the process,'' he said
now from the beginning, our central american policy has been designed to prevent another cuba and to let the people of nicaragua win back their freedom and their independence from the soviet union on their own _ to do this without having to commit american military personnel,'' reagan told his radio audience
but now, because of congress' aid cutoff last month, the sandinistas have mounted their major cross-border incursion into honduras,'' he said
referring to his dispatch of u.s. troops to honduras to engage in exercises, the president said, ``our purpose is to send a signal to the governments and peoples of central america about the seriousness with which we view the situation.''
