the army announced friday it would follow the lead of the air force and begin testing buildings on its bases for the natural radioactive gas radon
the first structures to be tested will be day care centers, hospitals, schools and living areas,'' the army said in a statement
the next set of structures to be tested will be those having 24-hour operations such as operations centers, training areas and research, development, test and evaluation facilities. last to be tested will be all other routinely inhabited structures.''
all radon measurements will be completed by the end of fiscal 1991 (sept. 30, 1991),'' the service said
each building will be screened initially for 90 days, and any structure showing a radon level greater than 20 picocuries per liter of air will be scheduled for corrective action in six months or less, the army said
ultimately, any structure showing a radon level of 4 picocuries per liter or more will receive corrective sealing, the army added
radon is a colorless, odorless natural product of decaying uranium in the soil. medical research has indicated that exposure to high levels of radon may increase the risk of lung cancer. the environmental protection agency's guideline for radon exposure is 4 picocuries per liter of air
the air force announced plans to begin testing buildings on its bases around the world for radon last november. the navy and marine corps are said to be considering similar moves
during his visit next week, soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze will participate in a ribbon-cutting ceremony opening the washington end of u.s.-soviet ``risk reduction centers'' to improve communication between the two governments, the state department said friday
shevardnadze and secretary of state george p. shultz agreed last september to open the centers to exchange information under treaties to cut nuclear weaponry, avoid accidental war and reduce incidents at sea
the centers are far more sophisticated than the famous ``hot line,'' which president john f. kennedy and soviet leader nikita khrushchev set up after the 1962 cuban missile crisis to permit direct communications between soviet and u.s. leaders
state department officials gave reporters an advance peek at the center, a 12-by-18 foot room on the 7th floor of department headquarters, about a mile from the white house
access to the windowless room is by twin steel security doors, only one of which can be opened at a time, to prevent unauthorized access
inside are four computer consoles and color monitors; two for receiving data, one to transmit and one as a backup
the center will be manned around the clock by one communications specialist and a russian-speaking watch officer
david swartz, staff director of the center, said there is a corresponding installation in moscow but ``we don't know where it is.''
both sides have been testing the center since march 15 by sending hourly messages. the state department sent a map of the washington metro system on a data transmitter and the soviets responded on friday with a map of the moscow subway system. time for a page: about 150 seconds
swartz said the u.s. center cost $1 million
the centers, first proposed by senators sam nunn, d-ga., and john warner, r-va., are designed to exchange information under the proposed intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty and two pacts signed in the 1970s
they are the 1971 agreement on measures to reduce the risk of outbreak of nuclear war and the 1972 pact on the prevention of incidents on the high seas
the information could include notification of planned ballistic missile tests and hazards to navigation
the purpose of the nrrc is to help avoid situations that could lead through miscalculation, accident, of misinterpretation to a crisis,'' the department said
following are excerpts from the soviet-yugoslav declaration friday as translated from serbo-croatian by the associated press:
the socialist federal republic of yugoslavia and the union of soviet socialist republics stress the historic role and unpassable value of universal principles contained in the belgrade (1955) and moscow (1956) declarations, and especially: mutual respect of independence, sovereignty, territorial integrity, equality and non-interference in internal affairs in any form. their adequate implementation has played the crucial role in the normalization of inter-state relations and the development of all-around and stable cooperation. the two sides shall continue to adhere by these principles
the socialist federal republic of yugoslavia and the union of soviet socialist republics are building and advancing. their relations starting from the unconditional respect of particularities of the paths and norms of their socialist development and different international positions
proceeding from the conviction that no one has a monopoly over the truth, the two sides declare that they have no pretensions of imposing their concept of social development on anyone. the success of any path to socialism is tested through socio-political practice and confirmed by the results of social progress
the league of communists of yugoslavia and the communist party of the soviet union will strive to enrich cooperation and cultivate permanent political dialogue for the purpose of an exhaustive exchange of opinions and experiences about current issues of socialist development in the two countries, about socialism as a world process, about global issues of the world and social progress, and international cooperation and strengthening confidence between peoples
the two countries consider the development of socialist self-management, in keeping with the specificities of each country, to be of the highest importance. it ensures the genuine authority of the people and the freedom of the individual and is a dependable guarantee against any administrative-bureaucratic distortion of socialism, against dogmatism and voluntarism
socialism is at a crossing point, at the threshold of a fuller realization of material and spiritual potentials, of deepening humanistic bases
- the policy of non-aliignment is against imperialism, colonialism and neo-colonialism, apartheid and all forms of aggression, interference, violence, domination, hegemony and discrimination in political and economic relations and restrictions of international cooperation by narrow limits of existing groupings
the decisive step in the realization of this striving is halting the armaments race and opening an irreversible process of nuclear and conventional disarmament for the purpose of general and full disarmament under effective international control
realistic removal of the danger of a nuclear catastrophe, which implies a full and general liquidation of nuclear armament, represents the highest and most urgent interest of all peoples
this process has been opened by the treaty of the union of soviet socialist republics and the united states of america about destruction of the rockets of the medium- and long-range variety and thus encourages hopes of mankind for a safer future
it is indispensable and possible that, without delay, the preparation and conclusion of an agreement on a general and full ban of nuclear arms testing be taken up, with the strictest steps of control in this area, preventing militarization of the cosmos which belongs to mankind, and a ban and liquidation of all kinds of weapons for mass destruction
the two countries attach great significance to the respect of human rights and they strive for their full and consistent realization in the whole world
human rights and basic freedoms are unalienable, indivisible and mutually interlocked. a particular significance of those rights and freedoms enable man to take part in creating a condition of life, in disposing with the results of his work, and in directly influencing social and political relations in his own country
an explosion and flash fire at a sugar refinery burned at least seven workers friday, three critically, officials said
the blast caused heavy damage to the union sugar division of holly sugar corp. plant, said charlie johnson, a santa barbara county fire department spokesman
fire capt. jim trask said that the blast was caused by sugar dust but that investigators had yet to determine what ignited it
johnson likened the accident to grain elevator explosions, in which fine particles of wheat often are ignited by a spark. ``it appears to be very similar to a dust explosion common in the midwest,'' johnson said
three workers were in critical condition at marion medical center and were transferred to the burn center at sherman oaks community hospital, said ethel donati, a nursing supervisor at marion
four victims were in satisfactory condition at valley community hospital, said nursing supervisor maureen shannon
the blast occurred on the second floor of a six-story brick warehouse in a room where workers said different grades of sugar are sorted. the fire was contained quickly, johnson said
the plant, which produces beet sugar, is isolated from other buildings about 5 miles outside this town 125 miles northwest of los angeles
fire investigators were joined by inspectors from the state occupational safety and health administration, building inspectors and county health officials. holly sugar corp. has headquarters in colorado springs, colo
the international monetary fund on friday announced a $317 million loan to argentina that will help it pay back a $500 million loan from the united states and keep up with interest payments on its $50 billion foreign debt
the fund said the loan was granted because heavy rains, floods and lower market prices cut into argentina's earnings from the export of grain and oilseeds
the u.s. loan of $500 million, granted earlier this year, was intended to bridge over the period until the fund made its decision
an international monetary source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the fund also approved release of $225 million next week, part of a loan that depends on president raul alfonsin's government meeting its promises to the fund on new policies. the government has pledged to keep down its budget deficit and take other economy measures
argentina already owes the fund more than $3.5 billion
the decisions by its board of executive directors, which represents the 151 member governments, are expected to trigger release of loans to argentina promised by banks. the banks agreed to do their lending in tandem with the fund, disbursing their loans as the imf gave its seal of approval to argentina's efforts
the loans may provide only a temporary respite, since the need to pay interest is a continuing drain on argentina's dwindling reserves. some argentine political leaders have been pressing alfonsin to suspend interest payments, as brazil did last year. brazil has resumed payments, but arrangements have not been completed on the money owed from 1987
according to the world bank, debts of third world countries will amount to $1.245 trillion by the end of this year
argentina's troubles are compounded by inflation which reached 175 percent last year, more than twice the 1986 rate. economy minister juan v. sourrouille has predicted that this year's rate will be more than 100 percent and some forecasts have put it as high as 20 percent for march alone. with reax from machinists' union president; picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `but john'</note>
eastern airlines ``isn't above the law'' and should be penalized for trying to sell its east coast shuttle operation in violation of a court order, the union for the carrier's mechanics told a federal judge friday
but u.s. district judge john h. pratt said he would not grant the labor organization's request that he force frank lorenzo, eastern's chief executive, to appear before him to promise that he would halt efforts to shed the shuttle
pratt said at a hearing called to determine sanctions to be levied against eastern that he would announce the penalties monday
we're not going to, at this juncture, order mr. lorenzo to come in here and genuflect,'' pratt told lawyers for the international association for machinists and aerospace workers
the union also had asked pratt to order eastern to halt all efforts to gain federal permission to sell the shuttle, restore jobs to workers who retired after learning of the shuttle sale proposal, and fine the carrier $20,000 per day for any future violations of the judge's orders
on march 10, pratt found the miami-based carrier in contempt for trying to sell its profitable shuttle service to its parent company, texas air corp., for $225 million. lorenzo also heads texas air
pratt ruled that in trying to sell the shuttle, the financially ailing eastern was violating his july 2, 1987, injunction ordering the airline to maintain the status quo of its contract with the machinists
the union, which represents 12,000 employees, has argued that by selling the shuttle to another company set up by texas air, the labor group's bargaining power with eastern would be weakened seriously. the sale would have required the transfer of 6,000 eastern employees to the new company
we believe that, as a result of the order, negotiations will be normalized and we hope to reach agreement in a collective bargaining process that will be both satisfactory to the company and the union,'' said charles e. bryan, president of machinist's union at eastern
judge pratt was very straightforward and objective in his enforcement'' of the law, bryan said in a statement. ``he has restored our confidence in the federal courts and provided justice for all eastern airlines employees.''
joseph guerrieri, jr., lawyer for the machinists, said of lorenzo, ``he isn't above the law. eastern airlines isn't above the law. i think he has to come to understand that.''
but john j. gallagher, the attorney representing eastern, said the airline was now complying with pratt's orders and that there was no reason to compel an appearance by lorenzo. he said the machinists have long had a hostile relationship with eastern executives, even before lorenzo acquired the carrier
now there's a new management so there's a new black hat,'' gallagher said
labor and management at eastern have been battling for years. under lorenzo, eastern has tried a series of moves that the airline says are designed to increase efficiency but the union has claimed are efforts to break their power
the eastern shuttle serves washington, new york and boston
a federal grand jury indicted seven people in puerto rico, new york and florida on charges of belonging to a drug ring that sent cocaine and heroin to puerto rico, the fbi announced friday
three of the suspects were taken into custody in san juan and a fourth was arrested in new york, according to fbi spokesman angel berlingeri
he said arrest warrants have been issued for two suspects in puerto rico and one in fort lauderdale, fla
all seven are charged in the indictments opened friday with distributing and selling cocaine and heroin, berlingeri reported
he said more arrests are expected as a result of an investigation that started in the late 1970s of drugs shipped from new york and florida to puerto rico for sale on this u.s. commonwealth island
authorities reported one suspect, alberto aviles rodriguez, appeared voluntarily before u.s. magistrate justo arenas friday morning. they said juan r. berganzo romero and armando serrano miranda were arrested in san juan and taken into court in the afternoon. arenas ordered all three held without bail
the fbi said guiseppe tabbita was arrested in new york, but did not elaborate, and that a man identified as guiseppe pellerito was being sought in fort lauderdale
it said the others named in the indictment and being sought are puerto rican residents miguel reyes pantojas and joaquin beltran robles
the latest indictments came after hector rivera martinez and 15 other people were arrested in san juan on dec. 7. the fbi claims rivera martinez headed the ring
according to the fbi, the suspects sold heroin to undercover agents in july and august 1987. it did not specify the amount of heroin allegedly involved
conviction is punishable by from 10 years to life in prison and fines up to $4 million, according to authorities
the indictments alleges that rivera martinez was involved in drug trafficking in puerto rico since the 1960s. it says he hired tabbita and pellerito to send heroin and cocaine from new york and florida to puerto rico for processing and distribution, and that rivera martinez engaged in money laundering in puerto rico
after rivera martinez was arrested, authorities confiscated property valued at $1.5 million and a 16-foot boat. rights bill</head> update with cochran saying he will vote to sustain veto. picks up 13th graf pvs bgng: the measure ...</note>
civil liberties and religious organizations announced plans friday for a radio, newspaper and telephone campaign to combat fundamentalist preacher jerry falwell's assault on a major civil rights bill facing a senate vote tuesday
jerry falwell is a liar, and the truth is not in him,'' said the rev. john h. buchanan, chairman of people for the american way, the liberal lobbying group that is organizing the blitz with the support of major roman catholic, jewish and protestant organizations
falwell, chairman of the conservative moral majority organization, prompted a deluge of phone calls to senators' offices _ reportedly 80,000 calls in a single hour on thursday _ with his charge that the bill ``is the greatest threat to religious freedom and traditional moral values ever passed.''
in a ``special memorandum to pastors'' circulated last week, falwell said the bill, which he called the ``civil rights sodom and gomorrah act,'' might force churches to ``hire a practicing active homosexual drug addict with aids to be a teacher or youth pastor'' and allow the government to dictate sermons preached from the pulpit
buchanan, a baptist pastor in washington and former republican house member from alabama, joined mainline religious leaders and civil rights organizations at a news conference in denouncing falwell for ``spreading hysteria'' with ``scare tactics'' and ``obvious falsehoods'' about the bill
the measure, vetoed by president reagan on wednesday, was approved earlier this year by margins of 75-14 in the senate and 315-98 in the house, more than the two-third majorities necessary to enact the legislation over reagan's objections
the senate is scheduled to vote tuesday on overriding the president's veto, and house action will follow. approval by both chambers is required to put a vetoed bill into law
buchanan said that ``to help set the record straight,'' his organization will place radio advertisements in major listening areas over the weekend and will run newspaper ads in the washington post and usa today on monday
in addition, he said, people for the american way will spend the weekend phoning its 270,000 members nationwide to urge them to lobby members of congress in support of the bill
the anti-falwell ad campaign also will concentrate on newspapers in alabama, florida, south carolina and louisiana, buchanan said
the bill's foes, meanwhile, succeeded in persuading at least one senator who had voted for the bill, john w. warner, r-va., to change his mind
warner said friday he had decided to vote to sustain reagan's veto after his senate office received ``thousands of calls from virginians questioning how the law will be implemented and how it will impact their daily lives.''
sen. thad cochran, r-miss., who voted for the bill, said he also would vote to sustain reagan's veto, primarily because of the bill's unfavorable impact on homebuilders, farmers and some religious groups that the measure ``may encroach on separation between church and state.''
cochran said assistant senate minority leader alan simpson, r-wyo., told him he also intended to defect. but mary k. hill, a spokeswoman for simpson, said simpson had not decided which way he would vote
the measure was intended to overturn the supreme court's 1984 grove city decision, which restricted the scope of anti-discrimination laws. the court said the laws cover only specific programs receiving federal funds, rather than the entire colleges, corporations or other institutions under which the programs operate
advocates of the vetoed bill say it merely would restore institution-wide coverage that congress intended when it passed legislation banning discrimination against minorities, women, the handicapped and the elderly in federally financed programs
in an attempt to avert a house and senate override of his veto, the president proposed an alternative that would narrow the scope of the vetoed bill
among the groups joining the campaign in support of the bill were the leadership conference on civil rights, american jewish congress, u.s. catholic conference, american jewish committee, evangelical luthern church in america, american baptist churches usa, united methodist church, presbyterian church (u.s.a.), episcopal church, church of the bretheran and the national council of the churchs of christ in the u.s.a
water levels in the great lakes could drop as much as seven feet in the next 100 years because of a warming climate caused by man-made changes in the atmosphere, a federal hydrologist said friday
the forecast by dr. frank h. quinn of the national oceanic and atmospheric administration came as the great lakes commission at its semi-annual meeting criticized lakes-research budget cuts proposed by president reagan
quinn, speaking in chicago, said precipitation over lakes michigan and huron since 1965 has exceeded the average for the 20th century
the wet and cool climate of the past 20 years pushed the lakes to record high levels and may have produced a new norm for the lakes
however, this could be offset in the future by climate warming, which would have the opposite effect on lake levels,'' quinn said
computer simulations, based on expectations for the concentration of carbon dioxide and other chemicals in the atmosphere, suggest the warming climate could lower lake michigan and lake huron by three feet to seven feet in the next 100 years, and lake erie by two feet to four feet, said quinn, who heads noaa's great lakes environmental research laboratories in ann arbor, mich
the simulations suggest an average temperature increase of seven degrees over the great lakes basin, quinn said
in washington, the great lakes commission, an interstate organization that coordinates policy on issues affecting the lakes, released an analysis showing the reagan administration's budget would cut great lakes research funding nearly in half
the reagan budget for 1989 proposed $17.1 million in great lakes spending by the environmental protection agency, department of commerce and department of the interior, martin said. congress approved $32.7 million in spending on the programs in 1988
a former banker dying of aids has been charged with embezzling $1.3 million and giving some of it to gay charities
a federal indictment, made public thursday, accused william patrick debenport, 27, of using his position as manager of a first texas savings and loan branch to misappropriate the money
if convicted on all 15 counts, debenport could receive up to 75 years in prison and $75,000 in fines
debenport's attorney, j. stephen cooper, said in november that debenport used the money to buy luxuries for himself and friends but also donated some to gay charities, including $175,000 to a dallas home for aids victims
first texas has sued to recover the money from the home
debencourt was fired in june. cooper said his client began taking the money after being told by a doctor he had aids and had only a short time to live
cooper said debenport donated a small amount to a predominantly gay church and gave sums ranging from several hundred to several thousand dollars to as many as 15 friends
he also bought himself a luxury car and a $217,000 home, cooper said
seven palau lawmakers accused a house subcommittee friday of unreasonably delaying their country's independence with unfounded and unproven charges of corruption and narcotics trafficking
they warned that if the delay continues, the mid-pacific island chain will face a financial crisis and meanwhile might explore ``other political status alternatives'' than that already chosen, free association with the united states
the seven palau senators admitted that the islands had drug and other problems. but they had been ``permitted to develop unchecked'' during 40 years of u.s. rule, and could be attacked more effectively now by the new sovereign government with financing promised under the recently-approved compact with the united states
the palau senators raised the issues in a letter to ron de lugo, the virgin islands delegate, who is chairman of a house subcommittee on insular and international affairs
the letter took issue with charges of palau wrongdoing raised by de lugo and rep. morris k. udall, d-ariz., chairman of the house interior committee, in a march 2 letter to the chairman of the house foreign affairs committee, rep. dante fascell, d-fla
udall and de lugo said in their letter that palau was used as a transhipment point for heroin moving from southeast asia to the united states and that several unnamed ``senior palauan government officials have been identified to us as being connected'' with the traffic
palau, the last pacific territory still under u.s. trusteeship since world war ii, has entered into a compact of free association with the united states, now awaiting implementation by congress. other senate and house committees have voted final approval but de lugo and udall earlier this month held up action and raised the charges against unnamed officials of the government in koror, capital of the new republic
they also cited violence last summer surrounding a plebescite weakening palau's constitutional ban on nuclear weapons to accommodate the u.s. military, which counts on palau as a backup base if its forces are asked to leave the philippines
udall and de lugo have said the resolution implementing the compact won't be acted on until palau's courts rule on the legality of the plebescite approval, or opponents of it declare they won't renew a court challenge they had said earlier they withdrew because of intimidation
we urge that you do not permit the issue of alleged wrongdoing in palau to become tied to the approval of compact implementation,'' the seven senators said in their letter
palau, which has a population of less than 15,000 in its 200 islands, had repeatedly asked u.s. help against drug cultivation and trafficking but its requests were rarely honored, the letter said, asserting that subcommittee allegations of corruption and criminal acts lacked documentation
most of them ``are absolutely spurious and unfounded, and were made by a small group of discontented palauans under the influence of unknown outside elements ...'' it continued
we also believe that certain government officials including members of this national congress have been fueling this concern about irrelevant issues to further their individual political ambitions,'' it said
the 70-year-old founder of the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race crossed the finish line friday in fifth place, more than a day and a half behind the winner but still in the money
joe redington of knik collected $15,000 as one of the top 20 finishers in the annual anchorage-to-nome trek. herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref was a minute and 16 seconds behind as they arrived shortly after noon
for redington, who organized the first iditarod in 1973 but has never won, it was the fifth time he has finished fifth. nayokpuk will collect $12,000 for the no. 6 spot
susan butcher won the race wednesday night for the third time in a row. she finished in 11 days, nearly 15 hours ahead of her nearest rival, rick swenson of two rivers
redington pumped hard over the final couple of miles as he and nayokpuk made their run along the bering sea ice
i really had to work,'' redington said at the finish line
forty one mushers continued on the trail friday. some were more than four days from nome. the race began march 5
