torn and bloodstained from battle, regimental flags that led union soldiers into the breach at gettysburg and antietam face a new fight against the ravages of time, say museum curators trying to save them
many of the 30 silk banners at the civil war museum and library here remain rolled around their poles, as they were at the end of the civil war in 1865, with little protection against aging
some of the flags were wrapped with paper about 15 years ago to preserve them, but acids in the paper apparently foiled that effort. when several were gingerly unfurled last month for the first time since then, some turned to dust or broke apart
to me they are sacred. ... they are symbols of the ultimate sacrifice and love of country,'' said andy waskie, a member of the grand army of the republic, a group of descendants of union veterans which operates the museum. news digest: tegucigalpa, honduras _ honduras; managua, nicaragua _ nicaragua-sandinistas; washington _ us-panama; undated _ political rdp; phoenix, ariz. _ mecham; bern, switzerland _ sizing up yazov; washington _ north prosecution; chattanooga, tenn. _ old killing; nairobi, kenya _ kenya-election</note>
only 1 percent of $20 million in ``emergency'' u.s. military aid sent to honduras following a 1986 incursion of nicaraguan troops was used to respond to the attack, according to a secret report by congressional investigators
the $200,000 spent to respond to the four-day sandinista border raid in late march 1986 was used to airlift honduran troops to the remote jungle in southeastern honduras where the nicaraguan forces were attacking contra rebel camps and to provide them with field rations, according to the general accounting office
the remainder of the $20 million was used simply to speed up a schedule of routine purchases for the honduran military, most of them aimed at modernizing the country's armed forces, the gao found
the reagan administration will complain to soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze this week about his country's military aid to nicaragua but will not let the issue disturb preparations for a superpower summit, officials said
shevardnadze, due to arrive sunday afternoon, will hold three days of talks starting monday with secretary of state george p. shultz. lunch at the white house with president reagan is tentatively scheduled for wednesday
the aim is to clear the way _ especially on arms control _ for a reagan trip to moscow in may or june to sign another u.s.-soviet disarmament agreement
