u.s. businesses might have to pay billions of dollars in new taxes if the u.s. supreme court agrees that louisiana may tax a new orleans store for catalogs it had printed in and mailed from other states, the store's lawyer says
the case involves $43,937 in use taxes assessed against the d.h. holmes co. department store chain, but lawyers for both sides agree that the ramifications go far beyond that
i threw out the figure of $800 million at a meeting of the tax executive institute in new york. ... people said that was a half or a quarter of the taxes it would raise,'' william f. grace jr., an attorney for holmes, said in an interview
this first story in a four-part easter series, ``strangers no longer,'' deals with the new companionship among protestants and roman catholics in the quest for christian unity
on the flood-lit, greenery-bedecked platform stood the roman catholic pope, his raised hands joined with those of u.s. protestant and eastern orthodox leaders as they intoned the lord's prayer together
our father, who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name...''
out across williams-brice stadium in columbia, s.c., a sea of 65,000, mostly southern baptists and other protestants, also lifted clasped hands aloft, the prayer resonating in concert:
thy kingdom come, thy will be done, on earth as it is in heaven ...''
it was an unprecedented interlude, there in the overwhelmingly protestant south on sept. 11, 1987, as pope john paul ii led a billy graham-style service, using graham's advisers, pulpit and sound equipment, in conjunction with the widest array of american church officials ever assembled with a pope
we stand, side by side, to confess jesus christ, the one mediator between god and man,'' he said, ticking off the varied denominational leadership participating with him: methodist, baptist, lutheran, pentecostal, presbyterian, reformed, episcopal, catholic, orthodox, disciples of christ and others
brothers and sisters ... let us rejoice in this fellowship. and let us commit ourselves further to the great task which jesus himself urges upon us: to go forward along the path of christian reconciliation and unity.''
that impulse for unity, germinating among divided churches after centuries of conflict and antagonism, was implored by jesus on the night before his crucifixion
father, the hour has come,'' he prayed in that dark, tearful vigil on the mount of olives, pleading his followers ``may all be one ... so that the world may believe.''
that imperative, reiterated through the new testament, was a given for christians _ that having one lord, they were inherently one community. yet for centuries, they fragmented into hostile camps, spurning and vilifying one another
schismatic sects, apostates,'' rome labeled protestants, who inveighed against roman catholicism, ``the roman babylon, popism,'' and vied caustically among themselves. scattered pockets of that rancor remain
however, in a sweeping and comparatively brief span of the 20th century, the bitter enmity has largely vanished. the last 20 years have witnessed broad inter-church friendship and collaboration
the whole atmosphere has changed,'' said religion historian harry s. stout of yale university, noting that in television sermons it is generally impossible to tell a catholic from a protestant
it's one of the most important trends of the 1980s and it's on the rise,'' he said in an interview. ``christians of different denominations are coming together, recognizing a common enemy, whether you call it atheism, materialism or secularism. faced with a common enemy, they're realizing that they need each other, that they're in the same boat.''
congregations and pastors, once stiffly aloof and uncommunicative, have become trusting, sharing retreats and working together
for christ ``is our peace, who has made us both one, and has broken down the dividing wall of hostility,'' says ephesians 2 of differently descended believers. ``so then you are no longer strangers and sojourners, but ... fellow ... members of the household of god.''
the contemporary change began in the century's first half as protestantism and eventually eastern orthodoxy joined in councils and compacts, followed in the last 25 years by catholicism's transforming plunge into the convergent stream
it's called the ``ecumenical movement,'' meaning a global coming together. lately it has developed some uncharted currents beyond official banks _ or anticipation
it has moved far beyond the tinkling of teacups and the initial exuberance,'' said the rev. thaddeus horgan, assistant ecumenical officer of the u.s. roman catholic bishops. ``it has become so common it's often unnoticed. it has moved from adolescence into young adulthood.''
but the most prominent characteristic of the movement recently has been its growing power among the rank-and-file, creating an utterly new companionship and teamwork among protestants and roman catholics
a tide is rising and soon it will be felt on the quarter deck,'' said united methodism's foremost theologian, albert outler of dallas
it's like a half-full glass, he said, which, instead of filling from above, now is rising from the bottom. ``it's bubbling up in a way that it can burst out in new forms.''
outler, among the pioneering protestant observers at catholicism's reforming 1962-65 second vatican council, which unleashed the church's ecumenical involvement, added:
christians have discovered that they can live and work together, with or without official sanction or what used to be called organic unity. there's a sort of paralysis at the top, but a very vigorous grass-roots development and exploration _ not only in cooperative social action but in joint study, discussions and sharing in church life _ while official leadership has settled down into a kind of quiescence. ..
it's beginning to be the case that christian lay folk in general no longer believe that structural tinkering has much real impact for change, and they're turning to what may be more authentic, doing it themselves
the younger generation is growing up in this atmosphere, and denominational identities are being blurred. ... the new developments can't be calendared or predicted ... but i think we're actually moving more realistically in terms of basic essential ventures of christian unity than when we were so entranced by its theatrics.''
but the growing sense of community still has its dramatic moments. such was that juncture in the heavily protestant territory of columbia, s.c., where the pope met in an unparalleled interchange with the broadest cross-section ever of american protestant and orthodox leadership, black and white, mainline, evangelical and pentecostal
the 26 church leaders, in a joint statement read by african methodist episcopal bishop philip cousins, said the ``prayers and hopes of many american christians'' were for further steps in ``reconciling the divided people of god.''
later, at the end of the vast stadium service, the pope and the church leaders together raised their hands, pronouncing blessing on the multitude in unison:
the lord bless you and keep you. the lord make his face to shine upon you, and be gracious to you. the lord lift up his countenance upon you and give you peace.''
across that bible belt city of columbia, the church bells pealed
the second story in a four-part easter series, ``strangers no longer,'' reports on efforts for christian unity, dealing with the quiet, seldom-noted ties among roman catholics and protestants in bible scholarship and worship
in a gray stone building called adams house at princeton university, 30 scholars pray, discuss their agenda and progress reports, then divide in half and go to work in separate rooms
each is stocked with reference books, reproductions of hebrew and greek manuscripts, grammar books and biblical commentaries
the participants are protestant, roman catholic, eastern orthodox and jewish experts on the bible, and in the two sections _ old testament and new _ they are working on a revised translation
so far as this book is concerned, we're essentially at one,'' said the rev. bruce metzger, a presbyterian and head of a committee working on a new revised standard version, the protestant-sponsored bible that also has roman catholic approval
biblical scholars of roman catholic and protestant affiliation approach their work in terms of scholarship with little if any differences remaining,'' metzger said in an interview. ``the lines of distinction have meted away.''
that common treatment and usage of the bible has become a powerful undercurrent in their advance toward unity. work on the book is seen as the inner glue, acting from within to mend the ruptures
traditional differences are not relevant,'' said catholic old testament scholar conrad l'heureux of the university of dayton. ``we have lots of debates, but they don't fall along denominational lines. ... it's become second nature to get at what the text says objectively without bringing the perspective of your own church into it
in an odd sense, biblical scholars are ahead of the crowd.''
it's a wave of the future,'' agreed catholic bible scholar william holladay of andover-newton theological seminary in massachusetts. ``it may well bring everybody else along. confessional differences may seem to divide people on saturday and sunday, but they don't make any difference when it comes to biblical work.''
besides the joint scholarly work, most american christians hear identically worded biblical passages each week in worship services
for the most part, they aren't aware of it,'' said the rev. monsignor alan detscher of the u.s. catholic conference's liturgy office in washington, d.c. ``they generally experience only the scripture readings in their own church and aren't aware the passages are now mostly identical that sunday in other churches.''
this synchronization of scripture readings came about through a widely used common lectionary, the three-year cycle of bible lessons read in church and based on the roman lectionary developed since the reforming 1962-65 second vatican council
in most mainline denominations, roman catholic, episcopal, lutheran, presbyterian and united methodist, ``the readings now are generally the same and follow the same pattern,'' detscher said
for instance, last weekend on palm sunday, march 27, marking jesus' triumphant entry into jerusalem a week before his arrest and crucifixion, the epistle read in most protestant and catholic congregations was philippians 2:6-11, saying in part:
he ``emptied himself, taking the form of a servant, being born in the likeness of men. and being found in human form, he humbled himself and became obedient unto death, even death on the cross.''
provisions are made for shorter or longer readings and for alternative passages. the weekly pattern may get off schedule by a week or two, longer in periods not linked to major christian seasons, and the simultaneous passages are not adhered to in evangelical-style congregations
in many places, neighboring protestant and roman catholic pastors ``get together to prepare their homilies because common scripture materials are being used,'' detscher said
sharing the same texts on which to preach, they trade ideas for sermons, something that also makes for intellectual cross-pollination
the rev. roland murphy of washington, d.c., a catholic bible scholar, said that people's ``hearing the word of god sunday after sunday in the same readings, more or less, is creating a bond of unity that didn't exist before.''
protestant and catholic liturgies also have become increasingly parallel structurally, so that a casual visitor cannot tell in most respects whether he's at a catholic, episcopal or lutheran service
people no longer feel uncomfortable going to one another's churches,'' detscher said. ``from total separation in worship we've moved to a commonality in worship. slowly but surely, we've come a long ways toward unity. now that we're beginning to pray the same way, maybe we'll start believing that way.''
of course, the touchstone catholic-protestant barrier remains officially in holy communion, the central act of worship in which joint participation is so far barred. but even that sharing happens occasionally, quietly
in places, it's taking place casually, although it's not really kosher,'' said united methodist theologian albert outler of dallas. ``all kinds of protestants are at roman catholic altars, and catholics at protestant altars. they're beginning to think of ways to have pulpit and altar fellowship without the bureaucrats bothering them.''
however, one of the strongest approved links is common appreciation for the bible and study of it, something formerly inhibited by catholicism but now heartily encouraged
the transition came at the second vatican council, which urged general reading of the bible, including translations produced in cooperation with protestants
previously, ``reading or studying the bible was regarded as a protestant characteristic,'' said a catholic new testament scholar, the rev. raymond e. brown, adding ``that picture has changed dramatically.''
brown, who teaches at new york's interdenominational union theological seminary, said american catholicism had ``moved from scarcely mentioning the bible to a situation where the bible has become a fundamental referent in catholic theology, spirituality and religious discussion.''
the fresh, broad regard for the bible prompted a mutual searching of ecumenical origins, a refocus on roots, drawing churches closer to that common ground
in academic circles, catholics and protestants commonly teach at each other's schools and seminaries. protestant and catholic scholars, now often members of the same professional organizations, have become an interacting, underlying intellectual stratum that nourishes the whole enterprise
sometimes there is greater loyalty among those in professional societies than to their own seminary or denomination,'' said yale's paul minear, a united church of christ bible scholar. ``they're building lines of communication that simply ignore denominational identities.''
he said scripture scholars and theologians are ``much more united than church hierarchies. it just shows that what preserves the different denominations is a set of non-theological factors. historic conditions keep them apart institutionally.''
with theological training becoming more similar, with protestant and catholic worship and sermons more alike, with scholars working together, it's ``going to make an enormous difference in the long run in creating a sense of commonalty,'' said lutheran theologian george lindbeck
asked if this common undergrowth might eventually sprout into full-scale christian unity, he said:
if the urge becomes stronger, then the similarities will make it much easier. things could take off very quickly. but it's likely to require major external events, something to catalyze it.''
the third installment of a four-part easter series, ``strangers no longer,'' concerns with the protestant-catholic convergence toward unity, dealing with official dialogues
from across christianity's denominational spectrum, reactions to a proposal for unity have poured into the headquarters of the world council of churches in geneva, switzerland
the response has been tremendous,'' said the rev. gunther gassman, a lutheran and director of the council's faith and order commission, an inclusive protestant-roman catholic-eastern orthodox unit that is compiling the appraisals
it's a unique thing in the history of the ecumenical movement,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``never has there been so much interest and discussion of a church document throughout the world.''
roman catholic, protestant and eastern orthodox denominations, 170 of them from around the globe, have sent official responses to an agreement jointly produced by their thinkers on a reintegrated faith
bem,'' it's called, standing for the central aspects of baptism, eucharist (celebrating the lord's supper) and ministry
sometimes called the ``lima text,'' it was produced by a commission of 120 theologians, bible scholars, historians, clergy and lay leaders at a meeting in lima, peru, in 1982
we have become increasingly aware of our unity in the body of christ,'' they said. ``sadly divided churches have been enabled to arrive at substantial theological agreements. we believe many significant advances are now possible.''
to that end, bem circulated among the churches for five years, translated into 35 languages. after pondering, the denominations have now voiced their assessment, the broadest ever attained in an ecumenical accord
it's a towering achievement,'' said the rev. john hotchkin, ecumenical officer for u.s. catholic bishops. ``it could serve to put a new floor under the ecumenical movement. it's a very important landmark.''
the vatican also appraised the document, generally commending the results, but asked for further elaborations, especially on the ministry
the responses are being distributed to the churches in six volumes, with the last two still to be compiled. a summary will be considered by the joint commission at a meeting in august 1989, and any clarifications and adaptations will be taken care of before the final document is presented to churches by 1991
then it's up to them,'' gassman said. ``our strong hope is that they act on it in the next 10 years, initiating some form of eucharistic sharing. many of them are ready to do so now.''
bem offers concordant beliefs about key functions of the church, drawing on common biblical roots and christianity's centuries prior to the 1054 schism that separated rome and eastern orthodoxy and the 16th-century protestant break from rome
the document challenges present-day churches to affirm this common, early core of faith. baptism of infants as well as adults is recognized, with precedents for each in practices of the early church
regarding the eucharist, the approach goes behind the medieval catholic doctrine of ``transubstantiation,'' upholding instead a broader concept of christ's ``real presence'' in celebration of the lord's supper
on the ministry, bem recommends a threefold tier of bishops, presbyters and deacons. most major churches have all three, but usually refer to presbyters as pastors, priests or ministers. some protestant bodies avoid the term bishop but have parallel overseeing offices under other titles
the responses have been as varied as the denominations. the vatican's 40-page response wasn't as long as the salvation army's 70 pages, the longest. the shortest, a half page from the presbyterian church of new zealand, simply said fine, let's go with it
we've made an enormous lot of progress in the churches' acceptance of each other,'' said the rev. john deschner, a united methodist from southern methodist university's perkins school of theology in dallas, who chairs the world council commission. ``a trust has developed among protestant, catholic and orthodox churches that is beyond what we'd ever dared hope
bem culminates the rising pleas for increased acts of mutual recognition of members and ministry, a kind of unity of mutual hospitality, welcoming each other in each other's denominational context, acknowledging each other before god.''
paving the way for bem has been a swelling profusion of dialogues and surprising accords among the denominations
on national and international levels, the bilateral talks have gone on 20 years between teams of catholics with lutherans, with methodists, with anglicans, with baptists, with disciples, with eastern orthodoxy, with presbyterians, with pentecostals, with evangelicals
at the same time, protestant bodies have met with one another, scrutinizing their respective views, seeking closer understanding and concurrence
it has become a vast, interconfessional conversation, a constant to-and-fro hum of inquiry, explanation, discovery and, often surprisingly, consensus
the talks probe the tangle of mutual misconceptions, mistaken impressions and caricatured images accumulated through centuries of alienation from one another
they seek to clear up where each really stands. on many points, it turns out to be together
for instance, lutherans and anglicans in separate dialogues with catholics determined they basically agreed on a key issue of the 16th-century protestant reformation that had divided them
protestants emphasized ``justification by faith'' alone, that salvation comes only through faith in christ's forgiving grace, and asserted that rome claimed the church dispensed grace for earned merit
but it turns out that arguments in the heat of old battle were misconstrued on both sides. they now agree _ as the u.s. lutheran-catholic team put it _ that ``our entire hope of justification and salvation rests on christ jesus'' and his forgiving grace
similarly convergent views have been found about the papacy itself, with anglicans and lutherans agreeing on the benefit of a unifying center, a presiding bishop of a pastoral rather than juridical kind, responsible to regular ecumenical councils
the deluge of dialogue reports have dealt with virtually all basic issues of churchmanship _ spirituality, scripture, apostolic succession, conversion, worship, grace, authority, the holy spirit, family, mixed marriages, salvation and papal primacy, usually with degrees of agreement
so much is happening, there is so much development that it's hard to keep up,'' said catholic brother jeffrey gros, who heads the faith and order office of the u.s. national council of churches
in a book summarizing a score of such understandings, ``growth in agreements,'' lutheran scholar harding meyer and reformed scholar lukas vischer say the dialogues ``constantly point beyond themselves,'' so the main aim no longer is ``just reaching of consensus but translation ... into practice in the living fellowship of the churches.''
many issues remain unsettled between rome and protestantism on such issues as ordination of women, which catholicism and orthodoxy forbid. but anglicans and catholics, in new talks, are discussing it
different shades of understanding, terminology and doctrinal nuances also linger, as do conflicts on social issues such as abortion and divorce, along with bureaucratic inertia
the ecumenical movement is a glacier,'' said lutheran bishop herbert w. chilstrom, head of the newly unified evangelical lutheran church in america. ``it moves slowly, but it does move.''
the fourth and final installment of an easter series, ``strangers no longer,'' focuses on grass-root activities in protestant-catholic efforts toward christian unity.  
in the little town of beaverton, ore., the mission of the atonement has both roman catholic and lutheran members. across the country at holy apostles' church in virginia beach, va., members included episcopalians and catholics
we're one model of how the church can put itself back together,'' the rev. ray barton, catholic co-pastor of holy apostles', said in an interview. ``it's a harbinger of the future.''
added the rev. donald gross, holy apostles' episcopal co-pastor, ``it's a sign of how it might be possible for the two traditions to live together, a sign of the church united.''
the combined congregations, authorized by bishops on both sides, worship together in opening services. then they split in two, as church rules now require, for their main liturgies, including holy communion, using in weekly turns the sanctuaries or adjacent fellowship halls
about everything else _ sunday school, adult christian education, home study and social outreach _ is done together
it seems critical that the christian church give an example to the world of how to express our unity and yet respect our diversity,'' said the rev. dale jamtgaard, lutheran co-pastor in beaverton
it may be a little like royalty getting hitched between nations,'' said beaverton's catholic co-pastor, the rev. mathias tumulty. ``it's a way to get to know and understand each other personally and care for each other. if it's possible here, maybe it's possible elsewhere.''
such signs of the underlying bonds get a rousing display may 21-25 when an expected 3,000 protestants, evangelicals and catholics hold a national ``gathering for christians'' in arlington, texas
it is to bring out that ``we are no longer strangers'' and to ``honor and proclaim jesus christ whose cross and resurrection bring peace with god and humanity,'' said the rev. eileen linder, ecumenical officer of the national council of churches, which is putting together the event
this inter-christian linkage has grown dramatically, showing up in myriad protestant-catholic covenants and compacts at national and local levels
i'm always struck with the developments of the last two years,'' said the rev. john hotchkin of washington, d.c., the u.s. catholic bishops' ecumenical officer, ``the neighborhood coalitions, the working together in programs for the elderly, for people in need, recycling clothes, common feeding pantries, drug counseling for young people, shelters for the homeless
there's not much about it in the press, and people don't sense anything remarkable about it anymore, but it's really quite striking.''
the alliances take many forms. in brooklyn, n.y., churches joined in a huge interfaith project to build 5,000 low-cost houses for poor families. called the nehemiah project after the fifth-century prophet who rebuilt ravaged jerusalem, churches have pooled $15 million, with 1,000 houses already up
in houston, about 200 congregations are involved in a citywide aids education and care effort
in this crisis, denominationalism is just religious history,'' said the rev. earl shelp, the baptist co-coordinator of the program
churches in seattle outfit rooms for the homeless
through the center for corporate responsibility in new york, 19 protestant denominations and 210 catholic orders and dioceses use their $10 billion in stock holdings to sway business practices for social good
leaders of 40 denominations are involved in the religion alliance against pornography, with local units functioning around the nation. included are churches of the national association of evangelicals, which generally shun ecumenical efforts
catholics and protestants have banded together in such groups as bread for the world, witness for peace, clergy and laity concerned, interfaith hunger appeal, the american bible society and even an organization for laughs, the fellowship of merry christians
they've teamed up in civil rights causes, the farm crisis, the sanctuary movement to shelter central american refugees, backed one another's declarations on the american economy and against nuclear weaponry
spiritually, the togetherness shows up with uninhibited fervor among groups of charismatic christians, 40,000 of whom met in new orleans superdome last july, an ecumenical jamboree of prayer, singing-in-tongues and arms-high praises to god
local ``covenants'' have developed, with participants promising to pray for each other, to share resources, retreats, studies and facilities and work together in social betterment projects. more than 100 such covenants are estimated functioning between catholics and episcopal, lutheran, united methodist, presbyterian and other protestant congregations
in riverside and north riverside, ill., eight congregations _ two roman catholic, two lutheran, two presbyterian, one episcopal and one united methodist _ are linked in a covenant, with an eye to eventual unity
covenants pairing two congregations, usually catholic and episcopal or lutheran but also involving others, have arisen around the country _ in kentucky, massachusetts, wisconsin, new york, oregon, rhode island, colorado and elsewhere
they keep popping up here and there,'' said sister ann teresa nagy of the graymoor ecumenical institute in garrison, n.y. ``as a result of dialogues and meetings, they realize how close they are. ... they're learning how to live together, work together and be at one.''
in wyandanch, n.y., the parishes of trinity lutheran and our lady of miraculous medal once asked the vatican to permit inter-communion, but were turned down ``for the time being.''
catholic and episcopal dioceses have entered covenants in kansas city, mo.; san diego; little rock, ark.; seattle; providence, r.i.; milwaukee and chicago
in local communities, churches often ``are working together more closely than they are with their national headquarters,'' says veteran ecumenical theologian paul minear. ``something is happening there by way of real christian unity that does not follow traditional church lines.''
additionally, major mergers among protestants are being discussed or have occurred, two sealed in the 1980s reuniting northerners and southerners in the presbyterian church (usa) in 1983 and merging three lutheran branches into the evangelical lutheran church in america at the start of 1988
another gradually unifying process is at a decisive stage among nine u.s. denominations
this year is a watershed for us,'' said the rev. gerald moede, general secretary of the consultation on church union. five of the nine denominations will act on the plan in 1988 _ the episcopal church, united methodist church, presbyterian church (usa), the african methodist episcopal church and the african methodist episcopal zion church
the united church of christ and christian church (disciples of christ) decide next year. the two others already have approved _ the christian methodist episcopal church and the international council of community churches
we're looking for a new common identity in which we'd be related, yet preserve our diverse traditions,'' moede said, noting the ``covenanting'' plan would maintain present structures but bring sharing in ministry and communion
the objective is not one huge institution,'' he said. ``one thing we've learned is that not everything should be given up or changed. the early church had great diversity, and we want to preserve that diversity.''
bond traders are frustrated and would-be homeowners thrilled by the eerie calm that has overtaken the credit markets during the past several weeks. for the first time in quite a while, you can almost bank on interest rates
this has been one of the quietest periods i've ever seen,'' elliott platt, an economist at donaldson lufkin &amp; jenrette securities inc., said in describing recent trading for bonds, notes and other debt-related products
if there was a word that could be milder than calm that would be appropriate,'' added f. ward mccarthy, chief financial economist for merrill lynch capital markets
in the treasury market, trading has slowed substantially. according to the federal reserve, the average daily dealer transaction was around $90 billion in the week ending march 9, at least $10 billion below the norm
some economists say the flatness in the credit markets, which set the trend for consumer and business rates, can be attributed to conflicting economic signals. others say the markets are just taking a break after starting the year on a somewhat volatile note
whatever the reasons, most predict that interest rates will remain fairly stable, at least through the spring
from the consumer standpoint i think the fact that we've had some stability has been reassuring. volatility in recent years has taken its toll on consumer confidence,'' said mccarthy, who described as comfortable the current level of interest rates
the yield on the treasury's 30-year bond, the most-watched debt security, has remained in a fairly narrow range since late january, fluctuating around 8.5 percent _ the same level as the current prime lending rate
mortgage rates have inched their way downward so far this year but have remained fairly level in recent weeks, too
the average rate charged by commercial lenders on a fixed-rate, 30-year mortgage has been just below 10 percent since early february, according to the federal home loan mortgage corp. the rate on adjustable mortgages has hovered around 7.5 percent in recent weeks, freddie mac said
compared to a year ago, there isn't too much change. however, rates are at least two percentage points lower now than they were around the time when the stock market crashed last october
after the market plunged, the fed eased its credit policies, allowing interest rates to fall, to prevent the economy from falling into a recession. lately, some signs of economic growth have surfaced, mingled with reports to the contrary
in light of the mixed signals, analysts say the fed has indicated it will maintain a fairly stable policy through the spring
the government has intimated it was more concerned about high inflation than a recession,'' said elizabeth g. reiners, assistant director of money market reserach for dean witter reynolds inc. ``it looks like inflation is at a comfortable level
if you keep policy stable, you're looking at stable rates.''
among the benefactors of stable rates have been homebuyers and those looking to refinance loans or borrow for other big purchases
knowing that rates aren't likely to swing wildly ``means that people have more freedom of choice about when to do their home buying and moving,'' said carol a. stone, a senior economist at nomura securities inc
corporations and municipalities looking to sell their bonds and notes also have felt less pressured
if they're considering a deal it gives them a little more leeway ... because the market isn't moving wildly,'' said mrs. reiners
but the big losers, mrs. reiners said, have been bond traders, who make their money on the ups and downs of the market and investors looking for high-yielding securities
the nation's airlines embarked on a big gamble this past week
they hope their steeper fares and tighter restrictions on discount tickets won't overly upset customers, who have come to take for granted the cheap fares nurtured in recent years by the cut-throat climate of the deregulated u.s. industry
emboldened by robust passenger traffic in recent months, the big airlines put through major fare increases several weeks before they normally do _ jumping the gun on the peak travel season that starts in april
the october stock market crash triggered fears that consumer nervousness could cut sharply into air travel, but the major u.s. carriers have posted an average increase in traffic of 7 percent to 8 percent since new year's day from the same period last year
flush with those results, the airlines have increased their first-class, economy and discount fares by 15 percent to 85 percent, depending on the destination. they also tightened restrictions on their popular ``maxsaver'' discount fares, requiring that tickets be purchased seven days in advance instead of two
some discount tariffs were eliminated altogether. the changes hit hard at consumers who have to fly on short notice, especially business travelers
the fare increases amplified the upward trend in air fares that has prevailed for the past four or five months
it would seem the airlines run a very real risk of going too far,'' said paul schlesinger, an airline analyst for donaldson, lufkin &amp; jenrette securities corp. ``empty planes don't carry the debt.''
other analysts agreed that the airlines, in their bold grab for more revenue, could force themselves into a ``catch 22'' situation whereby the higher fares and restrictions scare too many potential passengers away
if that happens, fares could come back down as quickly as they went up. since the domestic airline industry was deregulated in 1978, it has become an increasingly nimble ``quick-change'' artist in responding to shifting market conditions
what you're really seeing is a marketing of airline travel the way retailers market,'' said robert joedicke, who follows the industry for shearson lehman hutton inc. ``fare policy is going to be a continual adjustment game.''
joedicke suggested that rounds of fare cuts are becoming as common as ``white sales'' of linen and other items offered regularly by department stores
this means that the latest increases in the cost of flying, while steep, do not necessarily signal a move toward a full-fare airline industry
besides, skeptics noted, some of the recent rise in traffic could be coming from passengers taking free trips on frequent-flier travel bonuses and triple-mileage awards. an estimated 8 million americans are enrolled in frequent flier programs and may be bumping paying passengers
many major airlines, believing that the frequent-flier giveaways have gotten out of control, have imposed restrictions on the plans or are thinking of doing so
in fact, some of the recent push toward higher fares may be an attempt to compensate for lost revenue from frequent fliers
the airlines take a negative risk with the triple mileage,'' said andrew geller, a transportation analyst for provident national bank in philadelphia. ``the question arises of who's got to pay for it _ the normal-fare people?''
all this does little to reassure the individual customer, who has been hit with a near-doubling of fares to some destinations
it's created a problem for us,'' said david perlman, president of dms travel, a retail travel agency in midtown manhattan. ``it just creates havoc with everybody.''
he noted, for example, that a one-way, unrestricted economy fare from newark, n.j., to chicago jumped under the new changes from $185 to $280. a first-class, round-trip ticket between new york and aspen, colo., now costs a hefty $1,200, up from $800
perlman said he has spent much of the past week explaining the changes to bewildered customers
in other business and economic news this past week:
_the federal government moved to calm depositors' fears and protect the nation's banking system by advancing $1 billion to banks owned by the troubled first republicbank corp. of dallas, the biggest banking company in texas
_r.h. macy &amp; co. sweetened its friendly merger deal with federated department stores inc. by $200 million cash to $6.3 billion, and a federal judge rejected campeau corp.'s attempt to overturn federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
