_american standard inc. accepted a nearly $2.5 billion cash tender offer from kelso &amp; co., an investment banking firm specializing in employee-led leveraged buyouts, spurning black &amp; decker corp.'s hostile advances
_j.p. stevens &amp; co. accepted a nearly $1 billion cash buyout bid from a private investment group over offers from its own management and rival west point-pepperell inc
_mesa limited partnership, controlled by oilman t. boone pickens, withdrew its $1.88 billion cash offer for homestake mining co
_henley group inc., which lost a court battle to block part of santa fe southern pacific corp.'s restructuring, abandoned plans to wage a proxy fight to gain seats on santa fe's board
_pillsbury co. reported a larger-than-expected quarterly loss and said it was negotiating to sell its godfather's pizza chain
_the president of manufacturers hanover corp., john r. torell iii, resigned effective at the end of the month to pursue outside business opportunities. torell, 48, had been stalled on his way to the chairmanship of the nation's sixth largest banking company
_the teamsters union set a new target of march 29 for its 6,700 member flight attendants to strike northwest airlines after getting a pledge that the carrier's mechanics and baggage handlers would honor picket lines
_led by a jump in purchases of ford motor co. vehicles, sales of domestic cars and light trucks rose 6.3 percent in early march from a year earlier, the automakers reported
_the government said the deficit in the broadest measure of u.s. foreign trade surged to a record $160.7 billion in 1987 as the nation fell deeper into debt to the rest of the world. the merchandise trade deficit, meanwhile, widened to $12.44 billion in january
_business inventories rose 0.4 percent in january, less than half the increase of the previous month, the government said
_u.s. industrial production edged up 0.2 percent in february as reductions in output at auto factories and coal mines offset gains in other areas. factories, mines and utilities operated at 82.4 percent of capacity for the third consecutive month
_the housing industry, after staggering for two months, enjoyed an 8.9 percent increase in construction activity in february
_the government revised its latest report on retail sales to show a 0.4 percent increase in february, a slightly smaller increase than reported a week ago
_a private survey found job prospects for both production and service workers are the brightest they have been in three years but are declining slightly for technical, professional and office workers
_britain's conservative government unveiled a sweeping reform of the nation's tax system, slashing rates for higher income groups
_japan overtook the united states last year in economic output per person, according to a japanese government report. it said per-capita gross national product for japan reached the equivalent of $19,642 in 1987, compared with $18,403 in the united states
_the canadian dollar, buoyed by higher interest rates north of the border, rose to 80 u.s. cents for the first time in four years
a 72-year-old rancher who said she was forced into bankruptcy because the farmers home administration thought she was ``an old woman who should quit farming'' is suing the government lender for $3 million
beulah jorgenson, who her attorney said has operated a ranch for many years, claims in the lawsuit that fmha denied her a $300,000 emergency loan in 1986
the bowman county fmha county committee found her eligible for the loan, but it was denied by county supervisor ronald holtz, according to the lawsuit
the suit, which names holtz and the fmha as defendants, said mrs. jorgenson was forced to file under chapter 12 of the federal bankruptcy act to reorganize her debts after foreclosure proceedings began. chapter 12 is a relatively new provision of the act intended to help financially strapped farmers
holtz told mrs. jorgenson she could not pay off the loan but he ``specifically declared to other persons that he was rejecting the plaintiff's fmha application because ... the plaintiff was an old woman who should quit farming and ... and stop bothering fmha,'' according to the lawsuit
bob zimmerman, chief of fmha farm programs in north dakota, said friday the agency had not seen a copy of the lawsuit, which accuses holtz and the fmha of age and sex discrimination. the suit was filed wednesday in u.s. district court
fmha is the government's lender of last resort for farmers and ranchers
mrs. jorgenson ranches on 3,000 acres near bowman in southwestern north dakota with one hired man, said her attorney, rolf sletten of bismarck
her husband is in a nursing home and has been for many years. she has been running (the ranch) herself for many years,'' sletten said
mrs. jorgenson needed the emergency loan to pay off some higher-interest loans she owed the production credit association and the federal land bank, sletten said. ``she hadn't had any loans from the fmha,'' he said
holtz wrote mrs. jorgenson on april 4, 1986, telling her that the loan was denied because holtz believed she couldn't pay it back and all her property was already mortgaged, according to court documents
mrs. jorgenson is still ranching while her bankruptcy case is pending, sletten said friday
as winter gives way to spring on wall street, investors' worries are much different from what just about anyone imagined three months ago
increasingly, fears of an impending recession are being quelled by signs of persistent strength in the economy. the stock market, after suffering what looked like a knockout blow in october, has bounced back with an impressive show of vitality
so the pessimists have turned to worrying not about hard times, but rather too much of a good thing
consider the position of the federal reserve. in the midst of the crash last fall, it stepped up with a promise to provide as much money to the system as was necessary to keep it from suffering grave damage
now, alan greenspan, the fed's chairman, is sounding warnings about the possibility that growth at too strong a pace could revive inflationary pressures
the trade deficit, a primary focus of concern last fall, has improved to the extent that some people now interpret it as a signal of an economy heating up to potentially dangerous temperatures
the bond market has grown increasingly jumpy lately over much better-than-expected growth in employment, for fear that it might soon exert upward pressure on inflation and interest rates
all this has a familiar ring. it was the kind of mood that often set in during the great bull market of 1982-87
in the bond market memories remain fresh of the wrenching rise in interest rates, and accompanying drop in bond prices, that started right about this time a year ago
the stock market is approaching a critical juncture,'' says joseph barthel, an analyst at butcher &amp; singer inc. ``bonds must rally to ward off a correction, or worse.''
all this suits many of wall street's bulls just fine. stocks seem to be ``climbing a wall of worry,'' in the time-honored phrase used to describe bull markets
in the past week, the dow jones average of 30 industrials gained 52.39 points to 2,087.37, reaching new highs since the october debacle
the new york stock exchange composite index rose 3.20 to 152.65; the american stock exchange market value index was up 3.02 at 299.11, and the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market added 6.10 to 381.58
volume on the big board averaged 175.26 million shares a day, against 199.77 million the week before
in the view of mitchell held, chief financial economist at smith barney, harris upham &amp; co., ``the fed is likely to hold policy steady for the time being, and consequently we expect to see little movement in short-term rates for now
should the economic data continue to exceed general expectations, as we anticipate, inflation expectations are likely to rise, and short-term rates will probably rise either in reaction to or in anticipation of fed action.''
however, if inflation is planning a comeback it is disguising its intentions pretty well. the producer price index of finished goods fell 0.2 percent in february
consumers seem to have found a degree of price consciousness and budget discipline,'' said david ressler, chief economist at nomura securities international
they seem willing to increase purchases of certain items such as a car when there are significant price discounts, but to balance that added spending with more restraint on other items
such price sensitivity will make it difficult for any broadbased cost pressures to be passed on to consumers.''
digital equipment corp. said friday that sluggish sales of expensive computer systems have forced analysts to downgrade third-quarter earnings estimates for the computer industry giant
mark steinkrauss, digital's investor relations director, said the company is forecasting lower earnings for the fiscal quarter ending march 26 because of the lag
while aggregate demand is very good and consistent with the level we expected in the last couple of years, there's been a mix shift to low-end products,'' he said
after discussions with analysts, digital, based in maynard, mass., agreed to cut its quarterly earnings forecast to about $2.30 a share from $2.50 a share. the company earlier this month agreed to cut forecast to $2.50 from $2.70
digital stock fell $1.50 a share friday to $110.75 in composite new york stock exchange trading. the stock fell $5.375 on thursday
wang laboratories, prime computer and data general all have indicated recently that business is sluggish due to slumping high-end demand, confirming a trend in minicomputer sales, analysts said
things are generally somewhat slow in the minicomputer sector right now,'' said bruce watts of needham &amp; co. ``digital has been reasonably candid that its product mix has shifted to less expensive machines.''
steinkrauss said digital has been unable to meet an unexpectedly high demand for its less expensive equipment, including workstations and terminals
the unanticipated shift caught us a little bit by surprise,'' he said. ``we didn't know demand was going to be as strong for workstations and products at the low end and we didn't have the capacity to ship it all this quarter.''
digital last week unveiled its 8800 series of mainframe computers in another challenge to industry leader international business machines. but analysts said the impact of the new line won't be felt for several months
the sales of high-end equipment are going slowly,'' said jean orr of drexel burnham lambert inc. ``customers are apparently hesitant to make a commitment to the expensive equipment
we don't know for certain how long the hesitation will last,'' she added. ``my view is that it's going to be a quarter or two that we see an effect.''
watts said digital stock probably will fall some more in the short-term but that its long-range prospects remain bright
i think there's no question that dec has established themselves as the leader in the minicomputer business and is starting to take on ibm in the big computers, he said
analysts also have dropped digital's yearly earnings estimates to $10 to $10.25 a share compared with $10.50 a share earlier this month. for fiscal 1987, digital reported profits of $1.14 billion on $9.39 billion in revenues, or $8.53 a share
kaiser steel corp., operating under chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings for 13 months, said friday a joint plan of reoganization had been filed by kaiser and representatives of retirees, other unsecured creditors and the united steelworks of america
under the plan, filed in u.s. bankruptcy court in colorado on thursday, a percentage of proceeds from the sale of assets and the settlement of litigation will be distributed to creditors
in addition, some claims against the company will be converted into common stock in the reorganized concern, to be known as kaiser holdings inc
the plan provides, in part, for 30 milion common shares of the new company to be distributed to retirees, kaiser's unsecured creditors, holders of preferred stock and, at the discretion of the new board, as incentive options to management
kaiser's current common stock, which is privately held, will be canceled
the plan is endorsed by kaiser and certain of its subsidiaries as debtors; the company's official unsecured creditors committee; that committee's retiree subcommittee, and the union
upon emerging from bankruptcy proceedings, kaiser said, it intends to develop its 900-acre steel mill in fontana as an industrial park, modernize and operate its existing liquid-waste treatment facility at the fontana site and seek to create a landfill for non-hazardous solid waste at its eagle mountain iron ore mine in riverside county
although most of its holdings remain in fontana, the company's headquarters were moved to colorado springs, colo., after a leveraged buyout of several years ago
the fontana plant was built by industrialist henry j. kaiser during world war ii to provide steel to build liberty ships on the west coast
the plant was located about 50 miles inland to protect it from possible enemy attack during the war. but that location proved fatal to the operation in later years, as high transporation costs made it impossible for steel from fontana to compete with low-cost imports. 0504</first>
a delaware judge declined friday to approve a settlement of shareholder suits against resorts international inc. that would have allowed investor donald trump to proceed with his $22-per-share tender offer designed to take resorts private
instead, chancery court vice chancellor maurice hartnett put off a decision until later, following a 2{-hour hearing
the action increases pressure on trump, the new york real estate developer, to raise his offer by giving wealthy entertainer merv griffin more time to press his rival $35-per-share cash bid for resorts, the atlantic city-based operator of hotel-casinos in new jersey and the bahamas
every continuance is a good thing for us in this situation currently,'' said mark gill, a spokesman for griffin, noting that trump's $22 offer expires on monday
resorts stock rose 50 cents a share friday to $25.75
while griffin's bid offers shareholders more money, it is contingent on a number of conditions, including a decision by trump to support the deal and to terminate a five-year operating pact with resorts worth an estimated $100 million
trump, who holds 88 percent of resorts' voting power by owning most of its class b stock that carries 100 votes per share, has said he wouldn't agree to either condition. as a result, resorts' directors thursday declined to pursue griffin's proposal on grounds that it was moot
in separate developments friday, griffin, based in los angeles, said he was dropping certain other conditions relating to financing, and trump announced he had filed suit against griffin seeking more than $250 million in damages
trump's suit, filed in u.s. district court in new york, names as defendants griffin, his privately held investment concern, the griffin co., and fidelle v. scutti, who owns about 5 percent of resorts stock
scutti, who has said he is dissatisfied with trump's offer, helped convince griffin to make the competing bid
trump's suit accuses the defendants with violations of federal securities laws, fraud and tortious interference with trump's contractual relations with resorts
it claims the defendants took part in a scheme to manipulate the market price of resorts stock by making false and misleading comments about their intentions and by making a $35-per-share offer that the suit said was ``completely delusory'' because of its highly conditional nature
in a statement, griffin termed trump's suit ``totally without merit and solely for the purpose of attempting to coerce mr. griffin to withdraw his offer.''
griffin said the suit of ``of no concern'' and that he intended to filed unspecified counter-suits against trump
griffin has previously said he expected to file suit against trump and directors of resorts for breach of fiduciary duty to shareholders
the conditions griffin eliminated from his offer were requirements that financing be arranged for the merger and that financing be arranged in advance to complete resorts' giant and luxurious taj mahal, a 42-story, 1,250-room hotel-casino being built in atlantic city
postal instant press inc., the nation's largest franchiser of printing centers, said friday a management-led offer to buy the company has expired and it is negotiating to be acquired by another suitor for a higher price
the company said it received the new offer of $17.50 per share, or $68.25 million, on wednesday from an investor group that it didn't identify
that is 50 cents a share higher than what was being offered by the management group and the chicago-based leveraged-buyout concern golder, thoma &amp; cressey. the management group made its offer feb. 19
in addition, pip said the new suitor has indicated it may raise its offer after studying non-public information provided by the los angeles-based company that has about 1,000 printing centers franchised in the united states, canada and the united kingdom
last year, pip escaped a hostile bid by tarrytown, n.y.-based kane-miller corp
an investor group led by the chairman of afg industries inc. friday revised its takeover bid for afg to offer all cash instead of a combination of cash and securities. the overall value of the offered remained the same at $940 million
afg, based in irvine, is one of the largest flat-glass manufacturers in north america
under the amended offer, clarity industries corp., headed by afg chairman r.d. hubbard, is offering $33 per share in cash for afg's 28.5 million shares. previously, clarity had offered cash for 94 percent of the stock and preferred stock valued at $33 per share for the remainder
the revised offer is to expire april 1
clarity launched its takeover bid late last month. it was upstaged early this month when the new york investment firm forstmann little &amp; co. indicated it may be willing to top hubbard's offer
that sparked speculation that drove afg's stock up, but a week ago forstmann said it had decided not to make an offer after studying confidential information provided by afg
apple computer inc. is rocking the personal computer industry with a lawsuit against one of its most important allies, microsoft corp., and rival hewlett-packard co
apple is charging that microsoft, of redmond, wash., and hewlett-packard, of palo alto, are selling software that infringes on the copyright on the way information is presented and controlled on its macintosh computer
hewlett-packard on friday disputed apple's claims and said it intends to oppose the suit vigorously. microsoft withheld comment
several computer executives expressed disappointment with apple's suit
the whole industry has existed by taking what is there and improving on it,'' adam osborne, president of paperback software of berkeley. ``is that going to end? if so, it'll be a disaster for us all.''
in the suit, filed in u.s. district court in san jose on thursday, apple seeks to prevent further sale of microsoft's windows 2.03 program and hewlett-packard's new wave software programs
windows and new wave were developed for personal computers made by or compatible with those of international business machines corp., apple's chief competitor, and are aimed at making the computers easier to use
like the macintosh, they employ a mouse pointing-device, and such on-screen displays as icons, scroll bars, pull-down menus, and dialogue boxes. these features replaced more complicated instructions, and made the macintosh one of the easiest computers to use
apple's chief operating officer, delbert yocam, said the company merely is protecting its investment
the suit could affect apple rival ibm, whose audio and visual features, called the ``user interface,'' for its new line of computers is expected to resemble the macintosh's. the program, called presentation manager, is being co-developed by ibm and microsoft
industry observers credit the macintosh interface with giving the computer a competitive edge over ibm's current line. presentation manager could eliminate that advantage
in its complaint, apple alleges microsoft overstepped the bounds of a licensing agreement it made with apple several years ago. hewlett-packard's new wave, in turn, requires microsoft's windows to operate
apple has sued before to protect its products. in 1982, the company challenged franklin computer corp., which was developing a compatible version of its apple ii, and won
apple also has prevented the import of apple ii clones by asian companies through legal challenges and cooperation with u.s. customs
campeau corp. has suffered a severe setback in its battle for federated department stores inc. with a federal judge's ruling that federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense could stand
u.s. district judge leonard sand, who issued his ruling friday, at the same time delayed a decision on when campeau's $6.2 billion cash tender offer for federated should be allowed to expire
sand denied a request from r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. to force campeau's offer to remain open until march 30, but he ruled the bid must remain in effect at least until next friday
federated's management supports macy's cash and securities offer, which analysts have valued at about $6.3 billion
the poison pill was seen as the key issue before sand and the issue that could ultimately determine who would win federated. campeau contended its offer could not proceed as long as the pill remained in effect
federated's pill would allow current shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a steep discount unless the board of directors withdrew the provision. poison pills make it prohibitively expensive for companies to acquire a target company without the support of the target's management
sand disagreed with campeau's contention that federated's board of directors had breached its duty to shareholders in creating the pill in 1986, or in amending it earlier this year, prior to the toronto-based developer's bid
campeau contended the pill prevented shareholders from getting the chance to fully consider its offer, but sand said the creation of the pill was a valid defense and a reasonable business judgment by the federated board
however, while the judge denied campeau's motion for a preliminary injunction, sand left open the possibility that the developer could raise the issue again
campeau said it had no immediate comment on sand's ruling
sand, relying on a securities and exchange commission recommendation, ruled against macy in declaring that campeau's latest bid, announced march 2, was an amendment to its original proposal, and not a new offer
macy had sought the bid to be declared a new offer in hopes of forcing it to remain open for 20 business days, as required by law
extending the length of campeau's offer would put the competing bids on on a more equal footing. macy, whose offer expires april 4, feared federated shareholders would feel pressured into tendering their shares to the developer because of the earlier deadline
campeau's latest offer changed the number of shares it was seeking and the price to be paid for them
sand ruled, however, that the campeau bid must remain open while he awaited a determination from the sec on whether the developer must file more documents on its financing for the acquisition
macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy would exchange shares in the merged company, macy's-federated inc., and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares. analysts have estimated the total value of the offer at $6.3 billion
federated stock rose 50 cents a share to close at $66.25 friday on the new york stock exchange. trading ended before sand made the ruling
campeau's bid is a two-step, all-cash package that would be worth $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. it is offering $75 each for 70.5 million federated shares, and proposes to acquire the remaining stock for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger
campeau announced friday that more than 5.7 million shares had been tendered under its offer so far. macy has not announced how many shares have been tendered to it
federated owns 650 stores, including the bloomingdale's, burdine's, filene's, foley's, lazarus and rich's department store chains; ralphs supermarkets; gold circle discount stores; and main street and children's place specialty stores
macy owns nearly 100 department and specialty stores
campeau, which started in real estate development in canada, moved into the u.s. retail market at the end of 1986 by acquiring allied stores corp
the oil market has continued to gain ground despite conflicting reports on whether opec would act soon to stabilize sagging prices
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, jumped 30 cents friday to $16.58 per 42-gallon barrel
refined petroleum products also closed higher. april contracts for heating oil increased 0.83 cent to settle at 45.05 cents per gallon, while wholesale gasoline gained 0.39 cent to settle at 45.99 cents per gallon
william byers, an oil analyst with bear, stearns &amp; co., said the market started out on a strong note
but he said trading began to narrow later in the day after reports suggested a planned news conference tuesday by opec president rilwanu lukman was not called to announce price stabilization measures
oil prices had strengthend on thursday after traders learned of the lukman conference
the market has traded nervously since reports picked up last week that the organization of petroleum exporting countries might convene an emergency meeting to discuss ways to prop up sagging prices
the postal service has been doing it practically forever, but private sector companies are likely to think twice if they ever have an opportunity to bid on moving mountains of the nation's correspondence and parcels
now that a presidential commission has recommended the postal service's monopoly on delivering letters should be phased out, private companies may begin to contemplate whether they would want to compete for the business
in a controversial report presented to president reagan on friday, the presidential commission on privatization called for transferring to the private sector scores of other government programs and services, including the operation of prisons and airport control towers, in the name of efficiency
as far as the nation's mail is concerned, ``there's nothing the postal service is doing that private enterprise couldn't do equally as well or better,'' said ken sternad, a spokesman at the headquarters of united parcel service inc. in greenwich, conn
sternad said united parcel, which maintains 1,300 facilities across the country, had not made any decision about trying to get into the letter-carrying business, ``but we certainly would look at it.''
but james coleman, director of public relations at federal express corp.'s headquarters in memphis, tenn., said: ``we do not view ourselves as having any role to play in routine handling of bulk shipments.''
federal express specializes in overnight and express deliveries, a small piece of what the post office does
taking on the postal system would require a major build-up for any company. united parcel, for example, has 200,000 employees who delivered 2.4 billion packages last year. the postal service, by comparison, has almost five times as many employees and delivered more than 100 billion pieces of mail in 1987, sternad said
if the government were to privatize merely the right to deliver mail, potential bidders would be limited to companies that are already in the post office-like business, said james voytko, a first vice president at the investment firm painewebber inc. who follows the transportation industry
but other big companies in unrelated businesses also might qualify if they had a particularly extensive transportation network set up
american telephone &amp; telegraph co., for example, operates a major, nationwide fleet of trucks
they go to a lot of addresses fixing phones,'' said one industry insider who asked not to be quoted by name. ``there are a lot of companies that reach a lot of people _ the sky's the limit.''
the bidding also could widen if the government decided to sell the post office's assets, such as its trucks and properties, and transfer the work force to the new owner
in that case, anybody with money could buy it,'' voytko said, although he noted that a company with experience in mail and parcel delivery probably would feel more comfortable in the expanded business
voytko said, however, that it was uncertain whether operating a nationwide postal service would be a good business opportunity
but it is good from a public policy point of view. the private sector has proved time and time again that it can deliver services better than the government,'' he said
already the recommendations generated sharp advance opposition from public employee and postal worker unions
the national association of letter carriers said ending the postal service monopoly on first- and third-class mail delivery would destroy the nation's system of universal service. ``rural and inner-city residents would not be served ... or would receive reduced service at exorbitant postal rates,'' the union said
however, david linowes, a democrat who headed the privatization committee, said the government could require private companies to deliver mail to all areas at the same price
